WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Where are you from? If someone asks me that question, I don't have an easy answer. I can

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:12.880
[Amit Varma]: tell you where I was born and where I grew up and where I worked and so on and so forth.

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:17.120
[Amit Varma]: But I am shaped less by geography than I would have been a century or two ago. The biggest

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:21.320
[Amit Varma]: influences in my early years were the books I read and the films I saw, most of which

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:26.120
[Amit Varma]: came from the West. English is my first language. And once the internet came into my life, it

00:00:26.120 --> 00:00:30.880
[Amit Varma]: became my window to the world. And that world became my hometown. I read Alice Munro and

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:35.120
[Amit Varma]: Yoko Ogawa. I listened to Van Morrison and Joni Mitchell. I'd rather watch paint dry

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:39.960
[Amit Varma]: in a Tarkovsky film than bullets fly in a Shahrukh Khan film. I also love Indian authors

00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:44.200
[Amit Varma]: and music and films, of course, so I'm not quite a deracinated product of the remote

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:48.280
[Amit Varma]: West. Some days I have pizza, some days I have biryani and my weighing scale doesn't

00:00:48.280 --> 00:00:52.920
[Amit Varma]: like it. But while much of my surroundings in Mumbai are a comfort zone for me, out of

00:00:52.920 --> 00:00:58.440
[Amit Varma]: pure habit, I do wish sometimes that my roots were deeper. I like the idea of being a global

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:03.200
[Amit Varma]: citizen, but this globe is an abstract thing, unlike the earth beneath my feet, which is

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:08.040
[Amit Varma]: unseen to me as I walk all over it. If one is to be cosmopolitan, one should be, in a

00:01:08.040 --> 00:01:15.440
[Amit Varma]: memorable phrase used by my guest today, a rooted cosmopolitan.

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:20.640
[Unknown]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:27.640
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:31.480
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen. My guest today is Sugata Srinivasaraju. And while he's

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:35.560
[Amit Varma]: been a writer and a journalist, those terms seem inadequate to describe him. A better

00:01:35.560 --> 00:01:40.560
[Amit Varma]: term perhaps would be a man of letters, or even better, a man of culture. Born to a literary

00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:44.920
[Amit Varma]: family, Sugata wanted to be a writer from a young age, hung out with legends of Kannada

00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:49.440
[Amit Varma]: literature, found equal fluency in Kannada and English, and by engaging with the world

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:54.880
[Amit Varma]: of ideas, he made himself into what Ram Guha once called a dying breed, the bilingual intellectual.

00:01:54.880 --> 00:02:00.040
[Amit Varma]: Sugata's latest book is Furrows in a Field, a biography of H.D. Devya Gowda that is as

00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:05.560
[Amit Varma]: much the portrait of a man as of Karnataka politics itself. I went to Bangalore in February

00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:11.040
[Amit Varma]: intending to chat with Sugata about this book. I read it carefully. I took copious notes.

00:02:11.040 --> 00:02:15.160
[Amit Varma]: They were passages I almost knew by heart. And then, Sugata and I spoke for over five

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:19.720
[Amit Varma]: hours and we didn't spend even one minute of that talking about the book. His life itself

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:24.280
[Amit Varma]: was so fascinating, especially when it came to describing the milieu where he grew up,

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:28.360
[Amit Varma]: a world of letters and ideas where every neighbourhood in Bangalore seemed to be home to a different

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:32.940
[Amit Varma]: school of literature. I learnt about the rich world of Kannada literature, a vast ocean

00:02:32.940 --> 00:02:37.720
[Amit Varma]: of art that our Anglophone elites miss while staring into a tumbler of water. I learnt

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:42.080
[Amit Varma]: about his journey through Indian journalism, a field in which high ideals and petty corruption

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:46.840
[Amit Varma]: are always jostling each other. We discussed how our culture and politics are changing,

00:02:46.840 --> 00:02:51.940
[Amit Varma]: the narrow visions of both nationalism and our many sub-nationalisms. I was struck most

00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:57.360
[Amit Varma]: of all by a phrase he used to describe himself, rootedly cosmopolitan. I know few people to

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:02.360
[Amit Varma]: whom that lovely phrase can be attached. I'm not one of them. Sugata Srinivasaraju is a

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:07.080
[Amit Varma]: rooted cosmopolitan. I love this conversation and I'm sure you will as well. But before

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:12.000
[Amit Varma]: we begin, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:17.800
[Amit Varma]: On the 20th of July, 2007, a lady named Mrs. Gaware returned to her home in Dombivali to

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:22.600
[Amit Varma]: find that her daughter Snehal, who had been relaxing in her room, was missing. Snehal's

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:27.280
[Amit Varma]: slippers, her spectacles, her braces, without which she never left home, were still there.

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:31.680
[Amit Varma]: There was a hunt for the girl, a police complaint was filed and worry gave way to panic. The

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:36.160
[Amit Varma]: next day, Mrs. Gaware entered Snehal's room and noticed that a water jar that was normally

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:41.100
[Amit Varma]: in the storage under the bed was now outside. So she opened up the storage and found her

00:03:41.100 --> 00:03:46.640
[Amit Varma]: dead daughter inside, her hands tied behind her back, a towel around her mouth. This happened

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:50.720
[Amit Varma]: just a few kilometres from where I live. But I hadn't heard of this till I came across

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:56.080
[Amit Varma]: the Desi Crime Podcast, the sponsors of this episode. The Desi Crime Podcast is hosted

00:03:56.080 --> 00:04:01.400
[Amit Varma]: by Aishwarya Singh and Aryan Misra, and they talk about crimes from India, Pakistan, Nepal,

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:05.800
[Amit Varma]: any place you'd call desi. In it, they talk about crimes like the bed-box murder, Snehal

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:10.520
[Amit Varma]: Gaware's case. We learn about Hercules, a vigilante in Bangladesh who punished rapists

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:15.440
[Amit Varma]: by killing them. Who was Hercules? Why did Hercules act where the law had failed? Great

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:20.760
[Amit Varma]: stories can raise fascinating questions that keep us up at night. And the Desi Crime Podcast

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:25.960
[Amit Varma]: has plenty of those. You can find it on Apple, Spotify, Amazon Music, or wherever you listen

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:30.600
[Amit Varma]: to your podcasts. So check out the Desi Crime Podcast and remember, there's a killer on

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:42.320
[Amit Varma]: the loose in your neighbourhood.

00:04:42.320 --> 00:05:02.360
[Amit Varma]: So

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:07.160
[Amit Varma]: much better and she took me through you know many decades of it and then someone on Twitter

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:13.080
[Amit Varma]: commented that you really must talk to Swagata Srinivasa Raju about Karnataka politics at

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:18.320
[Amit Varma]: which point my ears perked up but then I thought that I have to have some baseline knowledge

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:24.040
[Amit Varma]: of a subject to begin with to be able to talk to someone about it and I am completely clueless

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:29.400
[Amit Varma]: about Karnataka politics was then and to a lesser extent now because of your wonderful

00:05:29.400 --> 00:05:33.600
[Amit Varma]: book but you know that's kind of the extent of it but I've been following your work since

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:38.720
[Amit Varma]: and the book gave me an opportunity to invite you on the show so delighted to have you so

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:43.080
[Amit Varma]: you know let's let's kind of you've got such a rich and varied career and there are many

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:47.640
[Amit Varma]: aspects of that I'd like to touch on before we get to your book but first tell me a little

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:51.800
[Amit Varma]: bit about you know where were you born where did you grow up what were those years like

00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:59.400
[Guest]: thank you Amit I was raised in Bangalore I mean I was born in Bangalore brought up in

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:03.080
[Guest]: Bangalore and my ancestors in a sense been at least two or three generations were all

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:08.400
[Guest]: in Bangalore so I never sort of got a chance to sort of go to the rural hinterland or be

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:15.920
[Guest]: part of a rural you know setting whatever so I was always an urban boy but then Bangalore

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:22.160
[Guest]: of what what it is today is not the Bangalore of the 70s when I was born so I still always

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:26.640
[Guest]: had this feeling that I was a provincial boy and it was a provincial town or it was a small

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:32.800
[Guest]: town and so this and it was a very pastoral kind of city because if you you know went

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:38.680
[Guest]: into the smaller bylanes of Bangalore you would still see people having cows milking

00:06:38.680 --> 00:06:43.760
[Guest]: their cows in the morning and it was very laid-back kind of a city there was no the

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:49.520
[Guest]: city was not you know I mean set to the space that it is set to today that is after 2000

00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:54.440
[Guest]: you saw a sudden shift and many of us don't recognize the Bangalore that we grew up in

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:59.800
[Guest]: and I think this is the constant complaint of everybody who sort of has grown up in cities

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:05.760
[Guest]: you know and has seen say 20 30 years or 40 years go by because everything is dramatically

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:11.760
[Guest]: changed drastically changed and that is my experience too about Bangalore so I was basically

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:17.400
[Guest]: born and brought up in Bangalore my mother's side came from a place called Tumkur which

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:22.800
[Guest]: is right outside Bangalore which is now connected by a six-lane highway and you can reach there

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:28.120
[Guest]: in an hour and it's almost an extension of Bangalore now and my father's side came from

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:33.120
[Guest]: a much closer place in rural Bangalore district I don't know if you're familiar with a big

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:37.720
[Guest]: banyan tree you know you see it on all the record books and because it's a real big banyan

00:07:37.720 --> 00:07:45.320
[Guest]: tree and we were my father's you know forefathers were Patels of that village and that is supposed

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:50.640
[Guest]: to have come to us as some kind of a Jagir from the Mysore Maharaja my mother's side

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:56.680
[Guest]: came I think they migrated after the fall of the Vijayanagara Empire from that area

00:07:56.680 --> 00:08:03.600
[Guest]: Balari area so they they trace their ancestry back to Anegundi kingdom so but these are

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:07.800
[Guest]: things that I've not fact-checked and these are things that I've heard and you know I

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:12.000
[Guest]: mean there is in other cultures there is this genealogical thing maps written and all that

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:17.600
[Guest]: but here you know some of the property papers mention this but then you know I've never

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:21.720
[Guest]: I mean I should say as a journalist and as a writer that I don't think I've fact-checked

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:26.400
[Guest]: any of this this is what you've heard and I'm just sharing that with you so so this

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:33.720
[Guest]: is basically my background and my father was a professor of Kannada language and literature

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:38.240
[Guest]: and he taught at the Christ College which has now become Christ University was one of

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:48.000
[Guest]: the founding faculty members of that institution and he was a huge and major influence on me

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:53.640
[Guest]: he was he went to the St. Joseph's College in Bangalore his father I mean who had come

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:58.920
[Guest]: to Bangalore from Ramohalli which is that big banyan tree thing was a police officer

00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:03.200
[Guest]: you know he was in the first batch of CBI officers those days and so they were educated

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:07.560
[Guest]: he was the first generation he was educated that was the first generation that got educated

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:12.200
[Guest]: in the family that was my grandfather and my father was you know I mean relatively better

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:17.680
[Guest]: off because of his father's education and he went to the St. Joseph's College to study

00:09:17.680 --> 00:09:26.840
[Guest]: science so he did his BSc and then got into a job in a mining company again in Karnataka

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:31.800
[Guest]: but then I think in the 70s there was this resurgence of Kannada you know activism and

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:38.080
[Guest]: pride and the burst of literary activity and all that I think he was drawn into that and

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:43.880
[Guest]: he shifted from sciences and mining and all that into literature so he came back to the

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:49.880
[Guest]: Central College in Bangalore to do his MA in Kannada literature under Stalwarts so G.P.

00:09:49.880 --> 00:09:54.520
[Guest]: Rajaratnam who is one of the big names in Kannada literature was his teacher and he

00:09:54.520 --> 00:10:01.160
[Guest]: sort of almost called himself a disciple of this man and it is very important to mention

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:06.640
[Guest]: G.P. Rajaratnam because G.P. Rajaratnam did a lot of good for Kannada not in just terms

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:11.680
[Guest]: of you know a creative literature but also he brought Buddhist literature into Kannada

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:17.120
[Guest]: Jaina literature into Kannada he himself sort of became a kind of Buddhist and wore white

00:10:17.120 --> 00:10:23.760
[Guest]: you know all times and this man put this seed into my father's head that it is not just

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:28.440
[Guest]: enough to write literature but you also have to create a literary atmosphere and a culture

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:34.040
[Guest]: so wherein younger people sort of you know come in and thrive and do good things so culture

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:39.600
[Guest]: it's about nurturing that environment was an idea that came from G.P. Rajaratnam to

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:44.840
[Guest]: my father and G.P. Rajaratnam got it from another stalwart or a contemporary of his

00:10:44.840 --> 00:10:51.000
[Guest]: called A. R. Krishna Shastri so they used to run this Karnataka Sangha in Central College

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:57.100
[Guest]: and they actually nurtured really great writers like P. Lankesh was I'm just giving you one

00:10:57.100 --> 00:11:03.480
[Guest]: instance Nisar Ahmed who passed away recently was another very big name so they that was

00:11:03.480 --> 00:11:09.360
[Guest]: a kind of you know cradle for young writers and they they sort of picked their writing

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:14.080
[Guest]: looked at it you know edited it and put it into an anthology published it and sort of

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:19.920
[Guest]: made them feel that they were writers and then nurtured a kind of environment in Kannada

00:11:19.920 --> 00:11:24.080
[Guest]: which was a selfless thankless kind of a thing because these writers themselves were not

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:29.240
[Guest]: very rich you know they were themselves first-generation literates perhaps and they were just doing

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:34.600
[Guest]: this out of their own you know I mean volition and you know I mean certain kind of commitment

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:40.400
[Guest]: and you know a different kind of philosophy totally so my father was in that tradition

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:45.560
[Guest]: so my father thought that because he had received so much from this tradition he also has to

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:51.360
[Guest]: continue that and besides being a poet and a playwright in Kannada he also started a

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:57.600
[Guest]: small publishing house in Christ College which was a Christian institution as the name goes

00:11:57.600 --> 00:12:03.080
[Guest]: but run by I mean monks who came from Kerala you know it was a kind of congregation which

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:07.840
[Guest]: was which was that you know because that distinction has to be made because there are monks also

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:12.400
[Guest]: from Mangalore you know in the St. Joseph's College is run by mostly fathers who come

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:19.640
[Guest]: from Mangalore so this was a Malayalam Malayali kind of environment a Christ College and so

00:12:19.640 --> 00:12:25.520
[Guest]: he starts the Kannada Sangha there and has the first book that he brings out is an anthology

00:12:25.520 --> 00:12:32.100
[Guest]: of poems on Christ in Kannada and that becomes a controversy because you know I mean I forget

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:38.040
[Guest]: exactly why it became a controversy but he handles that controversy and what he did was

00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:44.080
[Guest]: that he kept a small you know portion of his salary aside to bring out these publications

00:12:44.080 --> 00:12:49.600
[Guest]: so my mother used to always tell us that your father is sort of you know I mean is more

00:12:49.600 --> 00:12:54.720
[Guest]: worried about what book to bring out next rather than you know worry about your education

00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:58.920
[Guest]: you know and she was teasingly you know I mean she was a willing collaborator in his

00:12:58.920 --> 00:13:05.560
[Guest]: enterprise but then but this was the kind of so he sort of did that so today in Kannada

00:13:05.560 --> 00:13:13.640
[Guest]: a lot of big writers including H.S. Shivaprakash or K.V. Narayan or a lot of people were products

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:19.480
[Guest]: of his sort of you know I mean a nurturing you know enterprise literally and a lot of

00:13:19.480 --> 00:13:23.600
[Guest]: I also met my wife through one of his you know he brought on an anthology and my wife

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:30.120
[Guest]: had published a poem so she used to come to see him my later wife you know so that's how

00:13:30.120 --> 00:13:37.200
[Guest]: I sort of met her so I keep telling my you know I mean friends and family that my father's

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:43.120
[Guest]: literature you know I mean indulgence and all that did not after all go waste because

00:13:43.120 --> 00:13:47.720
[Guest]: you know I mean I sort of found a life partner and it has done well and it has sort of given

00:13:47.720 --> 00:13:52.800
[Guest]: us so much of goodwill and there are so many writers you know today I am I mean I may have

00:13:52.800 --> 00:13:58.560
[Guest]: worked in publications in Karnataka I mean nationally internationally and all of that

00:13:58.560 --> 00:14:02.320
[Guest]: but in Karnataka I'm always known as my father's son so I mean that's another thing which I

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:08.200
[Guest]: always I mean sometimes it swell with pride that it is that way but sometimes I feel it

00:14:08.200 --> 00:14:16.600
[Guest]: or what more should I do to sort of be recognized as you know I mean on my own no terms so that

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:21.760
[Guest]: is essentially the kind of environment that I grew up in and my father was a was not a

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:27.040
[Guest]: person again this thing has to be told in the environment that we are in today that

00:14:27.040 --> 00:14:32.600
[Guest]: he was not a chauvinist he was not a no one did not think of literature and Kannada and

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:39.800
[Guest]: Karnataka in a in very narrow terms so he was he was rootedly cosmopolitan as a phrase

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:44.760
[Guest]: that I later came to use in my first book so he's rootedly cosmopolitan the sense his

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:51.440
[Guest]: assignments to be summer assignments to me Amit was asking me to translate say he used

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:56.000
[Guest]: to leave the house in the morning so he would say by the time I come back this is a short

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:01.360
[Guest]: poem or a short story and you should have translated it by evening so he put me on this

00:15:01.360 --> 00:15:07.640
[Guest]: bilingual swing you know right very very early so I mean my I think I started translating

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:12.520
[Guest]: when I was a three-year in my third class or fourth class and so there used to he used

00:15:12.520 --> 00:15:17.520
[Guest]: to subscribe to a lot of magazines you know including Encounter used to come home Quest

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:23.320
[Guest]: used to come only later did I realize that Quest was a CIA operation right then London

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:28.120
[Guest]: Calling the BBC magazine used to come home then we used to get Soviet literature which

00:15:28.120 --> 00:15:33.520
[Guest]: is again you know I mean from the Soviet Union those days used to subsidize all this then

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:39.080
[Guest]: Chinese literature used to come home you know printed on lovely glossy paper with lovely

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:45.680
[Guest]: paintings and so this was there and then we also sort of he used to you know he had this

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:53.080
[Guest]: habit of taking a loan from say the State Bank of Mysore or Canara Bank to buy encyclopedias

00:15:53.080 --> 00:15:57.760
[Guest]: or volumes which we could not just buy it one stroke and I mean it was very expensive

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:03.880
[Guest]: so so my so the encyclopedia that I have at home you know the American ones or the he

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:10.360
[Guest]: gifted me a six set tell me why series and that was expensive those days and I don't

00:16:10.360 --> 00:16:15.760
[Guest]: think a teacher's salary could afford that kind of indulgence so otherwise you know there

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:20.440
[Guest]: was always premium Mr. Shanbhag and they were great friends and he paid his bills only once

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:25.360
[Guest]: a month at the end of the month so you know and that was the kind of and houses fully

00:16:25.360 --> 00:16:32.440
[Guest]: stacked with books and so he introduced us to not just Kannada literature trying to tell

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:38.680
[Guest]: us that you should read your K.S. Narsimha Swami or your K.V. Puttappa or P.T. Narsimhachar

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:44.200
[Guest]: or say Lankesh, Lankesh was a huge huge influence on me later after he started his tabloid I

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:48.800
[Guest]: mean I mean I would call it a compact newspaper I wouldn't call it a tabloid it became a tabloid

00:16:48.800 --> 00:16:57.720
[Guest]: later for various reasons but then so so so he would ask me to read you know look at Russian

00:16:57.720 --> 00:17:01.520
[Guest]: literature especially and European literature you know I don't think I would have ever read

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:09.120
[Guest]: Stendhal or Balzac or Victor Hugo you know Baudelaire all of these people were being just you know

00:17:09.120 --> 00:17:15.920
[Guest]: they were names and then they became reality in my imagination and in my whatever so so

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:20.240
[Guest]: he sort of pushed me to look at them and he just did not ask me to read them then he just

00:17:20.240 --> 00:17:24.800
[Guest]: gave me passages to translate so they so they became part of me in a very different way

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:28.840
[Guest]: it is not not just about reading them and you know I mean making them part of you but

00:17:28.840 --> 00:17:34.840
[Guest]: also of your consciousness but also sort of making them a part of you in a entirely different

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:39.480
[Guest]: way where those phrases and those so you had to actually dabble in two languages wondering

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:44.680
[Guest]: what this is I mean I was just thrown a challenge once you know I mean there is a lovely poem

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:49.240
[Guest]: of K.S. Narsimha Swami so I used to tell my father why are you asking me to translate

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:54.120
[Guest]: only into Kannada I'll try and translate into English so why why is it why is it that I

00:17:54.120 --> 00:17:59.600
[Guest]: should not attempt the other way around so he said yeah you're you're welcome try and

00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:05.280
[Guest]: do it so I just picked a poem of K.S. Narsimha Swami to translate and in which there is a

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:13.040
[Guest]: very idiomatic expression which says which is she's this fellow is newly married he's

00:18:13.040 --> 00:18:18.400
[Guest]: come to his father-in-law's house and realizes the wife is actually not she's having periods

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:23.760
[Guest]: and they can't sort of you know I mean there is this whole cultural thing about not being

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:28.920
[Guest]: together when you're having your period so so he comes there and then this line is there

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:32.840
[Guest]: it is very subtly communicated in the poem so now how do you bring it into English was

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:37.480
[Guest]: the challenge to a boy who's still in his early teens who does not understand the idea

00:18:37.480 --> 00:18:43.800
[Guest]: and then so so my father's friend who was also a great literary critic in Kannada he

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:48.800
[Guest]: came in the evening and then he said okay so apparently you're trying to translate Narsimha

00:18:48.800 --> 00:18:52.800
[Guest]: Swami let me have a look at it and then he said how how will you go how will you translate

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:57.680
[Guest]: this line so then I said you know I I just said she's not inside or something like that

00:18:57.680 --> 00:19:04.320
[Guest]: you know Padumalu Olagilla Paduma is not inside is the literal translation of it so then he

00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:08.880
[Guest]: he just had a good laugh and then I don't think you know they tried to explain it to

00:19:08.880 --> 00:19:14.520
[Guest]: me but I realized it much later that you know I mean this is culturally that that's when

00:19:14.520 --> 00:19:19.880
[Guest]: I realized that there's so much culture idiomatic which you cannot translate there's so much

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:25.840
[Guest]: that this culture sort of holds together which another language finds it extremely difficult

00:19:25.840 --> 00:19:33.760
[Guest]: to capture or the registers of another language or idioms or expressions or phraseology of

00:19:33.760 --> 00:19:38.760
[Guest]: the other language cannot capture so then that gave me an idea that this is unique this

00:19:38.760 --> 00:19:42.480
[Guest]: world is unique and there is another world there so I am trying to be an ambassador between

00:19:42.480 --> 00:19:48.640
[Guest]: these two worlds so I always sort of had this idea that I was an ambassador between two

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:53.520
[Guest]: worlds or and and I wish that it became more than two worlds and therefore I went and learned

00:19:53.520 --> 00:19:58.560
[Guest]: a bit of French because Lankesh translated Baudelaire into Kannada called and it was

00:19:58.560 --> 00:20:03.640
[Guest]: called Papa the Hoogalu so when I read it I was so thrilled you know I mean so I said

00:20:03.640 --> 00:20:09.440
[Guest]: okay I should go and read these poems and they're original so I went to learn French

00:20:09.440 --> 00:20:13.720
[Guest]: at the Allianz Francais but then you know I mean the French that you learn there was

00:20:13.720 --> 00:20:18.720
[Guest]: so inadequate you just you know got a bit of an idea of what it was what the language

00:20:18.720 --> 00:20:23.000
[Guest]: is all about like but then I never got to read it and the original but then at least

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:28.160
[Guest]: there was that kind of trigger you know I mean to go and seek it out and the original

00:20:28.160 --> 00:20:33.960
[Guest]: but when I even as I sort of recount all this Amit and I you made me sort of look look back

00:20:33.960 --> 00:20:38.760
[Guest]: on all these and talk about this which I don't think I would have ever sort of pulled out

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:43.720
[Guest]: but I was a student of science I was not a student of literature you know I mean when

00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:49.560
[Guest]: I joined when I finished my 10th class and that's another story as to why I said I mean

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:54.400
[Guest]: I wanted to be a cricketer like every other Bangalorean I wanted to be a cricketer so

00:20:54.400 --> 00:21:02.240
[Guest]: I went to the St. Joseph's Indian High School which was started in I think 1904 as an alternative

00:21:02.240 --> 00:21:05.840
[Guest]: to the European St. Joseph's European High School which is a which is where the elites

00:21:05.840 --> 00:21:10.640
[Guest]: went and this was for the common people so I went to the St. Joseph's Indian High School

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:15.920
[Guest]: and there there was a great sporting culture so I wanted to play cricket too so I then

00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:22.120
[Guest]: we had Salus Nazareth who played Ranji Trophy for Mysore as one of our coaches and then

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:26.600
[Guest]: I thought I should get into the school team and I wasn't I wanted to play the BT Ramayana

00:21:26.600 --> 00:21:30.800
[Guest]: tournament which was like playing the World Cup those days you know I mean so I never

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:35.760
[Guest]: succeeded in getting into the team but I was always in the B team there was an A team and

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:39.840
[Guest]: a B team I think the school people understood that there are lots of kids who have to be

00:21:39.840 --> 00:21:45.400
[Guest]: accommodated so they created a B team so you always waited in the wings you know to take

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:50.360
[Guest]: the place of a person who's injured or you know I mean who's sort of out or whatever

00:21:50.360 --> 00:21:56.040
[Guest]: so you carry drinks to the field and come out and so that cricketing thing was very

00:21:56.040 --> 00:22:01.400
[Guest]: very important because hockey was another thing in our school Ashish Balar was our contemporary

00:22:01.400 --> 00:22:08.680
[Guest]: and he was he later went on to play for India and then Rojo Bini and Syed Mustafa Hussain

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:16.000
[Guest]: Kirmani were the alumnus of this school and 1983 the Prudential Cup thing was a big moment

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:21.440
[Guest]: because they had won the cup and I think Bini had taken 18 wickets or something like that

00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:26.280
[Guest]: if I remember right and Kirmani was a big hero so they were invited to the school and

00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:31.360
[Guest]: I was given the opportunity to speak at the assembly so and invite them and I was some

00:22:31.360 --> 00:22:35.080
[Guest]: kind of a school leader you know I mean there were different houses and I was the captain

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:43.000
[Guest]: of the Nehru house so I was expected to invite them on to this whole thing and then I did

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:48.600
[Guest]: that and that again rubbed off on me and then so I was always again shuttling between cricket

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:53.440
[Guest]: and hockey and I thought I should be a hockey star when the school won a tournament in hockey

00:22:53.440 --> 00:22:58.160
[Guest]: then I thought no no no hockey is my calling then then you saw cricket and the paraphernalia

00:22:58.160 --> 00:23:02.920
[Guest]: that you know pads and you know you actually went to cricket because you like the gloves

00:23:02.920 --> 00:23:08.280
[Guest]: or you like the pads you like the bat and you like the name Schlesinger written on it

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:12.680
[Guest]: or whatever and then of course television was reiterating that ambition and you were

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:17.120
[Guest]: seeing all this and then you had these stars who were coming and watching you play in the

00:23:17.120 --> 00:23:21.400
[Guest]: morning you know I mean Bini used to be there in the grounds or Kirmani would come occasionally

00:23:21.400 --> 00:23:26.880
[Guest]: and then and I had a classmate called Krishna Prasad who went on to play I think the under

00:23:26.880 --> 00:23:31.200
[Guest]: 15 for India or something he went to England those days and I don't know what has happened

00:23:31.200 --> 00:23:35.000
[Guest]: to him but then he was there and Rahul Dravid was playing for the St. Joseph's he was my

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:41.640
[Guest]: contemporary again so so they sent a batch of students for these selections to the KSE

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:47.160
[Guest]: the Chinnaswamy stadium and I was not one of them but then I thought this is very unfair

00:23:47.160 --> 00:23:51.040
[Guest]: on the school's part I was a wicket keeper and an opening bat so I thought I should just

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:57.760
[Guest]: go and try my luck and there was Ian James I mean Anglo-Indian boy called Ian James I

00:23:57.760 --> 00:24:03.360
[Guest]: don't know what's again happened to him I'm not followed he used to open the bowling thing

00:24:03.360 --> 00:24:08.000
[Guest]: and they were all there they were sent for the selections and some of us who wanted to

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:12.320
[Guest]: very badly be there were not there so I think a three or four of us you know decided that

00:24:12.320 --> 00:24:17.680
[Guest]: let's just go and take a chance we'll just land up there and just also bowl or bat or

00:24:17.680 --> 00:24:23.400
[Guest]: you know keep wickets so I went there and I still remember Dravid coming and playing

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:27.760
[Guest]: and then Dravid keeping the wickets and AV Jai Prakash who later sort of you know gave

00:24:27.760 --> 00:24:34.280
[Guest]: this 10 out of 10 to Anil Kumble was the selector so of course we didn't get selected and then

00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:40.480
[Guest]: I then my I think my father was noticing all this and he said see you don't have to always

00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:46.360
[Guest]: be a player you can also you can enjoy the game like I do you can sort of you know mean

00:24:46.360 --> 00:24:50.240
[Guest]: enjoy it and you focus on your studies I think that's more important so that's when I sort

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:55.320
[Guest]: of turned my back to cricket and got involved in studies and so I got into science which

00:24:55.320 --> 00:25:00.280
[Guest]: was actually a kind of natural thing to happen because there are two reasons for that my

00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:05.640
[Guest]: mother's side they had an engineering college and they were pretty wealthy my father's side

00:25:05.640 --> 00:25:10.720
[Guest]: was more into education because my grandmother herself was English educated that's my father's

00:25:10.720 --> 00:25:19.120
[Guest]: mother she was a fantastic chess player and she used to read novels in Kannada and English

00:25:19.120 --> 00:25:24.520
[Guest]: and for me the sight of my grandmother still today is not about she being in the kitchen

00:25:24.520 --> 00:25:29.600
[Guest]: or making pickles or anything like that or making papadums or whatever which is the usual

00:25:29.600 --> 00:25:36.160
[Guest]: thing but she playing chess with my father so this lady was used to consume novels in

00:25:36.160 --> 00:25:40.800
[Guest]: Kannada like nobody's business and I think that she also pushed my mother to do a bit

00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:48.160
[Guest]: of that so that reading of the two women in the family was very very crucial and all my

00:25:48.160 --> 00:25:53.560
[Guest]: aunts we were a joint family living in Maleswaram a locality that was created the turn of the

00:25:53.560 --> 00:25:59.960
[Guest]: century because of plague and people had a new locality had to be created and so there

00:25:59.960 --> 00:26:03.480
[Guest]: my aunts were there they were all into music you know they were all performing artists

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:07.680
[Guest]: so there was a lot of music happening bhajan happening and my grandfather in the evenings

00:26:07.680 --> 00:26:13.560
[Guest]: used to recite from Jaimini Bharata which is a 16th 17th century you know Mahabharata

00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:18.360
[Guest]: written in Kannada then Kumar Vyasa Bharata tell us stories about it and these two women

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:23.080
[Guest]: used to go to the circulating library bring all the pulp fiction read and you know I mean

00:26:23.080 --> 00:26:29.600
[Guest]: cry and keep you know I mean sobbing over you know some passage in the thing or the

00:26:29.600 --> 00:26:33.960
[Guest]: thing about a character you know the death of a character or whatever and we used to

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:40.080
[Guest]: wonder what all this was and but it had an effect on you and so this one side it was

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:44.920
[Guest]: the mainstream thing coming from your father who's actually putting you into it and then

00:26:44.920 --> 00:26:49.040
[Guest]: then you're seeing your grandmother and your mother doing this without you know in doing

00:26:49.040 --> 00:26:53.440
[Guest]: it in a completely different way and then there is your patriarchal grandfather who's

00:26:53.440 --> 00:26:58.080
[Guest]: finished his evening chores and then sitting and reading it like in the traditional times

00:26:58.080 --> 00:27:03.600
[Guest]: you know reciting from it so this was the kind of environment that I had at home and

00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:08.400
[Guest]: then you were you're seeing Western magazines come home you're seeing books you're seeing

00:27:08.400 --> 00:27:15.840
[Guest]: your aunts perform Carnatic classical music and and so so this is the kind of environment

00:27:15.840 --> 00:27:21.600
[Guest]: and by I went into science because you know I mean I think the primary thing was also

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:25.040
[Guest]: because there was an engineering college that my grandfather maternal grandfather ran with

00:27:25.040 --> 00:27:30.680
[Guest]: his couple of our I mean a few of our other relatives and so there was a seat that was

00:27:30.680 --> 00:27:36.040
[Guest]: guaranteed and there was also this long-term thing that I should probably become an administrator

00:27:36.040 --> 00:27:41.640
[Guest]: of that thing because then they were all first-generation entrepreneurs who had made the money and they

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:46.880
[Guest]: were into construction business building dams and bridges and roads and highways all that

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:50.680
[Guest]: so they had made money and they were all very close to the Ram Krishna Hegde regime and

00:27:50.680 --> 00:27:55.440
[Guest]: they had got a license to run this college and so there was that kind of it was I think

00:27:55.440 --> 00:28:01.520
[Guest]: intellect it was mapped in the minds of my my mother especially that I should sort of

00:28:01.520 --> 00:28:05.640
[Guest]: probably do that so I got into science and getting into science was not difficult because

00:28:05.640 --> 00:28:12.200
[Guest]: I had decent scores in my SSLC but then once I got into my PCMB course it's physics chemistry

00:28:12.200 --> 00:28:19.400
[Guest]: mathematics and biology at the National College which is again a great institution I was there

00:28:19.400 --> 00:28:25.440
[Guest]: almost ambushed by a very good English teacher called Mr. Badrinath so he used to he used

00:28:25.440 --> 00:28:31.400
[Guest]: to teach English extremely well he made it very very interesting for for us so there

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:35.800
[Guest]: was an environment at home which already sort of you know I mean put you into that kind

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:40.640
[Guest]: of you know I mean gave you that orientation but here was a man and for the first time

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:45.120
[Guest]: it was an external influence and of course there were other intellectuals coming home

00:28:45.120 --> 00:28:50.640
[Guest]: you know D.R. Nagraj all the big names they were all juniors in age to my father so they

00:28:50.640 --> 00:28:55.400
[Guest]: all used to come home you know stay for long periods have food so that was all there but

00:28:55.400 --> 00:29:01.640
[Guest]: this man had a great influence on me and he I think is now a professor somewhere in Canada

00:29:01.640 --> 00:29:05.400
[Guest]: I'm not I'm not in touch with him and he did his PhD in sociology he was a very young man

00:29:05.400 --> 00:29:10.480
[Guest]: he had himself just finished his MA and was teaching younger people so there at that point

00:29:10.480 --> 00:29:14.760
[Guest]: I started thinking whether I whether it was engineering that I really wanted to or medicine

00:29:14.760 --> 00:29:22.560
[Guest]: that I really want to do so I quietly started writing poetry and bad poetry in English and

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:26.960
[Guest]: reasonably okay poetry in Kannada that's when that's that's my assessment because at least

00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:30.680
[Guest]: the Kannada poems got published here and there so the English ones never saw the light of

00:29:30.680 --> 00:29:35.760
[Guest]: the day and I still keep that diary of English poems that I wrote which I feel very embarrassed

00:29:35.760 --> 00:29:40.320
[Guest]: looking at now so you all you pick the biggest words in the dictionary and try to play with

00:29:40.320 --> 00:29:45.360
[Guest]: it you know the usual things that all of us do when we are starting this whole exercise

00:29:45.360 --> 00:29:52.960
[Guest]: so so this Bhadrinath was a kind of influence who sort of shifted my focus away from he

00:29:52.960 --> 00:29:56.520
[Guest]: was also an engineering student by the way I had given up this if I remember all this

00:29:56.520 --> 00:30:01.560
[Guest]: correctly and he had given up his sciences and had come into humanities and was doing

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:08.120
[Guest]: a great job so and he wore a dhoti and a white dhoti and a white kurta and came to class

00:30:08.120 --> 00:30:12.840
[Guest]: to teach so there was some some spiritual element in my head which was associated with

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:18.040
[Guest]: a simplicity and all that and I never went to ask why he wore as a young man now I mean

00:30:18.040 --> 00:30:21.880
[Guest]: a couple of pictures that I see now he's wearing a suit and all that but those days I think

00:30:21.880 --> 00:30:26.400
[Guest]: it was some strange idealism that was there there was already another teacher called Professor

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:30.560
[Guest]: G Ramakrishna who had studied in England was a professor of English professor of Sanskrit

00:30:30.560 --> 00:30:35.160
[Guest]: professor of Kannada and I think it had expertise in all the three languages and I'm still in

00:30:35.160 --> 00:30:40.120
[Guest]: touch with him is a great man and he wore this Gandhian attire I mean he was also at

00:30:40.120 --> 00:30:45.400
[Guest]: the National College but at another branch of the National College so so he was his student

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:50.760
[Guest]: and I finally became Dr. G Ramakrishna student also when I went to the National College Basundi

00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:58.600
[Guest]: to do my BA in English literature sociology and economics so after my pre-university I

00:30:58.600 --> 00:31:02.440
[Guest]: got into an engineering college but I went and told my father that I think I want to

00:31:02.440 --> 00:31:08.920
[Guest]: do literature like you so I thought there would be resistance but you know the first

00:31:08.920 --> 00:31:13.400
[Guest]: thing my father said was I'm very happy that you have made this decision but don't tell

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:18.800
[Guest]: your mother the way you told me I will convince her but you know you you sort of do what you

00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:22.800
[Guest]: want to do so I think I think that's a very very rare thing for the father he was very

00:31:22.800 --> 00:31:27.200
[Guest]: happy that I wanted to do English literature and my father was very good with his Kannada

00:31:27.200 --> 00:31:31.240
[Guest]: and all that but his I don't think he ever dabbled in writing in English or speaking

00:31:31.240 --> 00:31:36.160
[Guest]: in English you know I mean it was he was his Kannada only kind of a thing but with a very

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:42.000
[Guest]: good reading of English classics and English literature and European literature and all

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:48.160
[Guest]: that so he was I think he was quite a quite a liberal father and I mean hugely liberal

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:52.680
[Guest]: father who said don't worry about your mother I will tell her but once my mother came to

00:31:52.680 --> 00:31:58.120
[Guest]: know of it I think she told her father and her father sort of ridiculed my decision and

00:31:58.120 --> 00:32:03.760
[Guest]: then my grandfather here he is he influenced my paternal grandfather and he was also very

00:32:03.760 --> 00:32:08.880
[Guest]: upset and I think they were all they did not speak to me properly until I finished my degree

00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:16.160
[Guest]: you know BA in sociology English and economics so but then of course you know they all reconciled

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:20.760
[Guest]: because they saw me sort of going abroad and doing things well and so they all came back

00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:25.240
[Guest]: later but then nobody sort of made a good prognosis of my thing you know not that I

00:32:25.240 --> 00:32:30.480
[Guest]: was going to make a lot of money or get a Nobel Prize or something like that but then

00:32:30.480 --> 00:32:34.360
[Guest]: you know I mean they did not give me a chance but my father gave me a chance he said this

00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:40.040
[Guest]: is fine it's great you do what you want to do but he said whatever you do I want you

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:45.680
[Guest]: to be the best now it's like telling fathers telling their sons that even if you're a shoeshine

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:51.160
[Guest]: boy be the best I don't think they would have literally meant it but then you know that

00:32:51.160 --> 00:32:56.840
[Guest]: was the kind of encouragement and then he then I started accompanying him to seminars

00:32:56.840 --> 00:33:02.280
[Guest]: where he was speaking or his you know I mean I used to start started looking at his editing

00:33:02.280 --> 00:33:08.400
[Guest]: process very closely his table used to be stacked up with manuscripts of young writers

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:12.400
[Guest]: you know used to get up at 4 in the morning and you know I mean I mean I've written about

00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:17.440
[Guest]: it somewhere and I think the introduction to my translation of his plays he wrote mind

00:33:17.440 --> 00:33:22.400
[Guest]: plays during the emergency so so that is the only mind plays that exist in Canada even

00:33:22.400 --> 00:33:27.240
[Guest]: to this day so I translated it much later around I think 2004 for which I got the science

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:32.920
[Guest]: academy prize also so I think in the introduction of that I speak about how I saw my father

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:38.400
[Guest]: you know waking up and sitting at the table and he looking at his manuscript and there's

00:33:38.400 --> 00:33:44.880
[Guest]: a serenity a picture of serenity which I portray so so this was happening and at the same time

00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:51.200
[Guest]: when I was doing my BA my mother you know she was a homemaker and I think she had started

00:33:51.200 --> 00:33:57.880
[Guest]: accessing a different set of novels which were in translation and this is fascinating

00:33:57.880 --> 00:34:02.240
[Guest]: because again translation comes back into my life in a different way and this time my

00:34:02.240 --> 00:34:07.000
[Guest]: grandmother is out of the picture because she is passed on and we have moved to another

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:11.680
[Guest]: house because my father needed to be closer to his institution college to he couldn't

00:34:11.680 --> 00:34:17.720
[Guest]: travel long distances because he had become diabetic and we wanted to cut his travel time

00:34:17.720 --> 00:34:23.040
[Guest]: in the morning so we were in a separate setting now where it was not a joint family it was

00:34:23.040 --> 00:34:29.520
[Guest]: a nuclear family and my mother had started accessing translations of Bengali novels into

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:36.240
[Guest]: Canada which was published by Kavyalaya in Mysore and this was the entire Tagore this

00:34:36.240 --> 00:34:42.800
[Guest]: was all of Bimal Mitra then this was you know I mean Bhatir Panchali into Kannada and all

00:34:42.800 --> 00:34:49.360
[Guest]: of it was translated by a great soul called Aho Balashankara he had translated 4,000-5,000

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:55.200
[Guest]: pages of literature into Kannada from the Bengali originally had learned Bengali and

00:34:55.200 --> 00:35:00.800
[Guest]: yet translated them into Kannada and he was with the free press journal and then of course

00:35:00.800 --> 00:35:05.680
[Guest]: he also learned Malayalam and translated Nambudripad's autobiography into Kannada there's a great

00:35:05.680 --> 00:35:10.800
[Guest]: man but you know in those days when she was reading this and telling me you know summaries

00:35:10.800 --> 00:35:17.080
[Guest]: of what is happening in those mega novels written in the 19th century Bengal and you

00:35:17.080 --> 00:35:21.760
[Guest]: know there was also this affinity to Sharada and Ramakrishna Paramahamsa and all that in

00:35:21.760 --> 00:35:28.080
[Guest]: the house anyway Bengal nationalism and Bengal Bengali culture was the elite culture of the

00:35:28.080 --> 00:35:33.160
[Guest]: time so it had an influence on all literate I mean all families middle class families

00:35:33.160 --> 00:35:40.440
[Guest]: and so they came through Sharada I mean Sharada or through Ramakrishna Paramahamsa or through

00:35:40.440 --> 00:35:46.680
[Guest]: Vivekananda into all our households and there was a big you know photograph in my grandfather's

00:35:46.680 --> 00:35:51.920
[Guest]: you know I mean it was a pretty huge thing frame of Vivekananda the Hindu monk of India

00:35:51.920 --> 00:35:57.200
[Guest]: you know standing like this with a nice coat and so it had come into our house like that

00:35:57.200 --> 00:36:03.040
[Guest]: and so Bengali was an idea that sort of some of got into the culture and there was this

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:09.800
[Guest]: translations now so the so she was reading accessing all the classics and translation

00:36:09.800 --> 00:36:14.520
[Guest]: and I don't mean she was not interpreting it like my father was a literary literature

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:19.440
[Guest]: man trying to do that but she would tell me stories you know I mean tell me see this is

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:26.240
[Guest]: happening and so this fellow is going to die oh this is I think he has wasted some 25 pages

00:36:26.240 --> 00:36:29.440
[Guest]: writing on this why should he do that he can come straight to this story so there was a

00:36:29.440 --> 00:36:33.920
[Guest]: very different kind of kitchen you know she's cooking and she would tell me these stories

00:36:33.920 --> 00:36:38.120
[Guest]: and I got interested and I started reading for me it was not Tagore it was not Bimal

00:36:38.120 --> 00:36:44.280
[Guest]: Mitra it was not Bankim Chandra it was Ahobal Shankara I was reading the so powerful translation

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:49.440
[Guest]: can sort of come to you in such a powerful thing I only much later realized this Ahobal

00:36:49.440 --> 00:36:57.880
[Guest]: Shankara was none other than the maternal uncle of Akumal Ramchandra who discovered

00:36:57.880 --> 00:37:03.280
[Guest]: Harald Szepinski the abstract expressionist and got a 32 page profile in the New York

00:37:03.280 --> 00:37:10.440
[Guest]: at those times you know in the 80s so this is there was a Telugu Brahmin family I mean

00:37:10.440 --> 00:37:17.640
[Guest]: so this man was had translated all this so translation started coming into me in a completely

00:37:17.640 --> 00:37:24.880
[Guest]: different way again so that again made my reading and my looking at the world and the

00:37:24.880 --> 00:37:29.720
[Guest]: worldview that I had to know this whole idea of the world you started coming in you know

00:37:29.720 --> 00:37:32.920
[Guest]: you need to have a worldview because you know you had started I had started reading Lankesh

00:37:32.920 --> 00:37:39.040
[Guest]: by then and Lankesh I tell you all of European politics today there's so much happening in

00:37:39.040 --> 00:37:44.040
[Guest]: Russia and Ukraine and all that but those days you did not have access to the internet

00:37:44.040 --> 00:37:48.280
[Guest]: there was no internet in the first place you could not have got subscribed to an economist

00:37:48.280 --> 00:37:52.760
[Guest]: or you could not have subscribed to a Mother Jones or something else or New York Times

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:57.720
[Guest]: so all that you got to know about the about international events or personalities came

00:37:57.720 --> 00:38:03.680
[Guest]: to you through some very enlightened writers in Canada like P. Lankesh there was another

00:38:03.680 --> 00:38:10.080
[Guest]: one called Sita Ramayya VC we used to call her V. Sita Ramayya he used to subscribe to

00:38:10.080 --> 00:38:13.840
[Guest]: the Times Literary Supplement those days he wrote on economics and all that but then he

00:38:13.840 --> 00:38:18.840
[Guest]: was of an older generation much older generation to Lankesh and Lankesh used to tell us about

00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:23.480
[Guest]: what's happening with Mitterrand what's happening in Germany what's happening in America and

00:38:23.480 --> 00:38:27.480
[Guest]: used to write as if he is there and talking to all those personalities used to he had

00:38:27.480 --> 00:38:33.160
[Guest]: brilliant prose and when he when when Gowri passed away and I was interviewed on Gowri

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:39.440
[Guest]: I said see don't get me wrong Gowri was not the great journalist or great writer it was

00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:44.160
[Guest]: her father and her father always came across to me as a French modernist because he used

00:38:44.160 --> 00:38:49.040
[Guest]: to write so much on European culture and he had made Steffi Graf a household name and

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:55.040
[Guest]: he used to call his dog Steffi right so you know you he sort of presented material to

00:38:55.040 --> 00:39:00.280
[Guest]: you in a very very fascinating fashion and that's when I thought that you have to write

00:39:00.280 --> 00:39:04.760
[Guest]: you have to have a worldview you have to be rooted but at the same time you have to present

00:39:04.760 --> 00:39:08.520
[Guest]: the material before you in a very interesting fashion you shouldn't you know write with

00:39:08.520 --> 00:39:14.480
[Guest]: 2,000 footnotes and I mean 100 pages of whatever you know I mean which doesn't sort of communicate

00:39:14.480 --> 00:39:20.520
[Guest]: what you have to make it interesting for people and getting people to read you and their attention

00:39:20.520 --> 00:39:25.320
[Guest]: spans you know I mean fixing their attention spans is far more important and interesting

00:39:25.320 --> 00:39:29.640
[Guest]: and challenging than sort of you know just writing and you know I mean letting your ego

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:35.800
[Guest]: you know be there all the way all I mean in all places so I think Lankesh was a very decisive

00:39:35.800 --> 00:39:40.160
[Guest]: influence and then at the same time you know I mean it's it's it's so happened that I've

00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:45.080
[Guest]: been lucky Amit that there is Lankesh who's trying to give you these lessons there's your

00:39:45.080 --> 00:39:51.480
[Guest]: father who's being a just gentle mentor and then there is I was also not completely alien

00:39:51.480 --> 00:39:57.480
[Guest]: to abstract ideas and theorization and the culture of insight as I call it you know it's

00:39:57.480 --> 00:40:02.440
[Guest]: not the culture of it's not empirical you know I mean stacking up of data which was

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:06.440
[Guest]: important but you know trying to look at a culture of I mean trying to develop a culture

00:40:06.440 --> 00:40:10.720
[Guest]: of insight you know so my father used to always tell me that you shall not write anything

00:40:10.720 --> 00:40:16.440
[Guest]: if you don't have an insight and something new to say so it's not just you just you know

00:40:16.440 --> 00:40:21.080
[Guest]: put things together and then say that this is your piece no you have to have something

00:40:21.080 --> 00:40:25.480
[Guest]: to say until then don't write and don't make writing so easy for yourself which of course

00:40:25.480 --> 00:40:31.400
[Guest]: you know I could not have done as a journalist later but but then I later realized the importance

00:40:31.400 --> 00:40:36.320
[Guest]: of the culture of insight which he sort of taught me but abstraction was another thing

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:41.160
[Guest]: which you know trying to sort of look at abstract ideas you know I had become interested a little

00:40:41.160 --> 00:40:47.520
[Guest]: bit in Barth, Rolla Barth at that time and then but I but you know Barth or Foucault

00:40:47.520 --> 00:40:55.400
[Guest]: and Derrida I'm I sort of came to study formally later but you know I mean in my BA and whatever

00:40:55.400 --> 00:41:00.160
[Guest]: there was this great literary critic in Canada and a cultural thinker in Canada called Kevin

00:41:00.160 --> 00:41:05.360
[Guest]: Narayan and Kevin Narayan was the one who introduced me to Chomsky's linguistics and

00:41:05.360 --> 00:41:11.680
[Guest]: I mean ideas of our ideas on language and then also and he had this enormous ability

00:41:11.680 --> 00:41:16.560
[Guest]: he was he was the teacher of D.R. Nagraj also and he had this enormous ability to theorize

00:41:16.560 --> 00:41:20.400
[Guest]: things in a way you know I mean look at something and say that okay this is the kind of broad

00:41:20.400 --> 00:41:25.720
[Guest]: structure into which it fell so I was fascinated by the way he designed his ideas you know

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:30.720
[Guest]: conceptually put them in boxes and he was a sort of student of science too so he's bringing

00:41:30.720 --> 00:41:36.800
[Guest]: his knowledge of science and learning and all that into looking at literature and making

00:41:36.800 --> 00:41:42.040
[Guest]: literature look more like science there was a phase in Canada when you know you they thought

00:41:42.040 --> 00:41:47.640
[Guest]: of making it very precise and you know I mean speaking of it like quantum theory or whatever

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:54.720
[Guest]: so there was that phase which I learned immensely from that phase because abstraction and theoretical

00:41:54.720 --> 00:42:00.040
[Guest]: ideas and how to build you know and put things in a larger frame how to put them in a context

00:42:00.040 --> 00:42:04.520
[Guest]: how to sort of link them and how to sort of bring this culture of insight into all of

00:42:04.520 --> 00:42:10.720
[Guest]: that all of this started happening inside me and now it's you know it's just that as

00:42:10.720 --> 00:42:16.080
[Guest]: I sit here and reflect with you I feel surprised that all these processes processes have happened

00:42:16.080 --> 00:42:20.640
[Guest]: inside me I mean you're giving me an opportunity to sort of you know I mean reflect on these

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:25.560
[Guest]: I'm just having a free flow thing with you but I was not conscious of all these things

00:42:25.560 --> 00:42:31.240
[Guest]: so this is how things I think get into anybody's mind anybody's personality and shapes you

00:42:31.240 --> 00:42:36.520
[Guest]: into a person that you finally become or are constantly becoming you know I mean so I think

00:42:36.520 --> 00:42:41.280
[Guest]: that was happening with me and Narayan was a huge influence Badrinath was an influence

00:42:41.280 --> 00:42:46.840
[Guest]: my father was a constant force and my mother was doing this something which is very fascinating

00:42:46.840 --> 00:42:51.480
[Guest]: and my grandmother was doing something and my grandfather I still keep his Jaimini Bharata

00:42:51.480 --> 00:42:58.440
[Guest]: in my study today even today even to this day it's a old thing the fat thick text and

00:42:58.440 --> 00:43:05.080
[Guest]: so classical traditional modern European Lankesh trying to take you across the seas now Lankesh

00:43:05.080 --> 00:43:09.760
[Guest]: never crossed the seas Lankesh never went abroad but he wrote about Europe as if it

00:43:09.760 --> 00:43:14.780
[Guest]: was his you know I mean the gully next door you know I mean he he wrote so insightfully

00:43:14.780 --> 00:43:22.320
[Guest]: about Hemingway he wrote so much about Spanish Civil War he wrote so much about the Mitra

00:43:22.320 --> 00:43:29.560
[Guest]: Mitra France then he is the one who told us about this great writer called Borges he said

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:35.320
[Guest]: there is this you should read Latin American writers and then there was another idea which

00:43:35.320 --> 00:43:39.680
[Guest]: of course there was a secular environment which I now called secular but then it was

00:43:39.680 --> 00:43:45.680
[Guest]: a very organic environment those days but I my father and Lankesh were friends and it

00:43:45.680 --> 00:43:51.600
[Guest]: was a very strange kind of friendship because my father was spoke very little so but Lankesh

00:43:51.600 --> 00:43:55.640
[Guest]: always used to sort of talk to him and my father would listen and probably respond a

00:43:55.640 --> 00:44:01.720
[Guest]: week later or something like that I still have cards that Lankesh would write and my

00:44:01.720 --> 00:44:08.360
[Guest]: my father would send a card and then stick a I mean another card asking him to respond

00:44:08.360 --> 00:44:12.040
[Guest]: because he would I think that was a practice you know you would just spin that and Lankesh

00:44:12.040 --> 00:44:17.320
[Guest]: would just sign at the bottom empty so I have many cards like that at home so so Lankesh

00:44:17.320 --> 00:44:22.280
[Guest]: and my father had this thing and once my father I think he would never visit his office he

00:44:22.280 --> 00:44:27.960
[Guest]: was already a very famous journalist and a writer and much much bigger than I mean you

00:44:27.960 --> 00:44:32.640
[Guest]: can imagine you know I mean I would you know in the Kannada space you know and I it is

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:37.200
[Guest]: Lankesh who's much much bigger than a Karnad or an Anant Murthy or whoever so I mean because

00:44:37.200 --> 00:44:41.840
[Guest]: he had the masses and he had the classes on a side and I went to see him once and then

00:44:41.840 --> 00:44:45.960
[Guest]: he asked me very strangely he asked me tell me the names of your friends you know I mean

00:44:45.960 --> 00:44:52.400
[Guest]: it's very strange thing question to be asked and I named a few and then he said but there

00:44:52.400 --> 00:44:56.880
[Guest]: is no Muslim name in it there's no Christian name in it you should you should have you

00:44:56.880 --> 00:45:00.640
[Guest]: should have a Muslim friend you should have a Christian friend I mean it is almost like

00:45:00.640 --> 00:45:06.080
[Guest]: didactic you know telling you that go and get these people into your life also so your

00:45:06.080 --> 00:45:11.600
[Guest]: life becomes richer that's all he said and then I mean he spoke about nothing else and

00:45:11.600 --> 00:45:15.920
[Guest]: then he was very dismissive about this and that and he was very erratic in his thing

00:45:15.920 --> 00:45:21.200
[Guest]: and very brusque in his you know expression so we one wouldn't want to stay there for

00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:25.440
[Guest]: too long and my father was a teetotaler and Lankesh always enjoyed his drink and all that

00:45:25.440 --> 00:45:30.880
[Guest]: so so we just came back and but Lankesh was a huge huge influence so all of these things

00:45:30.880 --> 00:45:38.320
[Guest]: were happening in my early life and then after my BA I mean I had finished my thing and then

00:45:38.320 --> 00:45:42.760
[Guest]: I got a seat at the Central University of Hyderabad in the English department and that

00:45:42.760 --> 00:45:48.560
[Guest]: was another huge huge change because for the first time I was going outside of home it

00:45:48.560 --> 00:45:54.840
[Guest]: was not very far off as Hyderabad but still you know it was like flying abroad so you

00:45:54.840 --> 00:46:00.240
[Guest]: you went and you put yourself in a hostel and then there are these students from postgraduate

00:46:00.240 --> 00:46:05.760
[Guest]: students from the computer applications department computer was a big thing just about getting

00:46:05.760 --> 00:46:11.600
[Guest]: off the thing and then there were students of doing PhD in physics and then you're interacting

00:46:11.600 --> 00:46:19.280
[Guest]: with all these fellows sitting in the hostel at your dining table and then I was also introduced

00:46:19.280 --> 00:46:24.960
[Guest]: there to radical student politics you know I mean Hyderabad was a hotbed of radical politics

00:46:24.960 --> 00:46:32.400
[Guest]: student politics and I it so happened that I became a roommate of a person who was on

00:46:32.400 --> 00:46:40.200
[Guest]: the extreme left and later that person became the son-in-law of Varvara Rao right so K Satyanarayana

00:46:40.200 --> 00:46:45.000
[Guest]: so he had contested an election new student body election and then I mean innocently you

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:50.320
[Guest]: went and campaigned and then that's also when I realized that you know I mean how ideologies

00:46:50.320 --> 00:46:56.080
[Guest]: are constraining and limiting and they try to exclude you because how much of a loyalty

00:46:56.080 --> 00:47:00.720
[Guest]: I showed these people they would never make me part of them never may never invite me

00:47:00.720 --> 00:47:05.520
[Guest]: to their secret meetings so I felt very disturbed and then in my second MA I think I wrote a

00:47:05.520 --> 00:47:10.120
[Guest]: letter saying that I have nothing to do with any of you so I still keep that letter which

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:14.880
[Guest]: a photocopy of that letter and so I thought that this is very limiting and then I got

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:20.120
[Guest]: back into my literature studies but literature studies literature department itself were

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:25.880
[Guest]: going through a transition at that time and there was this huge conflict about colonial

00:47:25.880 --> 00:47:31.200
[Guest]: curriculum curriculums you know I mean so people who wanted to study Shakespeare seriously

00:47:31.200 --> 00:47:37.640
[Guest]: or Shelley or the romantics or the key or Keats or Dunn or all these people were looked

00:47:37.640 --> 00:47:41.160
[Guest]: down upon you know I mean are you what is it that you're doing you know you're you're

00:47:41.160 --> 00:47:45.360
[Guest]: studying only what the British has asked you to study there's these are canonical texts

00:47:45.360 --> 00:47:49.280
[Guest]: there's so much that's happening in America and post-structuralism and structuralism that

00:47:49.280 --> 00:47:55.080
[Guest]: have dismantled this whole idea of education etc. etc. etc. so this was being constantly

00:47:55.080 --> 00:48:00.480
[Guest]: being thrown at us by one or two teachers and one of them later happened to become my

00:48:00.480 --> 00:48:06.280
[Guest]: MPhil and PhD guides Tejaswini Niranjana and it so happened that Niranjana's father and

00:48:06.280 --> 00:48:11.720
[Guest]: my father again they had this teacher-student relationship and it was a lifelong very very

00:48:11.720 --> 00:48:17.760
[Guest]: good relationship and I mean so she was she had just come back from the United States

00:48:17.760 --> 00:48:22.480
[Guest]: I mean I think she had she had done a PhD and she had come back and she was very high

00:48:22.480 --> 00:48:27.560
[Guest]: on literary theory and Foucault and Derry all of that and she wanted I mean she wanted

00:48:27.560 --> 00:48:32.200
[Guest]: us to read all of that you know and I really appreciate what happened at that phase but

00:48:32.200 --> 00:48:37.880
[Guest]: then you know it was trying to sort of make you look at your what you had until then thought

00:48:37.880 --> 00:48:42.400
[Guest]: was literature and I mean it put a lot of questions on that and that was welcome because

00:48:42.400 --> 00:48:48.880
[Guest]: you know you reconciled your new exposure and your old thing later much later and it

00:48:48.880 --> 00:48:53.640
[Guest]: sort of blend beautifully inside you but then at that point it was a kind of a disruption

00:48:53.640 --> 00:48:59.280
[Guest]: for me and then I mean so I moved from the literature department after MA after I got

00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:05.840
[Guest]: a good MA degree into the comparative literature department for my PhD and I chose her as my

00:49:05.840 --> 00:49:11.280
[Guest]: guide and I again because I was so familiar with the idea of translations and Ramanujan

00:49:11.280 --> 00:49:17.960
[Guest]: was a friend of ours you know he used to come home and I still keep letters of it that between

00:49:17.960 --> 00:49:23.320
[Guest]: my father and him and so he used to I mean out of the blue write to my father in an airmail

00:49:23.320 --> 00:49:27.360
[Guest]: saying that I need this book Raju can you please keep it for me I'll be coming on such

00:49:27.360 --> 00:49:31.280
[Guest]: and such a date I'll pick it up from you and then he was very interested in some of the

00:49:31.280 --> 00:49:36.440
[Guest]: poets that my father had published so he would say that this man is the next Adiga so Gopal

00:49:36.440 --> 00:49:41.640
[Guest]: Krishna Adiga is another very big name in Kannada and a stalwart of person who sort

00:49:41.640 --> 00:49:46.720
[Guest]: of shaped the Navya movement in Kannada and Ananthamurthy and others were all influenced

00:49:46.720 --> 00:49:51.800
[Guest]: by him big man but a Jansangh he contested on a Jansangh ticket now that's a separate

00:49:51.800 --> 00:49:56.560
[Guest]: thing now how ideologies again did not matter when it came to literature because his literature

00:49:56.560 --> 00:50:02.340
[Guest]: was good so I mean I used to when he had a he had a stroke and he could not write my

00:50:02.340 --> 00:50:06.960
[Guest]: father used to send me to his house great man and he would sort of I was I used to write

00:50:06.960 --> 00:50:12.080
[Guest]: down what he would tell me and then you know I mean that's how I became very very close

00:50:12.080 --> 00:50:18.360
[Guest]: to him before he passed away I think in 93 or so I'm not sure about the date but then

00:50:18.360 --> 00:50:23.400
[Guest]: so he was another person but then coming back to Hyderabad and this literary experience

00:50:23.400 --> 00:50:28.200
[Guest]: and this new challenges that were being thrown at me and trying to sort of undo all that

00:50:28.200 --> 00:50:34.280
[Guest]: I had thought was literature was a was a great thing and then there is also this little bit

00:50:34.280 --> 00:50:41.820
[Guest]: of radical politics entering into your horizon because you were a protected boy from a family

00:50:41.820 --> 00:50:47.100
[Guest]: which was had a literary orientation and you know and very cultural kind of a thing and

00:50:47.100 --> 00:50:52.160
[Guest]: suddenly you're being asked hard I mean being told that there are harsh realities there

00:50:52.160 --> 00:50:57.400
[Guest]: and this is all useless you know I mean your poetry is useless because it's very romantic

00:50:57.400 --> 00:51:01.520
[Guest]: after all it's about individuals you know you should write poetry for the society and

00:51:01.520 --> 00:51:07.280
[Guest]: that's when I very seriously when I came home for a holiday thing I took an anthology of

00:51:07.280 --> 00:51:12.960
[Guest]: socialist verse with me which was in my father's library by Alan bold it was edited by Alan

00:51:12.960 --> 00:51:17.760
[Guest]: bold and it had even to this day it's the most delightful anthology that I've ever read

00:51:17.760 --> 00:51:22.120
[Guest]: you know I mean I read Neruda for the first time there I read Mayakovsky I read Vasco

00:51:22.120 --> 00:51:28.000
[Guest]: Popper I read a lot of people and used to you know translate a few of them that I liked

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:33.640
[Guest]: and I would keep them so so so so I started opening up myself to bigger questions that

00:51:33.640 --> 00:51:38.120
[Guest]: were being asked so there's not just literature there was this not this cozy relationship

00:51:38.120 --> 00:51:45.200
[Guest]: of stories and there's not that literary questions or literary criticism and framing and abstract

00:51:45.200 --> 00:51:50.840
[Guest]: whatever ideas within a certain area and being familiar with the registers of literature

00:51:50.840 --> 00:51:56.600
[Guest]: and literary criticism but also larger questions that concern society and those questions were

00:51:56.600 --> 00:52:02.280
[Guest]: thrown at me without my asking suddenly in the hostels of the University of Hyderabad

00:52:02.280 --> 00:52:08.720
[Guest]: Central University of Hyderabad so that sort of again so I my mother's dream again because

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:13.560
[Guest]: right from my childhood she would make me listen to the AIR news at nine o'clock and

00:52:13.560 --> 00:52:17.960
[Guest]: she had kept a diary and I had to write the headlines and show it to her and then I would

00:52:17.960 --> 00:52:23.240
[Guest]: be allowed to go to sleep so that was the ritual that was practiced for years and apparently

00:52:23.240 --> 00:52:28.800
[Guest]: she did that because she wanted me to be an IAS officer and one of my father's colleagues

00:52:28.800 --> 00:52:34.480
[Guest]: had written the UPSC exams and had become an IAS officer not not so much an IAS officer

00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:38.920
[Guest]: but he had become the postmaster general I mean another service which you get if you

00:52:38.920 --> 00:52:45.040
[Guest]: get a slightly lesser score so so she wanted me to be an IAS officer and then I as officer

00:52:45.040 --> 00:52:50.520
[Guest]: the connotation was of power and you know you know prestige and all that so I think

00:52:50.520 --> 00:52:55.280
[Guest]: she had driven that into me or put that into my head and it was there somewhere in the

00:52:55.280 --> 00:52:59.600
[Guest]: back of my mind so so now that you've not done engineering at least do this you know

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:04.040
[Guest]: I mean you know that kind of a thing but that was also completely shattered when I went

00:53:04.040 --> 00:53:08.480
[Guest]: to Hyderabad you know I I thought that this was gulamgiri of a different kind you know

00:53:08.480 --> 00:53:14.200
[Guest]: I mean of course you know I mean later some of the finest bureaucrats became my friends

00:53:14.200 --> 00:53:19.440
[Guest]: and friends of our family and they still nurtured me and great men but you know at that point

00:53:19.440 --> 00:53:23.880
[Guest]: of time you know I mean this this whole disruption is happening and then literature is being

00:53:23.880 --> 00:53:29.380
[Guest]: exploded so everything is being exploded in your mind and even this idea got exploded

00:53:29.380 --> 00:53:34.480
[Guest]: so I never took the UPSC exams and my mother was even to this day I think she's terribly

00:53:34.480 --> 00:53:38.200
[Guest]: terribly disappointed so when I became an editor and chief secretaries used to call

00:53:38.200 --> 00:53:43.760
[Guest]: me up or principal secretaries used to come to see me I used to go back and tell her that

00:53:43.760 --> 00:53:47.720
[Guest]: see you wanted me to be an IAS officer see so many of them come to see me today they

00:53:47.720 --> 00:53:52.880
[Guest]: seek an appointment so but she was not very happy she said that's then something has gone

00:53:52.880 --> 00:53:57.400
[Guest]: into your head so don't don't don't really think that you've become something so you

00:53:57.400 --> 00:54:03.480
[Guest]: know she was still not convinced about it so this was so these ideas got exploded so

00:54:03.480 --> 00:54:10.360
[Guest]: again you started looking at world very differently and I remember there all night people reading

00:54:10.360 --> 00:54:15.320
[Guest]: out revolutionary verse you know the Telugu boys especially you know reading out Sri

00:54:15.320 --> 00:54:20.480
[Guest]: Sri's poetry to me and saying that see look at this look at this is does your KS Narasimha

00:54:20.480 --> 00:54:24.520
[Guest]: Swami write like this does your Gopal Krishna Adiga write like this is a reactionary so

00:54:24.520 --> 00:54:29.200
[Guest]: they started labeling writers for me saying that he is this he is that why do you need

00:54:29.200 --> 00:54:34.120
[Guest]: to read this fellow you know I mean oh Tolstoy you know I mean here's something else no that's

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:40.880
[Guest]: not sufficient you know I mean so so so these things completely changed in my mind around

00:54:40.880 --> 00:54:48.920
[Guest]: that time so this is then I am sort of there and doing my PhD and then I've picked a very

00:54:48.920 --> 00:54:53.240
[Guest]: interesting subject because translations is very dear to me I thought I'll become a translator

00:54:53.240 --> 00:54:59.080
[Guest]: in my life you know that was an academic researching on translations doing literary translations

00:54:59.080 --> 00:55:04.120
[Guest]: I've never meant to be a journalist I was never study I never studied journalism so

00:55:04.120 --> 00:55:10.160
[Guest]: I picked on nationalism and translations the idea of nationalism and run because my PhD

00:55:10.160 --> 00:55:16.640
[Guest]: guide Tejaswini Niranjana had done her work on translations and so I thought I mean I

00:55:16.640 --> 00:55:22.360
[Guest]: think we discussed this and we thought I thought I should look at the the early translations

00:55:22.360 --> 00:55:29.800
[Guest]: of modern Kannada literature and try to see why those translations happened so linking

00:55:29.800 --> 00:55:34.360
[Guest]: it up with Kannada sub-nationalism linking up with nationalism so I was trying to look

00:55:34.360 --> 00:55:40.920
[Guest]: at that and of course she was putting a very heavy theoretical framework and she was not

00:55:40.920 --> 00:55:46.680
[Guest]: very enthusiastic about the local literature that I was discovering and showing it to her

00:55:46.680 --> 00:55:50.800
[Guest]: so at some point I felt very slighted that she's not interested in what I'm showing it's

00:55:50.800 --> 00:55:56.000
[Guest]: it's a one-way thing so I suddenly decided I will not I'll take a break from doing PhD

00:55:56.000 --> 00:56:00.160
[Guest]: go back to Bangalore for some time and then probably I mean I was still very young so

00:56:00.160 --> 00:56:06.240
[Guest]: I thought I'll always come back to do my PhD and in I mean at that time also there was

00:56:06.240 --> 00:56:12.240
[Guest]: this huge subaltern history conference that happened in Hyderabad so there was Gayatri

00:56:12.240 --> 00:56:17.800
[Guest]: Chakravorty Spivak there was Ranjit Guha all these people congregating and I wasn't volunteer

00:56:17.800 --> 00:56:24.120
[Guest]: to that whole thing and at that time there was the Deccan Herald and Prajavani people

00:56:24.120 --> 00:56:29.480
[Guest]: the Sunday there was an editor who I was looking after that and he said this is happening I

00:56:29.480 --> 00:56:34.800
[Guest]: mean I had spoken to him very interestingly about the idea of subaltern history why it

00:56:34.800 --> 00:56:40.080
[Guest]: is interesting how it is different and I think I had spoken to him at length about Shaheed

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:45.320
[Guest]: Amin's piece on Gandhi as Mahatma or something like that you know I mean I think I remember

00:56:45.320 --> 00:56:49.400
[Guest]: speaking to him about it and then he got very fascinated he said why don't you write a long

00:56:49.400 --> 00:56:54.160
[Guest]: series so I said I'll do a three-part series on subaltern history for you and I wrote a

00:56:54.160 --> 00:56:58.160
[Guest]: three-part series on subaltern history for the Kannada newspaper which also got into

00:56:58.160 --> 00:57:03.800
[Guest]: the English newspaper later I wrote in Kannada for Prajavani primarily so that made me a

00:57:03.800 --> 00:57:08.280
[Guest]: bit of a local you know I mean antenna went up people started saying over we read your

00:57:08.280 --> 00:57:11.960
[Guest]: piece so there was this instant recognition and there was this crisis happening in my

00:57:11.960 --> 00:57:18.120
[Guest]: PhD program so I thought I can do some journalism some cultural journalism literature literary

00:57:18.120 --> 00:57:22.440
[Guest]: journalism and then go back to my academics so that's when I came back home and again

00:57:22.440 --> 00:57:27.680
[Guest]: I met my father I used to take this overnight bus if you don't get you didn't if you didn't

00:57:27.680 --> 00:57:33.040
[Guest]: get a train ticket you took an overnight bus with which used to play movies all night on

00:57:33.040 --> 00:57:38.800
[Guest]: that you know I mean they used to have a television set and Anu Malik's music used to run all

00:57:38.800 --> 00:57:43.280
[Guest]: through night and it was terrible you know those journeys but then I landed up in Bangalore

00:57:43.280 --> 00:57:47.760
[Guest]: at six o'clock and my father was up he was a very early riser so he was having his coffee

00:57:47.760 --> 00:57:52.720
[Guest]: he said oh I mean you've come back I said yeah I want to tell you something I didn't

00:57:52.720 --> 00:57:58.280
[Guest]: even wait for anything I said this is what I've decided I'll go after a point of time

00:57:58.280 --> 00:58:02.880
[Guest]: I don't want to sort of pursue it now because I don't feel happy so is that so why should

00:58:02.880 --> 00:58:08.520
[Guest]: you be worried okay again he was very cool about it he said did not ever tell me that

00:58:08.520 --> 00:58:12.640
[Guest]: you should no no no this is not the way to do it I mean I enough tell my son that you

00:58:12.640 --> 00:58:17.480
[Guest]: know me no no no don't take the breaks that I took you may never go back to what you want

00:58:17.480 --> 00:58:22.600
[Guest]: to do so but he never said said that he said okay good you know I mean fine that's all

00:58:22.600 --> 00:58:26.320
[Guest]: that's all fine you know I mean if you're not happy you shouldn't do it so you'll always

00:58:26.320 --> 00:58:30.520
[Guest]: sort of you know understand as to why you need to do it so you'll go back to it so and

00:58:30.520 --> 00:58:35.200
[Guest]: that phase when I came back and then there was nothing to do and I was reading and reading

00:58:35.200 --> 00:58:41.720
[Guest]: consuming literature again and you know when trying to read biographies at that time you

00:58:41.720 --> 00:58:47.520
[Guest]: know I mean I was reading all this kind of stuff that was coming up after the breakup

00:58:47.520 --> 00:58:51.440
[Guest]: of the Soviet Union I think there was a string of biographies that was coming out in the

00:58:51.440 --> 00:58:56.520
[Guest]: West which was dismantling the character of people like Brecht or Einstein or making them

00:58:56.520 --> 00:59:01.720
[Guest]: look like you know I mean trying to speak so heavily about their private lives and and

00:59:01.720 --> 00:59:06.440
[Guest]: the I mean trying to break the icon of these you know the it was an iconographic kind of

00:59:06.440 --> 00:59:11.200
[Guest]: a thing iconoclastic sorry iconoclastic kind of a biographies that were coming out and

00:59:11.200 --> 00:59:18.240
[Guest]: I was reading all of that and then suddenly one day my father had another very elderly

00:59:18.240 --> 00:59:22.840
[Guest]: writer friend who said if Sugata is doing nothing Girish Kasarwadi is making a movie

00:59:22.840 --> 00:59:27.440
[Guest]: why doesn't he sort of you know go and spend some time with him so I just went to Girish

00:59:27.440 --> 00:59:31.880
[Guest]: Kasarwadi's house and he was so welcoming and he said see I'm making this movie called

00:59:31.880 --> 00:59:36.920
[Guest]: Kravya it's based on the short story so you read the short story and come tomorrow let's

00:59:36.920 --> 00:59:42.200
[Guest]: discuss so I just read the short story and I next day I had a lot of ideas because of

00:59:42.200 --> 00:59:46.960
[Guest]: course you wanted to prove that you know you've you've you've come out you've come out of

00:59:46.960 --> 00:59:51.960
[Guest]: university and then you've read all these new things and you have great ideas and so

00:59:51.960 --> 00:59:55.640
[Guest]: I started discussing and we used to discuss with three four hours and he was very patient

00:59:55.640 --> 01:00:01.480
[Guest]: with me and he liked a lot of ideas and then I mean I sort of did a conceptual design for

01:00:01.480 --> 01:00:07.720
[Guest]: the film which you know means it was very interesting project for eight or ten months

01:00:07.720 --> 01:00:13.520
[Guest]: and then when Girish Kasarwadi finally released the movie I was thrilled of course I didn't

01:00:13.520 --> 01:00:19.120
[Guest]: get paid because it was I was volunteering or he never sort of drew up a contract for

01:00:19.120 --> 01:00:25.760
[Guest]: me but then this in the in the scroll in the credit scroll my name was right at right on

01:00:25.760 --> 01:00:32.280
[Guest]: top with B. V. Karanth and you know I mean that happened that that that kind of joy and

01:00:32.280 --> 01:00:37.040
[Guest]: you know you jumped off the chair and I mean I told my father see can you see by name it's

01:00:37.040 --> 01:00:41.000
[Guest]: with the great B. V. Karanth and B. V. Karanth my father were great friends again they used

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:44.600
[Guest]: to come to premia together to buy books and they used to go to Koshi's and have a coffee

01:00:44.600 --> 01:00:51.120
[Guest]: and then disperse in fact Ram Gohar mentions it in his obituary recently for I mean Shan

01:00:51.120 --> 01:00:57.280
[Guest]: Bagh Mr. Shan Bagh so I mean I was very happy and I thought oh I mean I mean I can do a

01:00:57.280 --> 01:01:02.920
[Guest]: lot of things there is movies there is these people have published a series for me you

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:07.640
[Guest]: know in Deccan Herald so I mean I can do journalism and I can do all this for the next two or

01:01:07.640 --> 01:01:12.040
[Guest]: three years and then go back to academics so I sort of very promptly applied for a job

01:01:12.040 --> 01:01:17.480
[Guest]: in Deccan Herald and I mean my application went up to Mr. Hari Kumar and then of course

01:01:17.480 --> 01:01:21.400
[Guest]: you know with all the you were bragging about yourself that you've done this you've done

01:01:21.400 --> 01:01:25.760
[Guest]: this and you read this and all that so he called me for an interview and that interview

01:01:25.760 --> 01:01:34.160
[Guest]: went on for easily more than an hour for a trainee's position and there he sort of started

01:01:34.160 --> 01:01:38.440
[Guest]: discouraging me at the end of the interview saying that you're not meant for journalism

01:01:38.440 --> 01:01:43.160
[Guest]: he said you won't fit into this whole scheme you don't know how a newsroom runs so you

01:01:43.160 --> 01:01:47.280
[Guest]: just think because you've written a article you think you can become a journalist no that's

01:01:47.280 --> 01:01:51.920
[Guest]: not how journalism that's not what journalism does so I kept you know I needed this job

01:01:51.920 --> 01:01:58.520
[Guest]: so I kept telling him that no sir I mean I can I can be very useful to you I can do cultural

01:01:58.520 --> 01:02:03.760
[Guest]: journalism and I at that point of time I never thought I'll do politics or write on politics

01:02:03.760 --> 01:02:09.680
[Guest]: or it was only about literature and culture and things like that so then he sort of gave

01:02:09.680 --> 01:02:15.240
[Guest]: a very strange offer he said okay I'll allow you two months in the newsroom then come back

01:02:15.240 --> 01:02:19.360
[Guest]: and tell me if you like it I'll give you a trainee's job so I had to work for two months

01:02:19.360 --> 01:02:24.680
[Guest]: without pay in Deccan Herald you know writing and collecting my bylines and then filing

01:02:24.680 --> 01:02:29.680
[Guest]: it with the executive editor and saying see I've done all this so why don't you give me

01:02:29.680 --> 01:02:34.960
[Guest]: a job so at the end of two months after much persuasion prodding and nodding and all that

01:02:34.960 --> 01:02:41.640
[Guest]: he gave me a trainee's job and for a princely sum of about two thousand rupees those days

01:02:41.640 --> 01:02:46.720
[Guest]: and that was you know I mean some and Prajawani and Deccan Herald that group was immensely

01:02:46.720 --> 01:02:50.800
[Guest]: respected at that time it was a number one paper the times was nowhere in the picture

01:02:50.800 --> 01:02:56.920
[Guest]: those days which year was this this is 95 1995 so times was nowhere in the picture it

01:02:56.920 --> 01:03:03.400
[Guest]: was it was torturing so to say Express had its own problems and Hindu was a very mild

01:03:03.400 --> 01:03:08.080
[Guest]: presence you know I mean as it is today in Karnataka so this was the number one paper

01:03:08.080 --> 01:03:13.000
[Guest]: and if you and it and had and it had Sunday Herald and articulations books it used to

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:20.320
[Guest]: be a thriving paper so you got into it then you thought you were you had arrived so but

01:03:20.320 --> 01:03:26.440
[Guest]: he took a liking to me once I sort of was confirmed as a trainee he took a liking to

01:03:26.440 --> 01:03:32.560
[Guest]: me and then instantly decided to send me abroad on an assignment and there was this Bombay

01:03:32.560 --> 01:03:38.280
[Guest]: was the minister of HRD and then he was going to Moscow for some cultural festival he said

01:03:38.280 --> 01:03:43.120
[Guest]: send so get there and I was a trainee so he was extraordinarily generous that and then

01:03:43.120 --> 01:03:46.760
[Guest]: of course it raised the eyebrows of all the seniors in the newsroom all that happened

01:03:46.760 --> 01:03:52.040
[Guest]: but then somehow he took a liking to me and then I mean I thought I should exploit that

01:03:52.040 --> 01:03:59.240
[Guest]: thing and then I wrote a note to him in 96 and I'd by then be become a regular journalist

01:03:59.240 --> 01:04:03.680
[Guest]: and I mean my training training period was over one year become a regular journalist

01:04:03.680 --> 01:04:09.440
[Guest]: I said Jacques Derrida has come to India I have some understanding of his writings and

01:04:09.440 --> 01:04:14.920
[Guest]: his philosophy and his and the polemics that surrounds it so if you permit me I will go

01:04:14.920 --> 01:04:19.360
[Guest]: to Delhi and interview him I just wrote I without even asking Jacques Derrida if you

01:04:19.360 --> 01:04:26.400
[Guest]: want to give me an interview so I wrote and he used to sort of have a very strange way

01:04:26.400 --> 01:04:30.840
[Guest]: of saying yes he used to just write an okay at the edge of the paper so that okay came

01:04:30.840 --> 01:04:37.000
[Guest]: back so they bought me a ticket and I went to landed up in Delhi and attended the lectures

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:40.640
[Guest]: of Jacques Derrida at the Delhi School of Economics it was on the short history of the

01:04:40.640 --> 01:04:47.120
[Guest]: lie and then I somehow wanted his to draw his attention and get a get an appointment

01:04:47.120 --> 01:04:51.280
[Guest]: with him and ask him a few questions and I was trying to very seriously brush up my French

01:04:51.280 --> 01:04:56.120
[Guest]: you know tuta puta kind of a French and all that but then you know I sent a note and left

01:04:56.120 --> 01:05:02.320
[Guest]: it with one of those people who are accompanying him and they very promptly called me and it

01:05:02.320 --> 01:05:06.080
[Guest]: was very strange you know people are so generous and kind at times you don't know why they

01:05:06.080 --> 01:05:11.360
[Guest]: pick you or what I was his rookie fellow you know I mean with absolutely no background

01:05:11.360 --> 01:05:17.440
[Guest]: and then they called me he said see Mr. Derrida will be free for about 15 minutes you can

01:05:17.440 --> 01:05:23.080
[Guest]: ask him whatever you want just before he starts this other lecture so I went and I honestly

01:05:23.080 --> 01:05:26.560
[Guest]: don't remember what I asked him I didn't have a tape recorder to record I think I had a

01:05:26.560 --> 01:05:31.440
[Guest]: record or something some very old tape some very strange thing so I asked him about Gandhi

01:05:31.440 --> 01:05:36.920
[Guest]: asked him about Chomsky and I asked him about his own thing one or two things of chromatology

01:05:36.920 --> 01:05:42.960
[Guest]: a few questions very very academic theoretical something that would not fit into a journalistic

01:05:42.960 --> 01:05:47.800
[Guest]: piece that I had to write I had been sent to write so I came by I was very happy so

01:05:47.800 --> 01:05:52.720
[Guest]: I went around telling that Derrida has given me an interview and I had taken a picture

01:05:52.720 --> 01:05:58.120
[Guest]: with him so I had everything that one had to so this was just 10 or 15 minutes of his

01:05:58.120 --> 01:06:03.640
[Guest]: tape but then I sat back in the room that night and I was staying at this tandoor hotel

01:06:03.640 --> 01:06:10.320
[Guest]: what had become called a tandoor hotel and then I sat there there was this I still remember

01:06:10.320 --> 01:06:16.360
[Guest]: the table was you know I mean it was a stone slab kind of a table and I said I should you

01:06:16.360 --> 01:06:21.160
[Guest]: know I mean this is my great moment I should craft a piece which will appeal to a larger

01:06:21.160 --> 01:06:25.320
[Guest]: Kannada audience and it I should introduce Derrida instead of saying that I interviewed

01:06:25.320 --> 01:06:31.320
[Guest]: I should introduce him so I was reading Feynman at that time you know Richard Feynman's books

01:06:31.320 --> 01:06:35.840
[Guest]: you know I mean you're surely joking Mr Feynman all the usual stuff that you read at that

01:06:35.840 --> 01:06:41.080
[Guest]: age and then there was a poem that he had used in some different context I wonder why

01:06:41.080 --> 01:06:48.760
[Guest]: I wonder why I wonder why I wonder why so I took that and I sort of tried to apply the

01:06:48.760 --> 01:06:54.040
[Guest]: principles of deconstruction to that and then the question that I had made it a kichdi of

01:06:54.040 --> 01:06:58.840
[Guest]: something but it had a narrative the most important thing was it had a kind of flow

01:06:58.840 --> 01:07:05.280
[Guest]: and a narrative and when I gave it to my editor immediate editor here she said it's very good

01:07:05.280 --> 01:07:10.840
[Guest]: so I was stunned that you know when I had pulled off something and it was published

01:07:10.840 --> 01:07:15.120
[Guest]: as full two pages in Deccan Herald those days in the Sunday Herald I still have it full

01:07:15.120 --> 01:07:20.760
[Guest]: two pages I don't think any newspaper would ever you know give space like that today even

01:07:20.760 --> 01:07:24.800
[Guest]: I have been an editor of big newspapers I don't think I would I would think ten times

01:07:24.800 --> 01:07:29.240
[Guest]: before giving that kind of real estate you know to any writer so they gave me two full

01:07:29.240 --> 01:07:35.680
[Guest]: pages and my father was on cloud nine that day because you know I mean he thought his

01:07:35.680 --> 01:07:40.360
[Guest]: son had arrived and he had bet see as a he was my father was also used to bring out little

01:07:40.360 --> 01:07:46.480
[Guest]: magazines so he used to bring out a little magazine called Ankana then as a student he

01:07:46.480 --> 01:07:52.560
[Guest]: had started a magazine called Vimochane and then this so this whole habit of betting on

01:07:52.560 --> 01:07:58.240
[Guest]: people and writers it was a different kind of gamble was always and I think instinctually

01:07:58.240 --> 01:08:02.440
[Guest]: was there in him so he thought probably at this time that my son's the better I put on

01:08:02.440 --> 01:08:07.200
[Guest]: my son has worked so he's actually sort of pulled off something so because he was damn

01:08:07.200 --> 01:08:13.800
[Guest]: thrilled because that day morning I think around 7.15 because I remember where we were

01:08:13.800 --> 01:08:19.600
[Guest]: sitting and what we were doing and having coffee he got a call it was landline and D.R.

01:08:19.600 --> 01:08:25.480
[Guest]: Nagraj was on the other side my father used to be called Mestre in the sense teacher Mestre

01:08:25.480 --> 01:08:31.080
[Guest]: I read Sugata's piece has done a great job so my former and D.R. was a rising star in

01:08:31.080 --> 01:08:36.960
[Guest]: Kannada those days and my father for my father to hear that from D.R. Nagraj was a very very

01:08:36.960 --> 01:08:43.320
[Guest]: big thing and he said D.R. said this and he would not show it off but then he said good

01:08:43.320 --> 01:08:47.840
[Guest]: great but don't stop here you know you have to read more your responsibility increases

01:08:47.840 --> 01:08:52.400
[Guest]: because now the next time you make a mistake people will tear you apart now you are still

01:08:52.400 --> 01:08:57.200
[Guest]: a young fellow and you are publishing only in Karnataka tomorrow you may have to write

01:08:57.200 --> 01:09:01.160
[Guest]: for a bigger audience and people will not be as generous and kind so you have to be

01:09:01.160 --> 01:09:05.400
[Guest]: more thorough you know you have to be pakka with what you write and always make margin

01:09:05.400 --> 01:09:10.360
[Guest]: notes my father's books are always full of margin notes and pencil and all that and he

01:09:10.360 --> 01:09:14.240
[Guest]: used to keep notes he used to tell me that you have to do that too so I mean that's a

01:09:14.240 --> 01:09:20.280
[Guest]: habit that came to me also so I make a lot of notes when I read so that is something

01:09:20.280 --> 01:09:25.520
[Guest]: that happened at that point of time so that was the big break and then next year Chomsky

01:09:25.520 --> 01:09:30.120
[Guest]: came to India for the first time so again I wrote this thing and now I had a thing so

01:09:30.120 --> 01:09:35.920
[Guest]: they said okay go and I and another good thing was Chomsky's PhD student was my linguistics

01:09:35.920 --> 01:09:39.160
[Guest]: teacher at Hyderabad Central, Prabhaldas Gupta.

01:09:39.160 --> 01:09:43.520
[Guest]: So I spoke to Prabhaldas Gupta and he said don't worry you come I'll get you access

01:09:43.520 --> 01:09:49.760
[Guest]: so so I went and I met him and then I wrote pieces again then when Edward Said came I

01:09:49.760 --> 01:09:55.280
[Guest]: did the same thing so I was more on this other side writing about literature, philosophy

01:09:55.280 --> 01:10:03.040
[Guest]: and I mean big theoreticians people with big ideas in the world and trying to make news

01:10:03.040 --> 01:10:10.560
[Guest]: out of them and trying to write features on them so that is how I framed my early journalism

01:10:10.560 --> 01:10:16.200
[Guest]: which was again a very very accidental kind of a thing from literature trying to be an

01:10:16.200 --> 01:10:20.880
[Guest]: academic and this academic thing I have to tell you this you know when I was going to

01:10:20.880 --> 01:10:27.440
[Guest]: Hyderabad and because I was so close to Gopal Krishna Adiga the great poet in Canada had

01:10:27.440 --> 01:10:32.280
[Guest]: just won the Kabir Sanman or something like that very big and there was this unhappiness

01:10:32.280 --> 01:10:38.120
[Guest]: that he had not been given the Gnanpeet and his student or his I mean the person of the

01:10:38.120 --> 01:10:42.400
[Guest]: next year Anant Moorthy had been given and there was this huge talk in Kannada literary

01:10:42.400 --> 01:10:46.440
[Guest]: circles that oh Anant Moorthy had lobbied it would have actually been Gopal Krishna

01:10:46.440 --> 01:10:52.440
[Guest]: Adiga because he was the trendsetter in Kannada and all that so I went to him and then he

01:10:52.440 --> 01:10:56.400
[Guest]: said what do you want I have nothing to give you you've done so much for me he was he was

01:10:56.400 --> 01:11:01.240
[Guest]: actually a quite a rebel actually you know I mean he had given up his jobs and his poetry

01:11:01.240 --> 01:11:07.360
[Guest]: was something had a very humane and connected with me so I did something very stupid so

01:11:07.360 --> 01:11:18.000
[Guest]: I told him I love this poem of yours it is so philosophical and it's so small can I

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:25.160
[Guest]: have it in your own hand I would like to frame it so he said okay get me a paper and get

01:11:25.160 --> 01:11:30.800
[Guest]: me a pen which with good ink or whatever so I took a sketch pen and a big poster kind

01:11:30.800 --> 01:11:37.040
[Guest]: a3 kind of sheet and went and gave it to him and the next day he had kept two copies there

01:11:37.040 --> 01:11:43.520
[Guest]: I did not realize till that point he had had a stroke and he could not write and this man

01:11:43.520 --> 01:11:48.280
[Guest]: did not want to deny me that I still keep it in my study it's the most precious thing

01:11:48.280 --> 01:11:55.300
[Guest]: that I have of a great Kannada writer having written this poem for me and he gave me two

01:11:55.300 --> 01:12:01.240
[Guest]: and he said see this there's too much of my hand is shaken a lot here I could not write

01:12:01.240 --> 01:12:06.600
[Guest]: properly so when it stabilized a little I've written another one I kept both and I had

01:12:06.600 --> 01:12:11.960
[Guest]: tears in my eyes and then he said Sugata you're going to Hyderabad you're going to a very

01:12:11.960 --> 01:12:15.840
[Guest]: good university those days I think it was only JNU and HCU were the only two central

01:12:15.840 --> 01:12:21.520
[Guest]: universities said you're going to a good place and when you come back you know people should

01:12:21.520 --> 01:12:25.800
[Guest]: stand up and say call you professor Sugata and you know they should you know respect

01:12:25.800 --> 01:12:30.160
[Guest]: you so you should I want you to do well of course I mean by the time I came back he was

01:12:30.160 --> 01:12:37.120
[Guest]: gone so that was the kind of academic dream that my father put into me Adiga put into me

01:12:37.120 --> 01:12:42.600
[Guest]: my mother of course was dreaming of something else but then this is the kind of intellectual

01:12:42.600 --> 01:12:47.720
[Guest]: environment so I think I'll stop there and then probably wait for you to ask me the next

01:12:47.720 --> 01:12:48.720
[Amit Varma]: thing.

01:12:48.720 --> 01:12:54.360
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for these remarkably rich recollections I have like 15-20 things to double down on

01:12:54.360 --> 01:12:58.440
[Amit Varma]: I'll begin with this when you know when I first recorded with Ram Guha like this time

01:12:58.440 --> 01:13:01.720
[Amit Varma]: I recorded my fifth episode with him but when I first recorded with him I think it would

01:13:01.720 --> 01:13:07.520
[Amit Varma]: have been 2018 or so I forget the year we did a couple of episodes on Gandhi and I think

01:13:07.520 --> 01:13:11.760
[Amit Varma]: when we recorded the second of them he said you want to come with me in the evening I'll

01:13:11.760 --> 01:13:16.960
[Amit Varma]: be you know Rajmohan Gandhi's book on South India is being launched and I'll be chatting

01:13:16.960 --> 01:13:22.280
[Amit Varma]: with him and I said sure I'll come so in the evening I went and Ram and Rajmohan were having

01:13:22.280 --> 01:13:28.760
[Amit Varma]: a chat and it was like Shahrukh Khan and Amitabh Bachchan would have a chat in Bombay it was

01:13:28.760 --> 01:13:34.360
[Amit Varma]: that kind of crowd like I was blown away there was like standing room only it was completely

01:13:34.360 --> 01:13:39.560
[Amit Varma]: packed absolute pin drop silence when they were speaking incredible engagement from the

01:13:39.560 --> 01:13:43.760
[Amit Varma]: audience when the audience questions came about and I thought to myself that my god

01:13:43.760 --> 01:13:48.200
[Amit Varma]: if you had this in Mumbai you would have like four people and a dog show up right and not

01:13:48.200 --> 01:13:54.200
[Amit Varma]: a dog because you don't allow dogs indoors but it would be like that and that was kind

01:13:54.200 --> 01:14:00.240
[Amit Varma]: of my first exposure to sort of seeing this environment in Bangalore and subsequently

01:14:00.240 --> 01:14:04.040
[Amit Varma]: I have come here I like to tell people that you know Church Street is my favorite street

01:14:04.040 --> 01:14:08.040
[Amit Varma]: in the whole world because all these bookshops including the Blossoms and all that you know

01:14:08.040 --> 01:14:12.920
[Amit Varma]: I remember once when I was recording with Ram I told him that when I was leaving after

01:14:12.920 --> 01:14:15.920
[Amit Varma]: the recording he said where are you going I said I'm going to the best bookstore in

01:14:15.920 --> 01:14:21.000
[Amit Varma]: the world it's Blossoms he said you fool it is not even the best bookstore on Church Street

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:25.560
[Amit Varma]: right and he went bookworm and I'm kind of kidding and exaggerating but in fact this

01:14:25.560 --> 01:14:29.800
[Amit Varma]: time when I came he said have you visited the two best bookstores on Church Street but

01:14:29.800 --> 01:14:35.240
[Amit Varma]: I want to then ask you about this sort of intellectual culture this respect for the

01:14:35.240 --> 01:14:39.720
[Amit Varma]: intellect like you spoke about Herald giving you two pages for a piece on Derrida I can't

01:14:39.720 --> 01:14:44.520
[Amit Varma]: imagine a Mumbai newspaper doing that or you know I'm not sure maybe in Calcutta they would

01:14:44.520 --> 01:14:49.920
[Amit Varma]: but I don't think that would happen in Delhi either you know so on the one hand it's pretty

01:14:49.920 --> 01:14:53.720
[Amit Varma]: obvious that you were kind of lucky to be born into a family of the sort you were born

01:14:53.720 --> 01:14:59.280
[Amit Varma]: into with a father like that and therefore all his friends circle and all that but it's

01:14:59.280 --> 01:15:04.840
[Amit Varma]: you know Bangalore itself seems to have some of that so tell me a little bit about you

01:15:04.840 --> 01:15:10.560
[Amit Varma]: know am I over reading am I overthinking the intellectual culture of this place or you

01:15:10.560 --> 01:15:16.240
[Amit Varma]: know has it always been this way for you and does it create a kind of a vicious virtuous

01:15:16.240 --> 01:15:21.160
[Amit Varma]: cycle that once you have a culture like this it perpetuates itself younger people get drawn

01:15:21.160 --> 01:15:25.880
[Amit Varma]: to it and it grows and in some other place where there might be similarly smart and intelligent

01:15:25.880 --> 01:15:30.320
[Amit Varma]: people you don't have an ecosystem to begin with so no one gravitates towards it and that

01:15:30.320 --> 01:15:35.400
[Guest]: becomes a vicious circle so thank you Amit that's a very interesting question because

01:15:35.400 --> 01:15:41.320
[Guest]: you spoke about Ram Gohar and Rajmohan Gandhi's meeting see the one thing we need to realize

01:15:41.320 --> 01:15:47.640
[Guest]: is Bangalore has many such circles and you know there's not one but many and you're obviously

01:15:47.640 --> 01:15:54.960
[Guest]: referring to a English kind of an environment but there are many such Kannada environments

01:15:54.960 --> 01:16:00.480
[Guest]: and there are a lot of infighting between those things so it makes it far more interesting

01:16:00.480 --> 01:16:07.560
[Guest]: so at you know I mean the 70s or the 80s or the 90s or even in the early 2000s you know

01:16:07.560 --> 01:16:12.080
[Guest]: I mean if you went to the Senate Hall of the Bangalore University and there used to be

01:16:12.080 --> 01:16:17.960
[Guest]: these debates and people used to come prepared to tear somebody down you know I mean I still

01:16:17.960 --> 01:16:23.320
[Guest]: remember there was this some presentation on post-colonial theory or some Eliot or something

01:16:23.320 --> 01:16:27.880
[Guest]: was happening you know I mean I forget what it was but then Anant Murti was there in the

01:16:27.880 --> 01:16:31.880
[Guest]: audience and that used to be common you know I mean people used to come even if they are

01:16:31.880 --> 01:16:35.240
[Guest]: not speakers they would come they would sit down and they would raise questions and one

01:16:35.240 --> 01:16:39.520
[Guest]: of the speakers said you haven't even read the text why are you asking questions reading

01:16:39.520 --> 01:16:44.560
[Guest]: the blurb you know I mean that kind of combative thing you know you were exposed to that even

01:16:44.560 --> 01:16:52.160
[Guest]: as a young boy of in my ninth class D.R. Nagaraj actually sort of pulled down I mean of course

01:16:52.160 --> 01:16:57.840
[Guest]: pulled on this is on in a seminar hall you know he sort of you know accused another literary

01:16:57.840 --> 01:17:03.680
[Guest]: critic who was very close to our family of course I called him uncle and unfairly and

01:17:03.680 --> 01:17:08.520
[Guest]: so that was a three-day seminar on Adiga or something you know when I forget what it is

01:17:08.520 --> 01:17:13.200
[Guest]: it was at the MES college that much I remember and a lot of small little magazines record

01:17:13.200 --> 01:17:19.720
[Guest]: have recorded that episode so so there I mean I mean I was so disturbed I came back and

01:17:19.720 --> 01:17:25.840
[Guest]: I read the original essay and I thought that D.R. had completely misrepresented that whole

01:17:25.840 --> 01:17:31.080
[Guest]: thing so the next day morning I asked the chair who was presiding over that session

01:17:31.080 --> 01:17:35.600
[Guest]: and I said I have to sort of you know speak for two minutes I want to make a submission

01:17:35.600 --> 01:17:39.880
[Guest]: on what happened yesterday and this was extremely unfair because he was attacking him because

01:17:39.880 --> 01:17:45.000
[Guest]: D.R. those days was a Marxist whatever thing this man was more central and centrist and

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:48.680
[Guest]: whatever so there was this kind of ideological thing happening I didn't even realize all

01:17:48.680 --> 01:17:53.000
[Guest]: that you know I mean as I just wanted to defend someone whom I knew so I went promptly read

01:17:53.000 --> 01:17:58.240
[Guest]: up and I found that this man had misrepresented so I went up and I just said that this is

01:17:58.240 --> 01:18:03.400
[Guest]: what he quoted that is not there in the in the essay this is what he said that's also

01:18:03.400 --> 01:18:07.840
[Guest]: wrong and this is the third thing so I just wanted to it was kind of fact-checking of

01:18:07.840 --> 01:18:12.920
[Guest]: course the phrase fact-checking wasn't prevalent then you know I was just trying to counter

01:18:12.920 --> 01:18:19.920
[Guest]: so in the audience was this great man called his mentor of Girish Karnad who rewrote his

01:18:19.920 --> 01:18:25.640
[Guest]: plays initially helped him write his play as well he was from Dharwad he was an English

01:18:25.640 --> 01:18:31.560
[Guest]: professor who had taught in Gujarat and he had come back and retired there it is name

01:18:31.560 --> 01:18:37.000
[Guest]: is not coming and it'll come back so he was there in the audience and there was there

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:41.800
[Guest]: was another great writer so the moment I came down they just patted my back and they said

01:18:41.800 --> 01:18:48.440
[Guest]: taming of the shrew things like that so there were several such things and in Karnataka

01:18:48.440 --> 01:18:54.120
[Guest]: if you just go a little beyond Bangalore see Bangalore of course Gandhi Bazaar was one

01:18:54.120 --> 01:18:59.920
[Guest]: hub so I mean we don't even consider this side this side this was all later when crosswords

01:18:59.920 --> 01:19:06.160
[Guest]: and other big you know I mean bookshops came up that they started holding discussions on

01:19:06.160 --> 01:19:11.840
[Guest]: Bangalore for us this doesn't did not exist there was a iron wall between old Bangalore

01:19:11.840 --> 01:19:16.440
[Guest]: and Cantonment Bangalore so this was can't so we did not know the Koshy's you know we

01:19:16.440 --> 01:19:20.800
[Guest]: used to come to Koshy's because my great my maternal grandfather was a great fan of the

01:19:20.800 --> 01:19:25.480
[Guest]: chicken patties there so he used to bring us there but then otherwise you know this

01:19:25.480 --> 01:19:30.440
[Guest]: was a different world for us we didn't consider this part of Bangalore so for us it was Baswan

01:19:30.440 --> 01:19:38.280
[Guest]: Gudi one big hub then Gandhi Bazaar was a great thing then Jainagar, Maleshwaram so

01:19:38.280 --> 01:19:42.000
[Guest]: there were different hubs you know and different kinds of people congregated there and they

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:47.320
[Guest]: fought and they you know had drink at the end of the day and then they just left so

01:19:47.320 --> 01:19:52.800
[Guest]: there was this great Kannada critic called Kiram Nagaraj and he was you know I mean he

01:19:52.800 --> 01:19:57.640
[Guest]: had he would he was great on Bendre and he was great on all the old Kannada writers like

01:19:57.640 --> 01:20:02.800
[Guest]: Kumar Avyasa and all that and we learnt a lot of poetry from him and he would sort of

01:20:02.800 --> 01:20:07.120
[Guest]: you know and he enjoyed his drink so he would come a little inebriated and you know create

01:20:07.120 --> 01:20:12.240
[Guest]: ruckus in seminar halls and that was a great thing for youngsters like us okay okay Kiram

01:20:12.240 --> 01:20:17.920
[Guest]: is going to just screw this person today let's listen or he would you know get drunk and

01:20:17.920 --> 01:20:23.800
[Guest]: get very upset with people writing songs for the cassette industry in Kannada let's say

01:20:23.800 --> 01:20:29.320
[Guest]: you write a song for I mean it was canonical of course you know I mean now I understand

01:20:29.320 --> 01:20:34.040
[Guest]: that this is this is a kind of you know I mean canonical structure there is a hierarchy

01:20:34.040 --> 01:20:37.800
[Guest]: which is not correct and should not be looked at that way it is all something that came

01:20:37.800 --> 01:20:44.280
[Guest]: later but at that point he would say you write you were born you know in Karnataka where

01:20:44.280 --> 01:20:49.040
[Guest]: Narsimh Swami wrote or a Pampa wrote or a Kumar and you write this dirty song I will

01:20:49.040 --> 01:20:53.360
[Guest]: tear it apart and that fellow would have taught him for five years or six years in the university

01:20:53.360 --> 01:20:57.440
[Guest]: and he would just and everybody would take it in in their stride because he was such

01:20:57.440 --> 01:21:03.320
[Guest]: a genius and a marvelous character and those characters you know I mean were allowed today

01:21:03.320 --> 01:21:08.360
[Guest]: everything is you cannot have such characters you know I mean today you only the such characters

01:21:08.360 --> 01:21:13.160
[Guest]: are there only in the right wing thing where they come and disrupt but here you had liberal

01:21:13.160 --> 01:21:17.420
[Guest]: characters who would come and confront you on on your reading of poetry and my reading

01:21:17.420 --> 01:21:22.960
[Guest]: of poetry so in fact the one phrase that he taught me he had read Harold Bloom or something

01:21:22.960 --> 01:21:28.040
[Guest]: and he told me Sugata it's okay you completely misread a poem no problem it's called the

01:21:28.040 --> 01:21:34.600
[Guest]: map of misreading he said I think it was an essay by Harold Bloom or I mean was it Levis

01:21:34.600 --> 01:21:39.520
[Guest]: and I forget but then he came he was the first who told me that you don't worry you misread

01:21:39.520 --> 01:21:44.400
[Guest]: everything that is also very important and it's that misreading actually leads you to

01:21:44.400 --> 01:21:48.760
[Guest]: a different kind of reading so he was a very insightful man and one day when I was at the

01:21:48.760 --> 01:21:54.320
[Guest]: Hyderabad Central University there was a knock on my room and I opened and I see Kiran he

01:21:54.320 --> 01:21:59.240
[Guest]: has come and he said sir you didn't even tell me he said no I told your father he must have

01:21:59.240 --> 01:22:04.460
[Guest]: forgotten to write a letter to you so then I said so why have you come he said no first

01:22:04.460 --> 01:22:09.160
[Guest]: buy me coffee I heard that there is a nice coffee thing there let's go so we I bought

01:22:09.160 --> 01:22:14.720
[Guest]: him coffee and he said no I have come here looking for a book by Alfred B Lord it's called

01:22:14.720 --> 01:22:22.400
[Guest]: the singer of tales this is establishes conclusively it's like he is Alfred B Lord was Milton Parry

01:22:22.400 --> 01:22:27.760
[Guest]: and all these were one group of people looking at classical literature and it establishes

01:22:27.760 --> 01:22:35.200
[Guest]: that Homer's thing was a part of the oral culture it was not a written classic so I

01:22:35.200 --> 01:22:40.000
[Guest]: want to look at it I wanted to read that book that book I heard there's one copy in your

01:22:40.000 --> 01:22:44.560
[Guest]: Central University library it's not even available in JNU so can you get me that I'll photocopy

01:22:44.560 --> 01:22:48.480
[Guest]: leave by the evening bus my god so he had come there to just pick up that book then

01:22:48.480 --> 01:22:54.160
[Guest]: I was so happy and I had heard a new name of an author and I wanted to read it and then

01:22:54.160 --> 01:22:59.200
[Guest]: for me it gave me a new leg up right I could go to the classroom and say what are you talking

01:22:59.200 --> 01:23:04.120
[Guest]: about Odysseus or Homer or Iliad you know I mean this is all part of the oral culture

01:23:04.120 --> 01:23:08.520
[Guest]: it all got stringed up together and then at some point in history it got written it got

01:23:08.520 --> 01:23:12.600
[Guest]: published and then you now think it was a written work there is no authorship to that

01:23:12.600 --> 01:23:18.120
[Guest]: see Barth had argued about authorship so much about work and text and he was making a distinction

01:23:18.120 --> 01:23:23.400
[Guest]: between all of that so here I had this new let thing to go and say that come on you know

01:23:23.400 --> 01:23:28.680
[Guest]: I mean what are you talking you know so Kiram he used to be called Kiram so we used to pun

01:23:28.680 --> 01:23:34.920
[Guest]: on the word rum because he used to always be consumed by old monk right so he was so

01:23:34.920 --> 01:23:40.520
[Guest]: passionate about his poetry and his house was full of you know I mean papers and you

01:23:40.520 --> 01:23:46.160
[Guest]: know things thrown around and there was I mean I still remember reading the bathroom

01:23:46.160 --> 01:23:51.120
[Guest]: door open seeing him in bathroom door open he's sitting on the commode and reading you

01:23:51.120 --> 01:23:56.600
[Guest]: know Pampavartha Deepike which is an introduction to Pampavartha and you know that was the kind

01:23:56.600 --> 01:24:01.920
[Guest]: of image that he gave so there were a lot of such characters in Bangalore and Bangalore

01:24:01.920 --> 01:24:07.600
[Guest]: University was a great place it allowed it assembled a lot of good people there was K V

01:24:07.600 --> 01:24:12.600
[Guest]: Narayan was a great theoretician there was Kiram who was a genius and who never wrote

01:24:12.600 --> 01:24:20.520
[Guest]: a word but I mean was in Kannada we call it Thondi, oral you know I mean critic so he

01:24:20.520 --> 01:24:24.320
[Guest]: was there there was G. S. Shurudrappa who became the poet laureate and he was the head

01:24:24.320 --> 01:24:27.960
[Guest]: of the department he was keeping all these people together there was Siddalingaya who

01:24:27.960 --> 01:24:33.280
[Guest]: passed away a Dalit writer who had been brought in and there was Bhargur Ramchandra who was

01:24:33.280 --> 01:24:38.440
[Guest]: another stream of Kannada consciousness so there were different kinds of people they

01:24:38.440 --> 01:24:43.400
[Guest]: were all in the same department Kannada literature department and they were all looking in different

01:24:43.400 --> 01:24:48.000
[Guest]: directions they would come together to fight you know come together for some social whatever

01:24:48.000 --> 01:24:53.400
[Guest]: thing and then you know explored these ideas on you and I mean just throw it at you so

01:24:53.400 --> 01:24:57.440
[Guest]: that was the environment in Bangalore but if you stepped out of Bangalore there was

01:24:57.440 --> 01:25:03.840
[Guest]: Mysore again which is a great hub so you had the great man Kuvimpu sitting there you went

01:25:03.840 --> 01:25:08.680
[Guest]: to Bangalore the coast you had Karan sitting there and you went to Dharwad you had the

01:25:08.680 --> 01:25:13.640
[Guest]: great Bendre sitting there I don't know if you I mean for a non Kannada reader you

01:25:13.640 --> 01:25:20.520
[Guest]: should read the just is those two pages of Dom Morris's introduction on I mean Bendre

01:25:20.520 --> 01:25:25.840
[Guest]: where he says and this man this is a journey through Karnataka book that was commissioned

01:25:25.840 --> 01:25:30.120
[Guest]: by the government of Karnataka and Devraja was the chief minister in that he says this

01:25:30.120 --> 01:25:34.880
[Guest]: man goes there to meet a great poet who's one big non Pete and all that and he speaks

01:25:34.880 --> 01:25:40.080
[Guest]: to him only physics and numbers he's there with Leela Naidu his wife interviewing this

01:25:40.080 --> 01:25:45.200
[Guest]: great man and he confounds him you know confuses him completely is speaking only numbers asking

01:25:45.200 --> 01:25:49.600
[Guest]: for his date of birth and telling giving him some formulation and does not discuss poetry

01:25:49.600 --> 01:25:55.680
[Guest]: at the end of the day so there was that person and then there again these kind of fights

01:25:55.680 --> 01:26:01.040
[Guest]: were common there were three or four streets were one literary thought another three or

01:26:01.040 --> 01:26:05.600
[Guest]: four streets another so there was Shambha Joshi one of the finest minds that Karnataka

01:26:05.600 --> 01:26:09.960
[Guest]: and Kannada has seen was there and would not get along with this man and then there was

01:26:09.960 --> 01:26:15.680
[Guest]: Kal Burgi who was shot down because he was not he was not seen as in their league but

01:26:15.680 --> 01:26:20.720
[Guest]: then he was very important of course and then there was if you came to Hubli and I mean

01:26:20.720 --> 01:26:25.880
[Guest]: there were many more such things and then there was Gokhak of course VK Gokhak was a very important

01:26:25.880 --> 01:26:30.560
[Guest]: figure who became the who won the Gnanpeet of course but also became the chairman of

01:26:30.560 --> 01:26:36.120
[Guest]: the Central Sahitya Akademy and he was he had gone to Cambridge and he was from the

01:26:36.120 --> 01:26:41.320
[Guest]: time of Karnad and Karnad studied there if you so that was another intellectual hub but

01:26:41.320 --> 01:26:46.960
[Guest]: then that was the Bombay Karnataka region then there was the Hyderabad Karnataka region

01:26:46.960 --> 01:26:51.400
[Guest]: which was always you know presented this victimhood that we have been neglected our writing has

01:26:51.400 --> 01:26:56.840
