01:28:48.760 --> 01:28:54.280
[Guest]: is known to the world outside now and for very unfortunate reasons but then it is Lankesh

01:28:54.280 --> 01:28:59.440
[Guest]: who is more important for us so I mean there is Adiga who is more important than an Anantamurthy

01:28:59.440 --> 01:29:03.620
[Guest]: known to the Western world of course Ramanujan is equally respected that's a very strange

01:29:03.620 --> 01:29:08.400
[Guest]: thing because Ramanujan had his firm footing in Kannada he wrote extraordinarily he did

01:29:08.400 --> 01:29:13.200
[Guest]: extraordinarily good work in Kannada and then Tamil and then it was a genuine trilingual

01:29:13.200 --> 01:29:17.960
[Guest]: English and all of that so there were there were these kinds of very interesting fights

01:29:17.960 --> 01:29:25.280
[Guest]: and intellectual disagreements and things that were happening in Karnataka and being

01:29:25.280 --> 01:29:30.080
[Guest]: my father's son I was a witness to all of this so this this thing that you mentioned

01:29:30.080 --> 01:29:36.840
[Guest]: about Ramguha and Rajmohan Gandhi was a was something that was taking off in Bangalore

01:29:36.840 --> 01:29:42.400
[Guest]: which was a literary culture in English so that came to dominate in a different way through

01:29:42.400 --> 01:29:46.800
[Guest]: translations and others and now it's a very sad thing that you don't see those arguments

01:29:46.800 --> 01:29:51.800
[Guest]: anymore literally I wrote a piece it's part of my first book where I spoke of the death

01:29:51.800 --> 01:29:57.040
[Guest]: of Little Magazines and I spoke about how Little Magazines had just died in Kannada

01:29:57.040 --> 01:30:02.680
[Guest]: and why it had happened so why it so happened and that you know I mean they had lost team

01:30:02.680 --> 01:30:09.240
[Guest]: and then to shut shop and how they were run in fact I was I quote if I remember correctly

01:30:09.240 --> 01:30:14.000
[Guest]: I'm please pardon me if I'm wrong I quote from the obituary that was written in the

01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:19.760
[Guest]: Boston Globe for Plimpton the person who had started the Paris Review he had passed away

01:30:19.760 --> 01:30:26.400
[Guest]: I think around 2004 I mean I don't remember the date again I may be wrong so there the

01:30:26.400 --> 01:30:33.600
[Guest]: Little Magazines were described as showcases of you know I mean I forget the phrase also

01:30:33.600 --> 01:30:41.120
[Guest]: I mean it was beautifully described where the kind of fragile economic environment in

01:30:41.120 --> 01:30:48.240
[Guest]: which they always ran but had great amounts of passion and all of that so that is sort

01:30:48.240 --> 01:30:53.640
[Guest]: of gone now even your cultural heroes are different now in Karnataka and Bangalore your

01:30:53.640 --> 01:30:59.360
[Guest]: cultural heroes are people who have by default have become people who have or philanthropists

01:30:59.360 --> 01:31:05.160
[Guest]: who made money who have sort of you know I mean led IT industries so there are no longer

01:31:05.160 --> 01:31:09.240
[Guest]: people you know I mean Akiram cannot be a cultural hero and Adiga is nobody's cultural

01:31:09.240 --> 01:31:15.040
[Guest]: hero a Kuvempu I mean a stalwart I think he would have made any language feel great you

01:31:15.040 --> 01:31:22.920
[Guest]: know I mean he was I mean a remarkable mind he is I mean lost in some sense but I don't

01:31:22.920 --> 01:31:26.720
[Guest]: want to say lost because they'll all be recovered in different ways and I don't want to have

01:31:26.720 --> 01:31:30.640
[Guest]: this nostalgic kind of thing I don't want to live in the past and say that was great

01:31:30.640 --> 01:31:36.720
[Guest]: and today is bad but this is these are trends and phases that we are seeing where your heroes

01:31:36.720 --> 01:31:42.040
[Guest]: are dead you don't have heroes like you had then you know where you said okay this is

01:31:42.040 --> 01:31:46.200
[Guest]: this is a character this has to be nurtured is straight out of a novel so he probably

01:31:46.200 --> 01:31:50.680
[Guest]: will get into my novel you know you looked at it in a very fascinating you didn't judge

01:31:50.680 --> 01:31:56.360
[Guest]: there was a narrative that was always running in your head so you did not stop to judge

01:31:56.360 --> 01:32:00.680
[Guest]: so that was something that is something that I miss in Bangalore today today it's more

01:32:00.680 --> 01:32:05.400
[Guest]: corporatized even the book event is very corporatized even you know I mean I mean I have seen what

01:32:05.400 --> 01:32:09.720
[Guest]: has happened with my own book you know when you have to do it you know I mean it's a very

01:32:09.720 --> 01:32:14.080
[Guest]: kind of it's not organic you know people don't come and fight in the middle of the street

01:32:14.080 --> 01:32:17.120
[Guest]: and say you have written nonsense you know I would have loved that that doesn't happen

01:32:17.120 --> 01:32:22.520
[Guest]: you know and very carefully crafted whatsapp messages that come to you and they say oh

01:32:22.520 --> 01:32:28.840
[Guest]: it's good but you know I mean but this you're missing this oh I mean there was no such kind

01:32:28.840 --> 01:32:33.560
[Guest]: of holding back because there was people understood each other and people knew that at the end

01:32:33.560 --> 01:32:38.000
[Guest]: of the day you're not going to be an enemy of that person you can have a lifelong grudge

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:43.000
[Guest]: and that he said this but then you would always go back to it was a small culture you were

01:32:43.000 --> 01:32:48.400
[Guest]: interdependent and it was a feeling of community I think that is the word there was a sense

01:32:48.400 --> 01:32:54.120
[Guest]: of community and running a little magazine I write in that piece was like a cottage industry

01:32:54.120 --> 01:33:01.120
[Guest]: see my father used to edit he used to proofread but the book post wrap that would go around

01:33:01.120 --> 01:33:06.000
[Guest]: it was used to be done by my mother she would put the Gandhi stamp one rupee stamp or whatever

01:33:06.000 --> 01:33:10.840
[Guest]: at the edge and then they would both go you know taking this to the post office and mail

01:33:10.840 --> 01:33:15.640
[Guest]: it so that is that used to be a bimonthly activity that I was witnessed to as a child

01:33:15.640 --> 01:33:22.240
[Guest]: it started in 79 and shut shop in I think 91, 91 is very significant Indian economy

01:33:22.240 --> 01:33:28.760
[Guest]: got liberalized opened up at that time so that is that was the kind of and people did

01:33:28.760 --> 01:33:33.760
[Guest]: not worry about you know they're losing money or you know I mean oh this is an investment

01:33:33.760 --> 01:33:38.360
[Guest]: gone bad or this is an investment that will get you nothing you did it you know you had

01:33:38.360 --> 01:33:47.080
[Guest]: a higher purpose culture or this whole linguistic environment I mean you also need a small group

01:33:47.080 --> 01:33:51.040
[Guest]: which pushes you to do that you have to be supported in different ways you have to be

01:33:51.040 --> 01:33:55.320
[Guest]: told that you know I mean this is good this is great this is something which so I think

01:33:55.320 --> 01:34:00.600
[Guest]: everybody lost that at some point that disconnect started happening of course it will all get

01:34:00.600 --> 01:34:07.480
[Guest]: connected back in different ways but then that disruption did happen in with huge money

01:34:07.480 --> 01:34:12.720
[Guest]: with huge real estate booms in Bangalore and now we know what Kannada professors do in

01:34:12.720 --> 01:34:17.280
[Guest]: Kannada Karnataka's universities you know they all do side businesses you know of different

01:34:17.280 --> 01:34:22.760
[Guest]: kinds I don't think there is serious kind of work that is happening and at least you

01:34:22.760 --> 01:34:28.840
[Guest]: know I mean I mean I'm not really aware but of course there are pockets there are islands

01:34:28.840 --> 01:34:34.080
[Guest]: of good work there are there's still a lot of hope and you will reconstruct all of that

01:34:34.080 --> 01:34:40.200
[Guest]: in a in a different context at a later point is what I feel I think you're comparing what

01:34:40.200 --> 01:34:45.480
[Amit Varma]: is there now to the past you know well I compare it to the present in other places and I'm

01:34:45.480 --> 01:34:49.480
[Amit Varma]: like saying wow what a rich culture and even though I can only see one tiny part of it

01:34:49.480 --> 01:34:54.320
[Amit Varma]: the English elite kind of part of it so you know before I go back to some of the other

01:34:54.320 --> 01:34:58.840
[Amit Varma]: questions I you know have planned a slightly provocative question and this starts with

01:34:58.840 --> 01:35:05.480
[Amit Varma]: like a slight anecdote so you know there's there's a guy in Bangalore his name is Shakeel

01:35:05.480 --> 01:35:09.600
[Amit Varma]: I've never I haven't met him yet and he's a huge fan he's been a huge fan of the scene

01:35:09.600 --> 01:35:14.000
[Amit Varma]: and the unseen been writing to me for years listens to every episode take takes notes

01:35:14.000 --> 01:35:19.000
[Amit Varma]: did my writing course so for a while he was insistent that he wants to send me a gift

01:35:19.000 --> 01:35:23.560
[Amit Varma]: and I was like that no boss it's okay you don't need to send me a gift and he said that

01:35:23.560 --> 01:35:26.920
[Amit Varma]: no no let me send it to you or I'll have to give it to you when you come to Bangalore

01:35:26.920 --> 01:35:30.600
[Amit Varma]: he's he's in Bangalore and it's very heavy I don't know how you'll manage so give me

01:35:30.600 --> 01:35:35.600
[Amit Varma]: a postal address I will send it to you so finally I relented and said okay let's do

01:35:35.600 --> 01:35:41.000
[Amit Varma]: it so then two weeks later this big carton comes right and I open the carton and it's

01:35:41.000 --> 01:35:46.760
[Amit Varma]: full of books in Kannada right by one guy I've forgotten the name now so please forgive

01:35:46.760 --> 01:35:53.320
[Amit Varma]: me but I think it's poet but it's it's essays and poems and all of that by so and I don't

01:35:53.320 --> 01:35:58.560
[Amit Varma]: know Kannada right so I asked him that you know what's the deal so he said no Amit your

01:35:58.560 --> 01:36:02.720
[Amit Varma]: work means a lot to me and this other person his work means even more to me and I wanted

01:36:02.720 --> 01:36:07.360
[Amit Varma]: to introduce you to his work but there aren't translations and I'm hoping that you will

01:36:07.360 --> 01:36:12.360
[Amit Varma]: learn Kannada and read his books now it is a sad reality of our modern times that I may

01:36:12.360 --> 01:36:16.960
[Amit Varma]: not do that but having said that while I have you know while we moved house I gave away

01:36:16.960 --> 01:36:21.000
[Amit Varma]: a lot of my other books because I was in space I've kept the carton because the sentiment

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:28.280
[Amit Varma]: means something to me right but why I'm bringing it up here is that it shows that it shows

01:36:28.280 --> 01:36:34.240
[Amit Varma]: a deep passion for language and literature right and it strikes me as something that

01:36:34.240 --> 01:36:39.120
[Amit Varma]: I would expect more from someone in the south of India whether it is Karnataka or Tamil

01:36:39.120 --> 01:36:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Nadu or whatever than someone in the north I can't imagine and I don't mean to be harsh

01:36:44.240 --> 01:36:50.320
[Amit Varma]: but just in probabilistic terms it is far less likely that someone from a Patna or wherever

01:36:50.320 --> 01:36:56.000
[Amit Varma]: is going to sort of an apologies to all Patnaites I think I just got myself into trouble and

01:36:56.000 --> 01:37:01.160
[Amit Varma]: clearly from what we just discussed about the deep cultural sort of little neighborhoods

01:37:01.160 --> 01:37:07.120
[Amit Varma]: all over Karnataka and all of that there is this engagement with culture with language

01:37:07.120 --> 01:37:13.080
[Amit Varma]: with the arts in South India that is not so much there among the Amits as it were as Twitter

01:37:13.080 --> 01:37:18.840
[Amit Varma]: people would say because Amit has become a sort of a shorthand for North Indian buffoons

01:37:18.840 --> 01:37:24.520
[Amit Varma]: and sadly I have to bear that name so this is therefore a provocative question it just

01:37:24.520 --> 01:37:29.720
[Amit Varma]: struck me we have many more interesting things to talk about but I just wonder that don't

01:37:29.720 --> 01:37:33.640
[Amit Varma]: people like you sometimes look at what is happening in the rest of the country and you're

01:37:33.640 --> 01:37:40.920
[Amit Varma]: like why the hell have we been buffeted together with these you know uncouth morons you know

01:37:40.920 --> 01:37:45.040
[Amit Varma]: and it's incredible you know up there they have no idea of South India they think that

01:37:45.040 --> 01:37:48.960
[Amit Varma]: you know Hindi should be natural language and we have tolerated you and whatever and

01:37:48.960 --> 01:37:53.520
[Amit Varma]: all of that shit and they have that kind of attitude right and and they are of course

01:37:53.520 --> 01:37:59.000
[Amit Varma]: you know multiplying like rabbits while South India is chilling listening to good music

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:03.080
[Amit Varma]: watching good plays and which is not to say there aren't outliers in the north as well

01:38:03.080 --> 01:38:07.400
[Amit Varma]: but if I was in the south I would be like to hell with this shit and a question that

01:38:07.400 --> 01:38:14.120
[Amit Varma]: I've asked my guests in recent episodes also is that we often take the status quo for granted

01:38:14.120 --> 01:38:19.600
[Amit Varma]: in such a way that it seems like it is solidified it is granite and to me one of those concepts

01:38:19.600 --> 01:38:24.720
[Amit Varma]: is nation states lines on a map right where you look at the current nation state a lot

01:38:24.720 --> 01:38:29.920
[Amit Varma]: of it is happenstance right to me like a Delhi has much more in common with Lahore in a good

01:38:29.920 --> 01:38:35.920
[Amit Varma]: way than it does with Chennai for example you know a few years later we'll have the

01:38:35.920 --> 01:38:42.280
[Amit Varma]: delimitation problem coming up which can also be sort of something that and I can totally

01:38:42.280 --> 01:38:45.680
[Amit Varma]: and friends of mine joke about this that we should have the Republic of South India and

01:38:45.680 --> 01:38:51.440
[Amit Varma]: blah blah blah so yeah so it's just a it's not even a question per se it's just a provocative

01:38:51.440 --> 01:38:55.960
[Amit Varma]: thought but I wonder if you feel this way sometimes and that you know I mean I come

01:38:55.960 --> 01:38:59.680
[Amit Varma]: to Bangalore it feels like a different country in a sense I mean it's the same country and

01:38:59.680 --> 01:39:06.160
[Amit Varma]: I love the whole country but you know what are your thoughts it's very interesting that

01:39:06.160 --> 01:39:13.600
[Guest]: you say this but then I mean I've also been fairly acquainted with say through my father

01:39:13.600 --> 01:39:19.320
[Guest]: as well as later to with the kind of Lucknowi kind of literary environment or I we spoke

01:39:19.320 --> 01:39:22.960
[Guest]: about the Bengali literary environment you know people are very very passionate my father

01:39:22.960 --> 01:39:28.120
[Guest]: had great linkages with writers in Bengal and Abhinita Shendev you know I mean there's

01:39:28.120 --> 01:39:33.480
[Guest]: he there's a joint kind of travelogue that he writes with us I mean he's his part of

01:39:33.480 --> 01:39:38.040
[Guest]: the travel he's a character in that travelogue where they go to meet this lady and this great

01:39:38.040 --> 01:39:42.800
[Guest]: grand lady of Bengal and they don't know what to call her they come out of this thing and

01:39:42.800 --> 01:39:46.600
[Guest]: they call her lady Kiram the Kiram that I was referring to because she's so passionate

01:39:46.600 --> 01:39:51.680
[Guest]: about poetry and she's spoken to them so much about that so for me you know I mean I don't

01:39:51.680 --> 01:39:56.600
[Guest]: know if it is a problem with me but I was shown only these things the good things my

01:39:56.600 --> 01:40:01.360
[Guest]: father had a good relationship with Bisham Sahani so we still have a lot of letters exchanged

01:40:01.360 --> 01:40:05.160
[Guest]: between the two of them and I have a copy of Thomas which is signed for him and then

01:40:05.160 --> 01:40:10.040
[Guest]: he would so meticulously inquire after my grandmother's health and stuff like that you

01:40:10.040 --> 01:40:18.720
[Guest]: know I mean so so there was always these Kartar Singh Duggal another name so Bengal Lucknowi

01:40:18.720 --> 01:40:24.600
[Guest]: and even in Delhi if you mentioned the partition thing and then in Delhi I had we had rather

01:40:24.600 --> 01:40:29.640
[Guest]: the family had a Sharda Prasad who mentored me you know I mean and Sharda Prasad was such

01:40:29.640 --> 01:40:35.760
[Guest]: a cultured man who would host Malik Arjun Mansoor and Shivram Karanth and all these

01:40:35.760 --> 01:40:40.480
[Guest]: people who were dissenting against Indira Gandhi's emergency at his house you know

01:40:40.480 --> 01:40:44.520
[Guest]: and he was still part of the PMO so it was that contradiction he never thought that you

01:40:44.520 --> 01:40:49.320
[Guest]: know I mean he was compromised you know anything like that because Karanth used to stay with

01:40:49.320 --> 01:40:54.720
[Guest]: this man and Karanth he has translated Karanth's book you know I mean the autobiography and

01:40:54.720 --> 01:41:01.040
[Guest]: has a couple of novels and all of that and Sharda Prasad is extremely good and so we

01:41:01.040 --> 01:41:05.080
[Guest]: were always painted this I don't know if my father painted these romantic pictures for

01:41:05.080 --> 01:41:11.640
[Guest]: us so there was this problem until and unless I started writing seriously on say federalism

01:41:11.640 --> 01:41:18.840
[Guest]: or finance commissions and GST and looking at the federal issues between the south and

01:41:18.840 --> 01:41:23.760
[Guest]: the center and how the whole centralization problem operates and that's I've been writing

01:41:23.760 --> 01:41:29.440
[Guest]: a lot about it in my columns in the times these days on that so I now feel that you

01:41:29.440 --> 01:41:33.680
[Guest]: know I mean feel more strongly that we are a union of states and there's less common

01:41:33.680 --> 01:41:39.040
[Guest]: but even having said that and I think I should also sort of add this caveat which is see

01:41:39.040 --> 01:41:44.200
[Guest]: you had a Andhra Pradesh right a united Andhra Pradesh and it was the one of the first linguistic

01:41:44.200 --> 01:41:49.760
[Guest]: states that was created after Poteshwar Ramlu started protesting and he has he dies and

01:41:49.760 --> 01:41:54.680
[Guest]: all that but look at what happened with Andhra Pradesh there was a cultural kind of breakage

01:41:54.680 --> 01:41:59.040
[Guest]: so the Telangana culture was different and the Andhra culture was different and when

01:41:59.040 --> 01:42:02.680
[Guest]: we were growing up you know when there was this pride injected about Kannada because

01:42:02.680 --> 01:42:07.040
[Guest]: Kannada had got so many Gnanpeeths so we thought that Telugu was a lesser thing or a Tamil

01:42:07.040 --> 01:42:11.560
[Guest]: was a lesser thing but that was not the case but then you know I mean you always sort of

01:42:11.560 --> 01:42:18.800
[Guest]: you were allowed to go on a certain highway or a certain path and you only saw these kind

01:42:18.800 --> 01:42:24.680
[Guest]: of markers so I may not be a fair judge of you know what what happens in a Patna thing

01:42:24.680 --> 01:42:32.000
[Guest]: or other places because I was not exposed to that but my political writing later took

01:42:32.000 --> 01:42:37.640
[Guest]: me to you know cover elections and all that then I saw that these places were you know

01:42:37.640 --> 01:42:41.400
[Guest]: what's wrong with these places why aren't they developed if you go to Hassan I write

01:42:41.400 --> 01:42:47.480
[Guest]: about it in 2009 much much before I even dreamt of writing a book on Deve Gowda that it's

01:42:47.480 --> 01:42:52.680
[Guest]: an island of some kind of a great development because Deve Gowda had everything going in

01:42:52.680 --> 01:42:58.080
[Guest]: that thing you know every scheme every central scheme the highways the roads you know you

01:42:58.080 --> 01:43:03.440
[Guest]: know I mean fantastic development in that place but if you go to say a Rai Bareilly

01:43:03.440 --> 01:43:07.840
[Guest]: or an Amethi you know you you feel like crying as to what is it that these people have done

01:43:07.840 --> 01:43:12.560
[Guest]: why is it that they have been showered with so much of affection by these people continuously

01:43:12.560 --> 01:43:18.800
[Guest]: you go to a filibit where Nehru used to contest his election you know everything looks completely

01:43:18.800 --> 01:43:25.840
[Guest]: dilapidated and dismantled and nothing seems to be working you know I mean but in Karnataka

01:43:25.840 --> 01:43:31.520
[Guest]: that was when I started making that it was not cultural see culturally you still got

01:43:31.520 --> 01:43:36.840
[Guest]: you you you sort of entered into something through a text or through a person or through

01:43:36.840 --> 01:43:42.400
[Guest]: a song right so Urdu for example I was so fascinated by Urdu at some point I wanted

01:43:42.400 --> 01:43:48.080
[Guest]: to learn to write and read Urdu but it never happened but then all my Urdu came through

01:43:48.080 --> 01:43:53.880
[Guest]: the Hindi films so this 60s and the 70s and the great lyricists and I was obsessed with

01:43:53.880 --> 01:44:00.320
[Guest]: the Hindi film music and now I have Mr. Chiranjeev Singh you know whom I call up the great bureaucrat

