01:44:06.080 --> 01:44:10.080
[Guest]: and I just call him up and I ask him sir why don't you explain this to me he can I ask

01:44:10.080 --> 01:44:15.760
[Guest]: him about Bengali poetry ask him what Urdu poetry I ask him about Punjabi poetry he himself

01:44:15.760 --> 01:44:21.800
[Guest]: writes Punjabi poetry and he's so kind to explain all of that to me so I mean these

01:44:21.800 --> 01:44:27.520
[Guest]: things were happening so you you enter through text and there is this politics which you

01:44:27.520 --> 01:44:32.440
[Guest]: enter through experience and you're you know you're sort of seeing it there happen so these

01:44:32.440 --> 01:44:38.440
[Guest]: two were different worlds for me when I was shocked when I started writing for outlook

01:44:38.440 --> 01:44:45.160
[Guest]: say on on these states and all that and but this this cultural thing never came up to

01:44:45.160 --> 01:44:50.480
[Guest]: me because I thought that that is still relevant that is still sort of their subsumed subterranean

01:44:50.480 --> 01:44:55.760
[Guest]: and it does not manifest itself in popular culture the way we need to but but we should

01:44:55.760 --> 01:45:00.760
[Guest]: also recognize that Hindi films probably sort of finished off all of this right because

01:45:00.760 --> 01:45:05.720
[Guest]: you know it was such a dominant thing in the north that it finished everything but in Canada

01:45:05.720 --> 01:45:12.840
[Guest]: or Telugu or Tamil I think there was still a bit of literary export into into films one

01:45:12.840 --> 01:45:18.240
[Guest]: of the great literary influences my father had was his uncle who was a bank manager and

01:45:18.240 --> 01:45:22.720
[Guest]: he was a great literary influence because he was the first reader of one of Karnataka's

01:45:22.720 --> 01:45:29.320
[Guest]: great Canada's great novelists Tarasu Tarasu Barao and Tarasu Barao wrote historical novels

01:45:29.320 --> 01:45:36.680
[Guest]: size which I mean huge novels and many of those were made into movies for Rajkumar right

01:45:36.680 --> 01:45:42.000
[Guest]: so so there was a lot of this that we were exposed to and not exposed to the other side

01:45:42.000 --> 01:45:47.640
[Guest]: but I became a very serious political writer only after I think went to Hindustan times

01:45:47.640 --> 01:45:52.000
[Guest]: I because I had it was by force that I had to look at different kind of material and

01:45:52.000 --> 01:45:57.600
[Guest]: even there you know you when I when I went to Jaipur to be an editor I used to go and

01:45:57.600 --> 01:46:03.560
[Guest]: create my own little you know I mean comfort zone of culture and literature with the writers

01:46:03.560 --> 01:46:09.280
[Guest]: there and with oral historians and and think that that is there that is the soul of that

01:46:09.280 --> 01:46:13.280
[Guest]: place and this is there of course there is Gaylord there is Bhairav Singh Shekawat whom

01:46:13.280 --> 01:46:18.600
[Guest]: you have to deal with for your pet ka sawal hai, theek hai likh lenge isme kya but then

01:46:18.600 --> 01:46:23.240
[Guest]: you all also bought the experience you also took the experience of your literary and cultural

01:46:23.240 --> 01:46:28.560
[Guest]: thing there and started looking at them as characters and so Bhairav Singh Shekawat was

01:46:28.560 --> 01:46:32.840
[Guest]: to used to be very fond of me used to be very nice to me in fact you know I mean even before

01:46:32.840 --> 01:46:36.720
[Guest]: he became the vice president of India used to lock up the latch up the door and used

01:46:36.720 --> 01:46:42.160
[Guest]: to give me a single small peg of black label or whatever whiskey I mean I've had whiskey

01:46:42.160 --> 01:46:47.720
[Guest]: with Bhairav Singh Shekawat and the age difference must have been you know me say 50-60 years

01:46:47.720 --> 01:46:52.920
[Guest]: you know you don't know so he was very very great and he liked me because I came from

01:46:52.920 --> 01:46:57.600
[Guest]: again very interesting he liked me because I came from Karnataka he liked me because

01:46:57.600 --> 01:47:04.440
[Guest]: I was somewhat related to Devraj Aras and Devraj Aras whom he saw as a great administrator

01:47:04.440 --> 01:47:11.040
[Guest]: statesman and all that and and a person who had revolutionized you know political thinking

01:47:11.040 --> 01:47:16.880
[Guest]: and all of that so so there were lots of these connections so then he was nice and then you

01:47:16.880 --> 01:47:21.000
[Guest]: you sort of started looking at these people for what they were but then there was other

01:47:21.000 --> 01:47:25.440
[Guest]: there was politics of course so that made my copy interesting so I used to sort of bring

01:47:25.440 --> 01:47:31.720
[Guest]: in this little insight about the man who newspapers would be rubbishing as you know I mean oh

01:47:31.720 --> 01:47:36.200
[Guest]: he's sold out or whatever this is but then there was this little thing about the man

01:47:36.200 --> 01:47:41.640
[Guest]: which would sort of come into my copy which would sort of give my copy a bit of a extra

01:47:41.640 --> 01:47:48.360
[Guest]: sparkle which made my copies more humane and then I used to sort of look at them not to

01:47:48.360 --> 01:47:52.600
[Guest]: judge them I used to look at them to sort of understand them and that's something that

01:47:52.600 --> 01:47:58.200
[Guest]: I got from my very early literary training and my father was someone like that who would

01:47:58.200 --> 01:48:03.760
[Guest]: listen even to this day he's mythologized you know in Kannada memoirs and a lot of people

01:48:03.760 --> 01:48:09.600
[Guest]: have written about how they used to come sit in front of him talk for hours he would not

01:48:09.600 --> 01:48:13.640
[Guest]: just speak anything and then they would just leave that's it and they would feel happy

01:48:13.640 --> 01:48:18.920
[Guest]: after that so that was the kind of person my father was I am not so reticent as him

01:48:18.920 --> 01:48:23.640
[Guest]: you know I'm I was my mother used to call me you know punning or the word Churchill

01:48:23.640 --> 01:48:28.960
[Guest]: Churchill in church in Kannada is debating so she would say you're a Churchill so you

01:48:28.960 --> 01:48:33.440
[Guest]: always you know you know get into an argument about something or the other so but my father

01:48:33.440 --> 01:48:38.560
[Guest]: was not like that but that but that that you quietly absorbed that and that came into my

01:48:38.560 --> 01:48:44.120
[Guest]: political writing also which did not make me did not sort of make me feel that I was

01:48:44.120 --> 01:48:48.960
[Guest]: doing something else completely divorced from my cultural reading or literary reading or

01:48:48.960 --> 01:48:54.000
[Guest]: whatever because when I I took all of that into my political thing so when I sat with

01:48:54.000 --> 01:49:00.000
[Guest]: these big people and I still remember Shekhar was telling me he came back from Delhi that

01:49:00.000 --> 01:49:04.680
[Guest]: evening and then he telephoned he said Bhaisahab kya kar rahe hain a jaaye hain you know and

01:49:04.680 --> 01:49:09.480
[Guest]: then I went and had good food and he spoke about his son-in-law and some unhappiness

01:49:09.480 --> 01:49:16.120
[Guest]: and all that in the family and then he said you know what I did today I went and had lunch

01:49:16.120 --> 01:49:23.640
[Guest]: with Advani I said why did you do that he said no I want to sort of make Vajpayee very

01:49:23.640 --> 01:49:28.440
[Guest]: alert about it you know Vajpayee is ignoring me so I just want want him to know that I've

01:49:28.440 --> 01:49:34.000
[Guest]: had lunch with Advani and then I said were you successful he said ha by the time I was

01:49:34.000 --> 01:49:39.520
[Guest]: leaving I got a call so Vajpayee called me he said what are you doing what were you doing

01:49:39.520 --> 01:49:44.440
[Guest]: there why are you doing this to me come let's have a chat so then they had broached the

01:49:44.440 --> 01:49:48.800
[Guest]: issue of becoming he becoming the vice-president so so I mean he used to he used to be such

01:49:48.800 --> 01:49:55.520
[Guest]: a he used to just disarm you by sharing things which you thought was was you know I mean

01:49:55.520 --> 01:50:02.360
[Guest]: high intrigue or whatever he said this is human see he would he would make if Vajpayee

01:50:02.360 --> 01:50:07.680
[Guest]: was human Advani was human and Shekhawat was human and then they would sort of you know

01:50:07.680 --> 01:50:11.960
[Guest]: that those jealousies or those kind of dynamics between them he would sort of share it in

01:50:11.960 --> 01:50:17.320
[Guest]: a very interesting fashion and then he said I just had to go to Advani's house for lunch

01:50:17.320 --> 01:50:22.480
[Guest]: to sort of get the antenna up there and Vajpayee's house and Vajpayee came to know of it obviously

01:50:22.480 --> 01:50:27.000
[Guest]: so he called me and then of course we broached this whole thing so I may be the vice-president

01:50:27.000 --> 01:50:31.320
[Guest]: of India so this was how he revealed to me that he would he may be the vice-president

01:50:31.320 --> 01:50:38.000
[Guest]: of India I was in Jaipur at that time so so political writing too for me was an extension

01:50:38.000 --> 01:50:43.640
[Guest]: of my cultural understanding of things I mean it was a it was a it was very important for

01:50:43.640 --> 01:50:48.760
[Guest]: me not to look at it as data so that is the reason why I keep sort of saying that you

01:50:48.760 --> 01:50:55.440
[Guest]: know people who really don't want to sort of speak about politics hide behind data because

01:50:55.440 --> 01:50:59.080
[Guest]: good political writing for me is of course data is there it's very very important it's

01:50:59.080 --> 01:51:05.320
[Guest]: it's extremely important to read it very carefully but then it's both a mix of emotion and reason

01:51:05.320 --> 01:51:10.040
[Guest]: because politics is full of emotion it is not reason alone you cannot sort of say why

01:51:10.040 --> 01:51:15.440
[Guest]: Devya Gowda did this or did not do this or why he goes to his temple so often I mean

01:51:15.440 --> 01:51:20.960
[Guest]: why did you know in Shekhawat sort of do this so I mean this is something that I have not

01:51:20.960 --> 01:51:27.920
[Guest]: been able to sort of effectively pass on to say the generation after me to tell them that

01:51:27.920 --> 01:51:35.520
[Guest]: see don't your graphs and your data is all very important but that does not say much

01:51:35.520 --> 01:51:39.160
[Guest]: about the person but if you want to write about the person you have to spend time with

01:51:39.160 --> 01:51:45.680
[Guest]: him look at him a little with critical sympathy is a phrase that my other guru the great guru

01:51:45.680 --> 01:51:50.560
[Guest]: who would change me after I went to England was Jeremy Seabrook was the one who used it

01:51:50.560 --> 01:51:55.680
[Guest]: first and he has used it for my book as well which makes me very proud so so critical sympathy

01:51:55.680 --> 01:52:00.720
[Guest]: you know you can you can be critical you know because all these seminars that and the conferences

01:52:00.720 --> 01:52:04.600
[Guest]: that I used to go where people used to you know I mean tear each other apart and then

01:52:04.600 --> 01:52:08.240
[Guest]: be having a whiskey at the end of the day or a rum at the end of the day it was all

01:52:08.240 --> 01:52:13.260
[Guest]: natural to me I mean for me it did not sort of make me look at this this thing as a black

01:52:13.260 --> 01:52:18.240
[Guest]: and white thing or a confrontationalist thing yes it's right as part of a culture it is

01:52:18.240 --> 01:52:23.560
[Guest]: a culture so when politicians you know I mean just shoot away in the on the floor of the

01:52:23.560 --> 01:52:28.080
[Guest]: house you know call names and then they're having a nice chat it does not surprise me

01:52:28.080 --> 01:52:32.880
[Guest]: because you know I mean it's I've seen that happen elsewhere in a different setting so

01:52:32.880 --> 01:52:36.680
[Guest]: I mean they're human beings you know I mean primarily I think we don't look at our politicians

01:52:36.680 --> 01:52:41.600
[Guest]: as human beings we seem to look at them as power you know filled with power some instruments

01:52:41.600 --> 01:52:45.800
[Guest]: of power which which they are not actually they are very humane they can be very humane

01:52:45.800 --> 01:52:50.000
[Guest]: they can be very cruel and that cruelty is also part of you know I mean you'll observe

01:52:50.000 --> 01:52:55.440
[Guest]: that cruelty much more only if you are willing to go beyond your data and sort of look at

01:52:55.440 --> 01:53:03.200
[Guest]: them interestingly so so for me it is I mean the silos that you spoke about does not really

01:53:03.200 --> 01:53:09.800
[Guest]: operate in in those ways it's it's a one continuous thing for me I take this with me there so

01:53:09.800 --> 01:53:14.640
[Guest]: therefore I see that there and then when I don't see that there I try to reason it out

01:53:14.640 --> 01:53:21.600
[Guest]: in a completely different way so so but but this whole Republic thing of South as a that

01:53:21.600 --> 01:53:27.600
[Guest]: South should succeed kind of a thing I don't want to create a controversy but but you know

01:53:27.600 --> 01:53:33.040
[Guest]: I mean India is a union of states what Rahul Gandhi said was correct in the parliament

01:53:33.040 --> 01:53:41.840
[Guest]: I wrote a column on that yeah you've you mean trying to create you know manufacture a nation

01:53:41.840 --> 01:53:47.920
[Guest]: with so much of diversity and so much of you know I mean dissonance and whatever it's it's

01:53:47.920 --> 01:53:53.640
[Guest]: it's a very false idea right you cannot you cannot you know in any it's inconceivable

01:53:53.640 --> 01:53:59.520
[Guest]: to sort of think that everything is flat you know to say one nation to say one you know

01:53:59.520 --> 01:54:05.160
[Guest]: religion one language it's a it's it's utmost stupidity to sort of speak of that and if

01:54:05.160 --> 01:54:09.400
[Guest]: somebody is trying to do that they're actually should be you know I mean they're they're

01:54:09.400 --> 01:54:13.280
[Guest]: actually trying to break up this nation you know they are accusing others of breaking

01:54:13.280 --> 01:54:17.640
[Guest]: up this nation actually the ones who speak of oneness are the ones who are to be charged

01:54:17.640 --> 01:54:23.640
[Guest]: with the the severest of sedition you know laws because they are the ones who are actually

01:54:23.640 --> 01:54:29.440
[Guest]: trying to break this whole thing up because if you don't allow this nation to exist the

01:54:29.440 --> 01:54:36.040
[Guest]: way it has been knit now loosely for whatever you know in some destiny of this nation you

01:54:36.040 --> 01:54:41.280
[Guest]: know when has put it together in this form if you want to retain it if you're serious

01:54:41.280 --> 01:54:46.120
[Guest]: about retaining this this whole nation in this form and it's in the same contours that

01:54:46.120 --> 01:54:52.120
[Guest]: it is in now I don't think you can impose I mean anything on this nation forget about

01:54:52.120 --> 01:54:56.840
[Guest]: doing it in the south you can't do it even in the Kashmir you can't do it in Bengal you

01:54:56.840 --> 01:55:01.920
[Guest]: can't do it you've seen reaction to the whole thing now this whole federal argument is coming

01:55:01.920 --> 01:55:06.800
[Guest]: back I'm very happy it's coming back because in 2018 I was a loner when I used to speak

01:55:06.800 --> 01:55:11.840
[Guest]: about it even Stalin was not back in power Stalin was not interested to listen to these

01:55:11.840 --> 01:55:17.040
[Guest]: arguments so federalism argument is coming back for me cultural federalism is more important

01:55:17.040 --> 01:55:23.000
[Guest]: than political federalism I think they have to move a step further so the Tamils try to

01:55:23.000 --> 01:55:27.680
[Guest]: make the Dravidian thing their cause but you know I mean if they are to argue for the Dravidian

01:55:27.680 --> 01:55:32.960
[Guest]: cause they have to actually be more inclusive they have to look at Andhra, Telangana, Karnataka,

01:55:32.960 --> 01:55:38.280
[Guest]: Kerala far more inclusively so it the Tamil exclusive idea is also not going to serve

01:55:38.280 --> 01:55:42.080
[Guest]: them well which they don't seem to realize at this point of time because you know the

01:55:42.080 --> 01:55:49.080
[Guest]: Dravidian thing has been completely captured I mean this is seen as a kind of their idea

01:55:49.080 --> 01:55:53.800
[Guest]: their thing their civil if it's a civilizational thing it can't be just yours so if you are

01:55:53.800 --> 01:55:59.000
[Guest]: using that to confront the north if you are using your the alternate epics that you have

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:02.800
[Guest]: to confront the north and try to say that we are a different country I mean there are

01:56:02.800 --> 01:56:07.440
[Guest]: fascinating I don't know Amit if you have had this chance to see fascinating debates

01:56:07.440 --> 01:56:13.520
[Guest]: in Rajya Sabha in the 60s when Anna Durai was a Rajya Sabha member brilliant speeches

01:56:13.520 --> 01:56:18.160
[Guest]: on this whole thing and you could speak about you know breaking away from India until 65

01:56:18.160 --> 01:56:24.320
[Guest]: I think this whole idea was different so brilliant speeches you know and he makes a cultural

01:56:24.320 --> 01:56:31.360
[Guest]: argument and even if you look at forget Rajya Sabha even if you look at the assembly Karnataka

01:56:31.360 --> 01:56:39.720
[Guest]: unification debates it's fascinating A.H. Ram his name was Ramchandra Rao I think Devagoda's

01:56:39.720 --> 01:56:45.600
[Guest]: mentor in Hassan he was the education minister he has a three-hour speech where he speaks

01:56:45.600 --> 01:56:51.120
[Guest]: about cultural differences and why Mysore should not integrate with the rest of Kannada

01:56:51.120 --> 01:56:55.800
[Guest]: speak is this on YouTube or something no it's you know just from the 50s yeah so it's it

01:56:55.800 --> 01:57:01.000
[Guest]: can't be there it's there is a it's an official record of the Karnataka legislature assembly

01:57:01.000 --> 01:57:05.360
[Guest]: it was those days it used to be called the Mysore legislature assembly you had you renamed

01:57:05.360 --> 01:57:11.440
[Guest]: only in 73 so it became Karnataka in 73 so you those debates are fascinating and you

01:57:11.440 --> 01:57:17.480
[Guest]: are not on you don't want there was a huge resistance to Mysore integrating with rest

01:57:17.480 --> 01:57:21.120
[Guest]: of Karnataka because they were impoverished area they were this would it would bring down

01:57:21.120 --> 01:57:29.160
[Guest]: the GDP of Mysore right so they didn't want that and as a result culturally Mysore dominated

01:57:29.160 --> 01:57:35.880
[Guest]: the rest of Karnataka culturally political power has shifted but culturally because the

01:57:35.880 --> 01:57:40.400
[Guest]: standard dialect that you use in Kannada today is a dialect that was spoken in Mysore so

01:57:40.400 --> 01:57:45.760
[Guest]: that became the standard thing that became your textbook language so the others who sacrificed

01:57:45.760 --> 01:57:50.960
[Guest]: because they were all fringes of other linguistic states so they were desperate more than the

01:57:50.960 --> 01:57:57.920
[Guest]: Mysoreans to become part of Karnataka so they gave up their dual identities they surrendered

01:57:57.920 --> 01:58:02.840
[Guest]: their Marathi there's there they surrendered their Urdu they're surrendered their Dakhani

01:58:02.840 --> 01:58:08.720
[Guest]: and Telugu Tamil everything and they became part of Karnataka and wanted to be identified

01:58:08.720 --> 01:58:15.440
[Guest]: with a Kannada state and now you see the kind of you know I mean rumblings that there are

01:58:15.440 --> 01:58:20.320
[Guest]: that people are not at all happy this this whole thing is this after the Telangana's

01:58:20.320 --> 01:58:25.520
[Guest]: formation I think it has become even more sharper where people say development is one

01:58:25.520 --> 01:58:32.080
[Guest]: part not giving enough funds for development is one part but the cultural differences the

01:58:32.080 --> 01:58:36.120
[Guest]: you know the kind of characters in Kannada movies you if you I mean since you don't see

01:58:36.120 --> 01:58:43.560
[Guest]: Kannada movies you may not realize this all the guys who are cooks who play the role of

01:58:43.560 --> 01:58:48.040
[Guest]: characters of cooks or whatever they're all from coastal Karnataka so they're not given

01:58:48.040 --> 01:58:56.120
[Guest]: the lead role then the jesters and the comedians and all of them speak a certain kind of Hyderabad

01:58:56.120 --> 01:59:01.960
[Guest]: sorry Darwad Hubli Darwad kind of Kannada which is very you know I mean it's not very

01:59:01.960 --> 01:59:08.160
[Guest]: smooth it's like the East Godavari Telugu and the Telangana Telugu it's very rough edges

01:59:08.160 --> 01:59:12.920
[Guest]: are more in the Telangana thing they have rough edges they come across as very very

01:59:12.920 --> 01:59:19.240
[Guest]: you know I mean it sounds very harsh the language sounds very harsh so but they're not people

01:59:19.240 --> 01:59:23.880
[Guest]: like that they're see it's their expression is like that they've spoken like that for

01:59:23.880 --> 01:59:28.720
[Guest]: centuries but you know I mean the Mysoreans look at it take a take offense to that kind

01:59:28.720 --> 01:59:34.840
[Guest]: of a usage in fact I was on a train recently to Goa and I was looking at I mean because

01:59:34.840 --> 01:59:42.120
[Guest]: I I mean I as there was a family which was sitting and they were using the word Gussa

01:59:42.120 --> 01:59:47.680
[Guest]: so beautifully in Kannada you know in their Kannada sentence so she that lady who was

01:59:47.680 --> 01:59:52.480
[Guest]: you know I mean sitting family and this little kid and she was telling me how this girl gets

01:59:52.480 --> 01:59:58.320
[Guest]: Gussa and she was putting it in Kannada you know I mean and then repeatedly I didn't want

01:59:58.320 --> 02:00:02.720
[Guest]: to make her conscious tell me how it sounded I mean even if I don't understand this girl

02:00:02.720 --> 02:00:09.840
[Guest]: is very angry see I mean you see and I instantly could understand that they had come from the

02:00:09.840 --> 02:00:13.880
[Guest]: Hyderabad Karnataka region and they had settled in Bangalore and they were going to go for

02:00:13.880 --> 02:00:20.480
[Guest]: a trip and similarly if you go towards Kolar and KGF and all that the Telugu you know Telugu

02:00:20.480 --> 02:00:25.040
[Guest]: is another language but that you know I was very familiar because my father was very familiar

02:00:25.040 --> 02:00:31.160
[Guest]: with Telugu and he studied in Chikbalapur because his aunt was widowed and my grandfather

02:00:31.160 --> 02:00:36.060
[Guest]: had a I mean transferable job so they kept the children in one place so that they could

02:00:36.060 --> 02:00:40.680
[Guest]: go and study there and all that so he had he says Telugu was extremely good he could

02:00:40.680 --> 02:00:46.880
[Guest]: read and write Telugu so if you go to those regions you go to Kolar, Chikbalapur, Chikbalapur

02:00:46.880 --> 02:00:51.640
[Guest]: is now a separate district but was part of undivided Kolar district so if you go there

02:00:51.640 --> 02:01:00.400
[Guest]: Telugu is a street language if you go to Mangalore you have Tulu, you have Biari, you have Konkani

02:01:00.400 --> 02:01:07.560
[Guest]: and then you have Kannada so I mean none of the Karnataka see Karnataka is not a state

02:01:07.560 --> 02:01:13.960
[Guest]: which wears its chauvinism on its sleeves like a Tamil or a Malayali whatever thing

02:01:13.960 --> 02:01:19.480
[Guest]: happens not so much Malayalam but they don't because you know when there are only three

02:01:19.480 --> 02:01:26.720
[Guest]: or four hardcore Kannada districts rest of them are all bilingual or trilingual areas

02:01:26.720 --> 02:01:31.560
[Guest]: the street market language is different from your kitchen language the language that you

02:01:31.560 --> 02:01:36.200
[Guest]: use in your kitchen to converse with your family is your mother tongue or whatever and

02:01:36.200 --> 02:01:41.400
[Guest]: then you come to the street and you speak say Tulu if you're in Mangalore and then if

02:01:41.400 --> 02:01:46.640
[Guest]: you're if you're you know into trade or whatever you use Biari because it's the Muslim traders

