[Amit Varma]: book with Deve Gowda and maybe we'll get to it at some point and maybe we won't because

02:08:54.080 --> 02:08:58.640
[Amit Varma]: I'm thoroughly enjoying this conversation and this trip you're taking me you know through

02:08:58.640 --> 02:09:03.520
[Amit Varma]: your life and through your times and all of that my next question actually comes out of

02:09:03.520 --> 02:09:08.160
[Amit Varma]: something two of the guests I've recorded with earlier this week I've mentioned and

02:09:08.160 --> 02:09:14.200
[Amit Varma]: one Ram Guha was talking about this classic essay he wrote the death of the bilingual

02:09:14.200 --> 02:09:18.600
[Amit Varma]: intellectual where he lamented that once upon a time they used to be bilingual intellectuals

02:09:18.600 --> 02:09:23.400
[Amit Varma]: and now they're not and it's a loss and Akar Patel when I mentioned to him that I'd be

02:09:23.400 --> 02:09:30.140
[Amit Varma]: chatting with you he said oh Sugata is a true bilingual person right and and that's actually

02:09:30.140 --> 02:09:35.720
[Amit Varma]: something that I envy and feel as a loss in the sense that I am multilingual in the sense

02:09:35.720 --> 02:09:41.240
[Amit Varma]: I can speak and understand multiple Indian languages but there is only one language really

02:09:41.240 --> 02:09:45.240
[Amit Varma]: in which I consume art and in which I can express myself which of course is English

02:09:45.240 --> 02:09:50.520
[Amit Varma]: which I'll consider an Indian language but it is just one language and I feel that loss

02:09:50.520 --> 02:09:56.080
[Amit Varma]: more and more when I speak to people like you or Mrinal Pandey or Sarah Rai or others

02:09:56.080 --> 02:10:01.200
[Amit Varma]: who've been on the show and they talk about and there's so much richness all around me

02:10:01.200 --> 02:10:08.160
[Amit Varma]: which I don't have a means to experience and and when you were talking about sort of growing

02:10:08.160 --> 02:10:12.720
[Amit Varma]: up and being bilingual and translating from English to Kannada and trying to translate

02:10:12.720 --> 02:10:17.500
[Amit Varma]: the other way and so on and so forth one of the things that struck me and I did an episode

02:10:17.500 --> 02:10:22.560
[Amit Varma]: on translation with Arunabh Sinha and I couldn't agree more and he was of the same view that

02:10:22.560 --> 02:10:27.720
[Amit Varma]: translation in a sense is impossible every language is so fundamentally different that

02:10:27.720 --> 02:10:32.080
[Amit Varma]: you know it's almost an act of creation to translate something because you try to capture

02:10:32.080 --> 02:10:37.880
[Amit Varma]: the essence and then you try to you know recreate that as it were but it also strikes me that

02:10:37.880 --> 02:10:45.440
[Amit Varma]: if you are that fluent in multiple languages you are living multiple lives you have multiple

02:10:45.440 --> 02:10:50.920
[Amit Varma]: brains you know in the because languages are so different and they are gateways to such

02:10:50.920 --> 02:10:56.320
[Amit Varma]: different worlds that you are no longer one person you are as many people as the languages

02:10:56.320 --> 02:11:00.400
[Amit Varma]: you are and I'm it's a little simplistic you are exposed to multiple milieus within each

02:11:00.400 --> 02:11:07.080
[Amit Varma]: language perhaps as well but you know and and therefore it seems that that sort of you

02:11:07.080 --> 02:11:14.920
[Amit Varma]: know richness and diversity is just incredible so what are your sort of thoughts on this?

02:11:14.920 --> 02:11:20.960
[Guest]: Amit, yeah I mean it's the death of the I remember that essay by Ram Guha I think it

02:11:20.960 --> 02:11:27.600
[Guest]: was in the EPW if I'm right I don't know if I wrote to him after that essay after reading

02:11:27.600 --> 02:11:33.400
[Guest]: that essay and around that time I delivered the H.Y. Shadaprasad memorial lecture this

02:11:33.400 --> 02:11:40.520
[Guest]: was I think 2012 of April for his birthday and it was titled bilingualism as a cultural

02:11:40.520 --> 02:11:47.920
[Guest]: idea so it was a long lecture and I think I raised a few questions about that essay

02:11:47.920 --> 02:11:52.920
[Guest]: in my lecture I of course forget what what it was I don't I don't remember the specifics

02:11:52.920 --> 02:12:00.840
[Guest]: of it but I in I mean in general I agree with what both with what Ram Guha is saying speaking

02:12:00.840 --> 02:12:06.000
[Guest]: about the death of a bilingual and there are various reasons for that you know I mean one

02:12:06.000 --> 02:12:11.880
[Guest]: of the reasons that I have actually been discussing in my books I mean my earlier books on language

02:12:11.880 --> 02:12:20.680
[Guest]: not the Dev Ekavatar book is that see the sub-nationalist thing model earlier that is

02:12:20.680 --> 02:12:28.640
[Guest]: I would you know if one would roughly put a kind of ballpark decades say from the 30s

02:12:28.640 --> 02:12:37.040
[Guest]: when the consciousness started I mean 30s 40s 50s up to the 60s even early I mean 70s

02:12:37.040 --> 02:12:44.400
[Guest]: it started getting distorted a little so those precious four of four decades you imagined

02:12:44.400 --> 02:12:53.760
[Guest]: a Kannada nation as an inclusive nation so if you look at the early proponents of the

02:12:53.760 --> 02:13:01.440
[Guest]: Kannada nation like B. M. Shrikantaiah or people of his generation they are even you

02:13:01.440 --> 02:13:07.120
[Guest]: know I mean someone who is referred to as the father of the whole idea and Alur Venkat

02:13:07.120 --> 02:13:13.080
[Guest]: Rao and others but they were all extremely inclusive in their imaginations you know me

02:13:13.080 --> 02:13:20.240
[Guest]: and B. M. Shrikantaiah in fact translates a bunch of hymns and songs and poems from

02:13:20.240 --> 02:13:26.480
[Guest]: English into Kannada and calls it English Geethegalu and those English Geethegalu were

02:13:26.480 --> 02:13:32.120
[Guest]: never English Geethegalu for a Kannada audience it became Kannada songs nobody remembers in

02:13:32.120 --> 02:13:38.560
[Guest]: fact that they were actually originally written in another language and they were translated

02:13:38.560 --> 02:13:44.960
[Guest]: into Kannada for example there is a very popular prayer in Kannada which nobody remembers and

02:13:44.960 --> 02:13:51.520
[Guest]: I don't want to remind them that it was written by a pastor in I think it's a Welsh pastor

02:13:51.520 --> 02:14:00.920
[Guest]: whatever I mean it's a song it's a poem it's a prayer which is so popular in Kannada that

02:14:00.920 --> 02:14:06.520
[Guest]: nobody remembered that it was a translated thing so that is the it speaks about the quality

02:14:06.520 --> 02:14:11.840
[Guest]: of the translation but it also speaks about the reception of a culture so and it is completely

02:14:11.840 --> 02:14:16.880
[Guest]: Kannadized you know it's not a verbatim kind of a translation so it's Lead Kindly Light

02:14:16.880 --> 02:14:22.000
[Guest]: is the poem so it's become Karunalu Baa Belakku it's actually more beautiful in Kannada I

02:14:22.000 --> 02:14:27.280
[Guest]: mean I've been listening to a different versions of Lead Kindly Light being performed in orchestras

02:14:27.280 --> 02:14:32.280
[Guest]: and others in the west but then this is so beautiful and it's composed in Kannada so

02:14:32.280 --> 02:14:37.600
[Guest]: beautifully it's it's you have it in your memory can you Karunalu Baa Belakku Musukidhi

02:14:37.600 --> 02:14:43.080
[Guest]: Muppinali Kai Hidedu Nadesem Manu that is the that's how it sounds so lovely so beautiful

02:14:43.080 --> 02:14:50.680
[Guest]: it's lyrical it's it's it's amazing and it makes you feel like you are a middle class

02:14:50.680 --> 02:14:54.840
[Guest]: person making a prayer in the morning and you are sort of I mean there's a reason why

02:14:54.840 --> 02:14:59.080
[Guest]: I say middle class because it's it's literary and all that because there is another thing

02:14:59.080 --> 02:15:04.600
[Guest]: which where it is it wouldn't be a prayer for another community so so you are making

02:15:04.600 --> 02:15:10.320
[Guest]: this prayer you're sort of inviting light to sort of lead you and there are these tough

02:15:10.320 --> 02:15:16.240
[Guest]: times and all that and it became one part of movies it became part of a singing culture

02:15:16.240 --> 02:15:20.920
[Guest]: became part of the light music what is called as quote-unquote light music in Kannada what

02:15:20.920 --> 02:15:28.280
[Guest]: is as opposite to the classical music is called light music Bhava Geethe Bhava is emotion

02:15:28.280 --> 02:15:32.080
[Guest]: I think it in Hindi it would be called Sugam Sangeet Sugam Sangeet yeah it's Kannada also

02:15:32.080 --> 02:15:37.760
[Guest]: it's called Sugam Sangeet but then Bhava Geethe is a more popular and more appropriate way

02:15:37.760 --> 02:15:44.080
[Guest]: of sort of looking at that so all of these became great Bhava Geethe in Kannada so that

02:15:44.080 --> 02:15:50.360
[Guest]: was an inclusive kind of imagination of Kannada which you see in the translation of Greek

02:15:50.360 --> 02:15:54.880
[Guest]: plays coming into Kannada so they were borrowing heavily you know they were constructing a

02:15:54.880 --> 02:15:59.720
[Guest]: kind of modern literature because there was nothing modern in Kannada everything was you

02:15:59.720 --> 02:16:06.040
[Guest]: know I mean 15th century 1670s I mean that was all you know closed court kind of literature

02:16:06.040 --> 02:16:12.520
[Guest]: so you had to create this and you had someone like Masti Venkatesh Iyengar he was a you

02:16:12.520 --> 02:16:19.080
[Guest]: know I mean Mysore service officer of those days and he creates a writer's fund to publish

02:16:19.080 --> 02:16:23.040
[Guest]: young writer something that my father did and in a different generation in a different

02:16:23.040 --> 02:16:27.400
[Guest]: time and I he was inspired by all these people he creates a fund because he is he has this

02:16:27.400 --> 02:16:33.920
[Guest]: big fat salary and he's working for the Mysore administrative service and he's a big commissioner

02:16:33.920 --> 02:16:41.280
[Guest]: of this and that and he keeps this money aside from his salary and publishes you will not

02:16:41.280 --> 02:16:48.040
[Guest]: believe the first work of K. V. Puttappa who became the great mighty Kuvempu later Kuvempu

02:16:48.040 --> 02:16:54.560
[Guest]: is now not just a literary figure in Kannada he's like Rajkumar a cultural figure in Kannada

02:16:54.560 --> 02:17:00.560
[Guest]: so he publishes Kogile his first anthology of poems he would be staying in the Ramakrishna

02:17:00.560 --> 02:17:05.800
[Guest]: mission hostel in Mysore so he goes finds him and you know publishes these poems he

02:17:05.800 --> 02:17:11.800
[Guest]: publishes the first work of he gives money to Bendre to publish his poetry anthology

02:17:11.800 --> 02:17:16.520
[Guest]: he gives money to Shivram Karanth to publish his anthology so there is this activity happening

02:17:16.520 --> 02:17:23.400
[Guest]: and look at all those people Shivram Karanth the kind of work that he wrote was liberal

02:17:23.400 --> 02:17:28.560
[Guest]: humanism you know I mean the kind of thing that he brought into his literature you know

02:17:28.560 --> 02:17:34.680
[Guest]: I mean speaking about God or philosophy or anything for that matter or human relate all

02:17:34.680 --> 02:17:40.960
[Guest]: of it had a great enlightenment influence right so it was it was an enlightenment kind

02:17:40.960 --> 02:17:45.600
[Guest]: of a thing renaissance kind of a thing that was happening in Kannada and these people

02:17:45.600 --> 02:17:51.600
[Guest]: were constructing from the broadest possible kind of platforms and broadest possible influences

02:17:51.600 --> 02:17:55.360
[Guest]: and they were bringing it all into Kannada and they were all of them I mean Atis Kuvempu

02:17:55.360 --> 02:18:00.880
[Guest]: and these people desired to be English writers and they were sort of you know course corrected

02:18:00.880 --> 02:18:06.760
[Guest]: and made Kannada writers and so they were not opposing this or that and saying oh this

02:18:06.760 --> 02:18:12.440
[Guest]: is not mine this is not mine I will not take this this is so there was no such compulsion

02:18:12.440 --> 02:18:18.480
[Guest]: on their thing and of course there was a mild caste thing underlying thing but that was

02:18:18.480 --> 02:18:24.040
[Guest]: not so pronounced as it is today but they were making their choices very wisely and

02:18:24.040 --> 02:18:29.320
[Guest]: they were constructing a broad platform like Nehru constructed the idea of India in a very

02:18:29.320 --> 02:18:35.040
[Guest]: broad fashion these people and I think in every literature it was happening every regional

02:18:35.040 --> 02:18:40.160
[Guest]: space it was happening they were all seeing Aurobindo they were seeing Nehru they were

02:18:40.160 --> 02:18:45.200
[Guest]: seeing Gandhi and they were constructing a very different kind of cultural space see

02:18:45.200 --> 02:18:53.240
[Guest]: in Kannada Ramakrishna Paravamsa, Aurobindo all are huge influences Tagore the Bengalis

02:18:53.240 --> 02:18:59.200
[Guest]: the Bengali cultural you know milieu and literature and all of that had a huge influence and they

02:18:59.200 --> 02:19:04.040
[Guest]: were constructing similar and they were there was a spiritual kind of a you know I mean

02:19:04.040 --> 02:19:09.080
[Guest]: element to their writing and there was a liberal humanist streak and there was experiential

02:19:09.080 --> 02:19:16.360
[Guest]: elements and the two novels that Kuvampu wrote Malagalalli Madhumagulu and Kanuru Subba Mahigrithi

02:19:16.360 --> 02:19:20.440
[Guest]: are I think the two of the greatest novels that I have read I mean I have read Marquez

02:19:20.440 --> 02:19:27.560
[Guest]: I have read Joyce I have read you know I mean Hemingway and I have I mean sort of even Tolstoy

02:19:27.560 --> 02:19:33.360
[Guest]: but I think it stands in that same kind of place it takes the same kind of importance

02:19:33.360 --> 02:19:37.880
[Guest]: in my mind you know I mean and unfortunately it's not translated well there have been attempts

02:19:37.880 --> 02:19:43.960
[Guest]: and it's not so great but then you know I wouldn't worry about the translation bit because

02:19:43.960 --> 02:19:48.600
[Guest]: why I mean it's it's I mean it's it's difficult it's difficult to translate and convince another

02:19:48.600 --> 02:19:53.400
[Guest]: audience I'll I'll I have another comment on translation itself see I mean there are

02:19:53.400 --> 02:20:00.600
[Guest]: people who write to be translated and there are people who write for an audience they

02:20:00.600 --> 02:20:05.800
[Guest]: have a dialogue with their people so therefore you don't see a Lankesh being translated because

02:20:05.800 --> 02:20:09.960
[Guest]: he's having a dialogue with his community but there are certain writers in Kannada who

02:20:09.960 --> 02:20:15.400
[Guest]: are only known as pan-indian greats for example Karnad did not write good Kannada at all and

02:20:15.400 --> 02:20:21.240
[Guest]: he he speaks about it himself so so I mean Anant Murthy did not have a body of work he

02:20:21.240 --> 02:20:26.760
[Guest]: spoke more in fact Sharda Prasad very jokingly used to tell me that I think P V Narasimha

02:20:26.760 --> 02:20:31.920
[Guest]: was the chairman of the Nanpeet committee when Anant Murthy got it and P V N and Sharda

02:20:31.920 --> 02:20:39.560
[Guest]: Prasad were great friends so P V N asked him what do you think so he said I told Narasimha

02:20:39.560 --> 02:20:47.120
[Guest]: to sort of give it to him with the condition that his you know he writes more that's a

02:20:47.120 --> 02:20:52.240
[Guest]: that's a kind of interesting thing so there are I mean I'm not trying to say that they

02:20:52.240 --> 02:20:57.560
[Guest]: only wrote to be translated and if Samskara was not translated by Ramanujan I don't think

02:20:57.560 --> 02:21:01.640
[Guest]: it would have become such a big thing you know I mean because there were lots of similar

02:21:01.640 --> 02:21:05.740
[Guest]: stuff being written in different Indian languages at that point of time and there was the central

02:21:05.740 --> 02:21:10.800
[Guest]: saithya academy which for which which had a mandate to get Indian languages to have

02:21:10.800 --> 02:21:16.440
[Guest]: a dialogue between themselves it was not English centric not everybody wanted to get into English

02:21:16.440 --> 02:21:21.160
[Guest]: so you're enriching English you're not enriching your regional languages what is coming into

02:21:21.160 --> 02:21:27.360
[Guest]: you is a third or third degree or fourth degree removed kind of a thing reality that's coming

02:21:27.360 --> 02:21:32.520
[Guest]: into your languages so you're translating a Paulo Coelho or some other person or another

02:21:32.520 --> 02:21:37.440
[Guest]: person but you are not actually translating between Indian languages so this is something

02:21:37.440 --> 02:21:42.840
[Guest]: that I raised when recently there's some very big translation a fellowship was announced

02:21:42.840 --> 02:21:48.720
[Guest]: by the New India Foundation I wrote up my column in the Express saying why this is you

02:21:48.720 --> 02:21:53.800
[Guest]: know I mean something that lacks vision so you are giving so much money for somebody

02:21:53.800 --> 02:21:59.280
[Guest]: who's translating from an Indian language into English and so finally English gets enriched

02:21:59.280 --> 02:22:04.520
[Guest]: so that's something that has happened with English all the while because of its colonial

02:22:04.520 --> 02:22:09.200
[Guest]: kind of legacy or whatever English has borrowed so much from these languages and it has enriched

02:22:09.200 --> 02:22:15.720
[Guest]: itself but Kannada or a Telugu or a Tamil or a Marathi see there it's understandable

02:22:15.720 --> 02:22:23.780
[Guest]: because they don't get the same kind of importance or same kind of value if it is if it is bit

02:22:23.780 --> 02:22:29.840
[Guest]: between Indian languages because it gets sort of dissipated for them you know it that philanthropy

02:22:29.840 --> 02:22:35.960
[Guest]: doesn't look big if it doesn't come into English English is like an approval gang right it

02:22:35.960 --> 02:22:41.280
[Guest]: is like academicians who become approvers of everything that is getting written or spoken

02:22:41.280 --> 02:22:46.320
[Guest]: about they say somebody sitting in JNU or in Harvard or wherever or they say this is

02:22:46.320 --> 02:22:52.520
[Guest]: great oh it's great so these kind of approval gangs get created and they start judging literatures

02:22:52.520 --> 02:22:58.000
[Guest]: and without knowing much about what is happening inside them and that becomes possible because

02:22:58.000 --> 02:23:02.000
[Guest]: everything is getting into English and they access English and they think they can understand

02:23:02.000 --> 02:23:08.760
[Guest]: or judge or make pronouncement based on their reading in English which is so very limited

02:23:08.760 --> 02:23:13.860
[Guest]: so that's why I mean I have nothing against anglophone elites but you know when I always

02:23:13.860 --> 02:23:17.920
[Guest]: look at it look at them with a bit of suspicion because you know I mean they are so confident

02:23:17.920 --> 02:23:22.160
[Guest]: because they're using a language of power which is English they are using a language

02:23:22.160 --> 02:23:27.160
[Guest]: which is just economically very very sound and it is that which is giving them confidence

02:23:27.160 --> 02:23:32.440
[Guest]: to make pronouncement about the world and there is it calls for a greater humility to

02:23:32.440 --> 02:23:36.640
[Guest]: sort of speak about anything that you don't understand or anything that is alien or anything

02:23:36.640 --> 02:23:41.120
[Guest]: that you have not accessed in their originals so you know I mean and to just say that this

02:23:41.120 --> 02:23:45.360
[Guest]: is a he's a great writer in Kannada or you say he's a great writer in Bengali without

02:23:45.360 --> 02:23:51.120
[Guest]: having read even an original text in that language is a little you know I mean shoddy

02:23:51.120 --> 02:23:56.800
[Guest]: kind of a thing so one has to be very careful of approval gangsters what I always tell myself

02:23:56.800 --> 02:24:01.760
[Guest]: because I don't need endorsements when you know I mean I've I know that you know I mean

02:24:01.760 --> 02:24:08.080
[Guest]: things are far more complex so this was the kind of the larger broad-based even a person

02:24:08.080 --> 02:24:16.040
[Guest]: like Ananthamurthy till that generation Ananthamurthy or a Lankesh or all these people created a

02:24:16.040 --> 02:24:24.080
[Guest]: kind of Kannada or the after the earlier whatever it was very broad there was so much of enlightenment

02:24:24.080 --> 02:24:28.800
[Guest]: Europe in it there was so much of reason there's so much of you know many experiential elements

02:24:28.800 --> 02:24:36.240
[Guest]: getting mainstreamed and so much of different castes coming in bringing in their experiences

02:24:36.240 --> 02:24:40.960
[Guest]: of course that got expanded in the 70s and the 80s but that took you in a different direction

02:24:40.960 --> 02:24:49.720
[Guest]: so all of this was happening but what happens in the 90s or yeah late 90s I would say is

02:24:49.720 --> 02:24:56.200
[Guest]: that the sub-nationalist cultures start borrowing the what I call the Shiv Sena model so they

02:24:56.200 --> 02:25:01.960
[Guest]: that becomes a kind of exclusionary thing oh no this is not Kannada oh no this is not

02:25:01.960 --> 02:25:08.320
[Guest]: it had started in Kannada in the 70s in fact I refer to an incident in my book where Anakrishna

02:25:08.320 --> 02:25:13.600
[Guest]: a great man otherwise you know objecting to M.S. Subalakshmi singing you know we're not

02:25:13.600 --> 02:25:18.800
[Guest]: singing Purandara or whatever they were great friends but then he sort of you know makes

02:25:18.800 --> 02:25:23.760
[Guest]: a symbolic protest and he says you should sing Purandara and all that so I mean at a

02:25:23.760 --> 02:25:30.720
[Guest]: particular concert you know it was just there and so that kind of a streak entered into

02:25:30.720 --> 02:25:36.640
[Guest]: the sub-nationalist cultures where they it started in a very gentle literary specific

02:25:36.640 --> 02:25:44.160
[Guest]: way but then it got expanded into a larger culture and then the chain the activism the

02:25:44.160 --> 02:25:51.840
[Guest]: language activism had wonderful faces as great great faces but they all became lumpen elements

02:25:51.840 --> 02:25:58.320
[Guest]: you know and suddenly used I mean people who represented Kannada or who spoke for the primacy

02:25:58.320 --> 02:26:05.000
[Guest]: of Kannada or who sort of started painting the boards black or people who sort of created

02:26:05.000 --> 02:26:10.720
[Guest]: a kind of environment which started excluding a lot of things and then they started there

02:26:10.720 --> 02:26:15.880
[Guest]: are certain people whom who are very very close to me who sort of taught me how to look

02:26:15.880 --> 02:26:24.600
[Guest]: at the world in a wonderful way to sort of perceive Chomsky, Derrida, Lacan or Foucault

02:26:24.600 --> 02:26:31.400
[Guest]: everybody you know in trying to you know grapple all of that those very same people in the

02:26:31.400 --> 02:26:35.840
[Guest]: 90s started speaking a very different thing they started saying that it's enough you know

02:26:35.840 --> 02:26:40.800
[Guest]: Kannada is enough why do why do we need the crutches of any other language why do we need

02:26:40.800 --> 02:26:45.240
[Guest]: to they were not see they never they were not bilinguals in the sense that they did

02:26:45.240 --> 02:26:50.800
[Guest]: not write in both the languages they were you know monolinguals in the sense that they

02:26:50.800 --> 02:26:56.080
[Guest]: wrote in Kannada but had new English read in English read English but did not write

02:26:56.080 --> 02:26:59.800
[Guest]: in English now that is the kind of another little thing that we need to make so these

02:26:59.800 --> 02:27:07.200
[Guest]: people started saying that you the knowledge the epistemological thing you have to create

02:27:07.200 --> 02:27:12.360
[Guest]: knowledge in Kannada so Kannada is enough you don't need mirrors of other languages

02:27:12.360 --> 02:27:17.680
[Guest]: so that you know they were all professors and teachers and were heading institutions

02:27:17.680 --> 02:27:24.400
[Guest]: and departments and all that they started changing the way their students think so these

02:27:24.400 --> 02:27:30.880
[Guest]: people who are under them started thinking that it is enough to be a Kannada person it's

02:27:30.880 --> 02:27:35.920
[Guest]: it's not important to have a dialogue with somebody who's outside of Karnataka and those

02:27:35.920 --> 02:27:42.160
[Guest]: dialogues were not to be had in the in the manner that they were being held earlier which

02:27:42.160 --> 02:27:46.840
[Guest]: is you know I mean on broad terms even if you had it was on very narrow terms it was

02:27:46.840 --> 02:27:51.600
[Guest]: for a seminar so you go you get it translated you read you make a kind of you know show

02:27:51.600 --> 02:27:57.360
[Guest]: of it and you just come back so there was no organic kind of exchange that was happening

02:27:57.360 --> 02:28:04.280
[Guest]: so that got I think that phase made Kannada and the sub-nationalist thing very very very

02:28:04.280 --> 02:28:11.280
[Guest]: sad in fact so when you became an independent state or when you became a linguistic state

02:28:11.280 --> 02:28:17.520
[Guest]: in say 56 there was a huge difference between the idea of the nation and the idea of the

02:28:17.520 --> 02:28:22.560
[Guest]: sub-nation so you again build bridges you said I was the daughter of that mother and

02:28:22.560 --> 02:28:27.960
[Guest]: mother of this daughter you try to create a kinship relationship with an abstract idea

02:28:27.960 --> 02:28:32.600
[Guest]: called India and there was this real ground beneath your feet and you try to create that

02:28:32.600 --> 02:28:36.920
[Guest]: kinship relationship and that was an arrangement you knew everybody knew that was an arrangement

02:28:36.920 --> 02:28:40.640
[Guest]: that you were creating because Gandhi had created that atmosphere there was this idea

02:28:40.640 --> 02:28:47.480
[Guest]: of independence and all that had happened so but now and so you were different and therefore

02:28:47.480 --> 02:28:52.560
[Guest]: you became a union of states in the first place you were culturally different you could

02:28:52.560 --> 02:28:59.520
[Guest]: not be put with say Assam or Bengal or whatever you were different so you there were pebbles

02:28:59.520 --> 02:29:04.360
[Guest]: in a thing they were not a soup lovely way to put it right so there were pebbles they

02:29:04.360 --> 02:29:11.000
[Guest]: were all there so now what happened was now we speak about so much about Hindutva we speak

02:29:11.000 --> 02:29:19.160
[Guest]: about this whole nationalism one language so now these people sub-nationalist agenda

02:29:19.160 --> 02:29:26.840
[Guest]: and nationalist agenda have sort of somewhere merged or sort of come closer together because

02:29:26.840 --> 02:29:31.600
[Guest]: these people also speak of an exclusionary language they also speak of an exclusionary

02:29:31.600 --> 02:29:37.520
[Guest]: language they say it's only for Hindus only India only for only Hindi and these people

02:29:37.520 --> 02:29:42.400
[Guest]: say only Canada and when they say only Canada they're excluding everybody and Canada becomes

02:29:42.400 --> 02:29:47.920
[Guest]: only a language an instrument you can what you put into that Canada you could be speaking

02:29:47.920 --> 02:29:53.080
[Guest]: the language of NRC and CA in that language and you can be speaking the language of anti

02:29:53.080 --> 02:29:59.840
[Guest]: hijab or anti whatever in that language so but that language became alienated from the

02:29:59.840 --> 02:30:05.560
[Guest]: linguistic culture linguistic culture and language became two different entities so

02:30:05.560 --> 02:30:11.160
[Guest]: the linguistic culture had a broader thing had a bigger thing so you forgot about that

02:30:11.160 --> 02:30:17.880
[Guest]: you just made the language you know you reduce the language to a kind of instrument of communication

02:30:17.880 --> 02:30:22.880
[Guest]: that's it it did not carry the culture and the tradition and the heritage and all that

02:30:22.880 --> 02:30:30.960
[Guest]: you had used to build this wonderful plank for 30 40 years so that is where so so when

02:30:30.960 --> 02:30:36.720
[Guest]: when this whole Hindi thing was happening and that hashtag don't impose an imposition

02:30:36.720 --> 02:30:41.080
[Guest]: of Hindi and all that I wrote a piece in the mint a long 2000 word piece saying opposing

02:30:41.080 --> 02:30:47.440
[Guest]: Hindi alone is not sufficient if you're talking you talk about linguistic cultures because

02:30:47.440 --> 02:30:52.680
[Guest]: it's okay you will oppose Hindi you want Canada in its place or Telugu or Tamil in its place

02:30:52.680 --> 02:30:57.120
[Guest]: but what is Tamil and Telugu doing Tamil and Telugu are speaking the same language that

02:30:57.120 --> 02:31:02.840
[Guest]: they are sort of advocating in a different context and in a different space so you have

02:31:02.840 --> 02:31:09.840
[Guest]: to sort of actually draw from your own past your own history your own heritage and make

02:31:09.840 --> 02:31:15.320
[Guest]: yourself more acceptable and more accommodative and more open and more inclusive and that

02:31:15.320 --> 02:31:20.720
[Guest]: is something which is not happening and that is where these ruptures have happened and

02:31:20.720 --> 02:31:25.200
[Guest]: that is why the initial question that you asked about the death of a bilingual is a

02:31:25.200 --> 02:31:31.800
[Guest]: far more serious thing for me than just two people I mean one person talking two languages

02:31:31.800 --> 02:31:38.120
[Guest]: having gone away it's not just as simple as that it is actually a cultural crisis of a

02:31:38.120 --> 02:31:44.400
[Guest]: huge magnitude which we don't seem to be paying attention to so it is not about just merely

02:31:44.400 --> 02:31:50.240
[Guest]: felicity with two languages it's about the imaginations and cosmologies and world and

02:31:50.240 --> 02:31:55.880
[Guest]: then the world views of two languages which don't seem to sort of sit next to each other

02:31:55.880 --> 02:32:01.920
[Guest]: anymore they sort of you know operate in silos and operate in compartments and then you know

02:32:01.920 --> 02:32:09.080
[Guest]: there is a very false agenda that is being put forward to notionally or nominally keep

02:32:09.080 --> 02:32:15.560
[Guest]: the idea of subnationalism alive so it has become very tragic actually you know you invoke

02:32:15.560 --> 02:32:21.000
[Guest]: the same activist invoke the name of Kuvempu but haven't read Kuvempu, Kuvempu has not

02:32:21.000 --> 02:32:26.800
[Guest]: advocated that the same people speak of Karanth they put all their pictures and they say we

02:32:26.800 --> 02:32:31.600
[Guest]: are a Kannada organization but they don't seem to have read anything that these people

02:32:31.600 --> 02:32:36.820
[Guest]: have written and that is not the Kannada that's not the modern Kannada imagination that they

02:32:36.820 --> 02:32:43.840
[Guest]: actually built for the initial decades of this new state so for me the trigger is very

02:32:43.840 --> 02:32:50.280
[Guest]: interesting but the death that Ram spoke about is very correct very genuine but it's not

02:32:50.280 --> 02:32:55.920
[Guest]: just as simple as two languages it's far more far more.

02:32:55.920 --> 02:33:00.640
[Amit Varma]: That's very illuminating and the part that I want to double down on is the irony that

02:33:00.640 --> 02:33:07.200
[Amit Varma]: movements that look so different like the nationalism that stresses Hindi or the subnationalism

02:33:07.200 --> 02:33:12.400
[Amit Varma]: which stresses a particular kind of Kannada are actually similar if you look deeper because

02:33:12.400 --> 02:33:18.000
[Amit Varma]: they are both exclusionary as you put it and I think that too much of political difference

02:33:18.000 --> 02:33:22.960
[Amit Varma]: really isn't political difference you know these days we think in terms of tribes while

02:33:22.960 --> 02:33:28.680
[Amit Varma]: I think we need to think more in terms of ideas so it might seem for example that you

02:33:28.680 --> 02:33:33.400
[Amit Varma]: know that Hindutva today is the opposite of what happened in Pakistan but the point is

02:33:33.400 --> 02:33:38.760
[Amit Varma]: it's in a sense it's the same thing you're saying that this is you know one nation one

02:33:38.760 --> 02:33:43.360
[Amit Varma]: religion basing nationhood on that similarly a Hindi nationalism and a Kannada nationalism

02:33:43.360 --> 02:33:47.840
[Amit Varma]: may seem opposed to each other but they're actually the same and similarly even like

02:33:47.840 --> 02:33:52.600
[Amit Varma]: you know I keep saying Vox and Bhakts are the same because it's you know you're reducing

02:33:52.600 --> 02:33:58.160
[Amit Varma]: a person to their identity and forcing upon them a narrative of either victimhood or oppression

02:33:58.160 --> 02:34:02.920
[Amit Varma]: when of course we contain multitudes and we have to be able to have those conversations.

02:34:02.920 --> 02:34:10.760
[Amit Varma]: My next question is actually about what appears in my mind to be even contradictory or two

02:34:10.760 --> 02:34:15.920
[Amit Varma]: opposite things simultaneously existing or two opposite processes simultaneously existing

02:34:15.920 --> 02:34:18.680
[Amit Varma]: and I don't know what I make of it I don't think I've thought through it enough so I'll

02:34:18.680 --> 02:34:24.820
[Amit Varma]: ask you what you think of it. One is a danger of homogenization for example you know I did

02:34:24.820 --> 02:34:29.760
[Amit Varma]: an episode on Indian food with Vikram doctor and he spoke about the Cavendish banana and

02:34:29.760 --> 02:34:33.920
[Amit Varma]: the funda of the Cavendish banana is it's a kind of banana which was in India it got

02:34:33.920 --> 02:34:39.520
[Amit Varma]: taken out it got exported out and then in the US and Latin America and whatever it got

02:34:39.520 --> 02:34:44.080
[Amit Varma]: mass produced factory produced and it was amenable to scale it would last a long time

02:34:44.080 --> 02:34:48.240
[Amit Varma]: and it basically took over the world and other bananas died and now the Cavendish and then

02:34:48.240 --> 02:34:53.280
[Amit Varma]: the Cavendish banana came to India where it is now destroying all indigenous varieties

02:34:53.280 --> 02:34:57.400
[Amit Varma]: and you have a homogenization there where there is a fear that all these other beautiful

02:34:57.400 --> 02:35:02.520
[Amit Varma]: banana types will disappear. Now I sometimes worry about a similar thing happening with

02:35:02.520 --> 02:35:08.320
[Amit Varma]: language like even within elite circles or academia you spoke about the approval gang

02:35:08.320 --> 02:35:13.320
[Amit Varma]: which is a phrase I love so much and you know Snigdha Poonam in her book dreamers and I

02:35:13.320 --> 02:35:18.240
[Amit Varma]: did an episode with her about young Indians also spoke about this craze in small towns

02:35:18.240 --> 02:35:24.600
[Amit Varma]: everywhere for learning English. English became this big aspirational thing so a Kannada person

02:35:24.600 --> 02:35:27.920
[Amit Varma]: will want to learn English a Tamil person will want to learn English. English is that

02:35:27.920 --> 02:35:32.520
[Amit Varma]: common point similarly when you spoke about translation which is such a great point that

02:35:32.520 --> 02:35:36.640
[Amit Varma]: you made that Kannada is getting translated to English Tamil is getting translated into

02:35:36.640 --> 02:35:41.520
[Amit Varma]: English why not to each other why not that dialogue so there is this danger of a kind

02:35:41.520 --> 02:35:47.000
[Amit Varma]: of centralization and a homogenization so that is one strand but a strand that seems

02:35:47.000 --> 02:35:53.520
[Amit Varma]: to me to be running in the opposite direction which I have a lot of hope for is a sort of

02:35:53.520 --> 02:36:00.520
[Amit Varma]: decentralizing strand where across different fields I find that the mainstream is dissipating

02:36:00.520 --> 02:36:06.080
[Amit Varma]: the center is not holding like I would say this is true of music for example at least

02:36:06.080 --> 02:36:09.960
[Amit Varma]: Western music which I'm far more familiar with where there is no longer a mainstream

02:36:09.960 --> 02:36:14.040
[Amit Varma]: you know rock was mainstream maybe from the Beatles or Dylan going electric to Nirvana

02:36:14.040 --> 02:36:19.160
[Amit Varma]: as Steve Van Zandt sent in a recent interview a link and you know but the mainstream has

02:36:19.160 --> 02:36:24.520
[Amit Varma]: dissipated and now it's decentralized I won't even call it niches it's just decentralized

02:36:24.520 --> 02:36:29.240
[Amit Varma]: in media we have seen that that you had your mainstream media in the 90s you had a consensus

02:36:29.240 --> 02:36:34.440
[Amit Varma]: on the truth now I feel mainstream media is completely irrelevant in India and we are

02:36:34.440 --> 02:36:39.280
[Amit Varma]: completely decentralized and I net net I think it's a good thing because it empowers individuals

02:36:39.280 --> 02:36:43.840
[Amit Varma]: of course there are problems like the fake news economy and all of that where we are

02:36:43.840 --> 02:36:48.560
[Amit Varma]: constantly in narrative battles and truth doesn't have the value and in some senses

02:36:48.560 --> 02:36:54.200
[Amit Varma]: I feel that even at the level of governments the power that nation-states have will dissipate

02:36:54.200 --> 02:36:59.160
[Amit Varma]: with technology where a nation-state cannot stop you know a culture and cannot constrain

02:36:59.160 --> 02:37:04.240
[Amit Varma]: it within its borders we are all talking to each other one way or the other so these are

02:37:04.240 --> 02:37:11.000
[Amit Varma]: two you know two different movements that I see going in two different directions one

02:37:11.000 --> 02:37:16.680
[Amit Varma]: is this homogenization driven by you know economic imperative self-interest and it's

02:37:16.680 --> 02:37:20.840
[Amit Varma]: all rational everybody's learning English that's what they want to learn right so there's

02:37:20.840 --> 02:37:24.880
[Amit Varma]: one language for the home and there's one language for the rest of the world and the

02:37:24.880 --> 02:37:30.160
[Amit Varma]: other is this sort of decentralization you see it in entertainment also like I used to

02:37:30.160 --> 02:37:36.720
[Amit Varma]: love tik-tok because there was so much great entertainment great art I would say coming

02:37:36.720 --> 02:37:40.240
[Amit Varma]: from small towns and villages in different languages even when I didn't understand the

02:37:40.240 --> 02:37:44.560
[Amit Varma]: languages you could make out what was going on and just love it you know so what's your

02:37:44.560 --> 02:37:52.000
[Guest]: take on you know I mean I think this whole one you know I mean the nation-state idea

02:37:52.000 --> 02:37:59.520
[Guest]: itself is sort of limiting in the sense it's sort of you always are looking for an official

02:37:59.520 --> 02:38:04.000
[Guest]: thing you know one language you know what I mean there is a constitution but then the

02:38:04.000 --> 02:38:08.240
[Guest]: constitution has a different role to play but then it's not about oneness it's about

02:38:08.240 --> 02:38:13.720
[Guest]: a set of rules that we have given ourselves or promised ourselves so that impulse is always

02:38:13.720 --> 02:38:19.080
[Guest]: there when you sort of when the moment you frame something as a nation then that impulse

02:38:19.080 --> 02:38:23.960
[Guest]: to homogenize is always very strong so the moment you made a Karnataka the moment you

02:38:23.960 --> 02:38:29.240
[Guest]: made an Andhra Pradesh the impulse to impose a certain thing as the standard because this

