02:40:49.320 --> 02:40:55.040
[Guest]: collapse there would be liberalization people would move within in inside the country outside

02:40:55.040 --> 02:40:59.840
[Guest]: the country all of that was not imagined when these ideas came about so I think this is

02:40:59.840 --> 02:41:06.200
[Guest]: a phase from the 90s I think from 2000s of the millennial generation is trying to make

02:41:06.200 --> 02:41:12.040
[Guest]: sense of all that we imagined say 75 years ago this is a good time to think about it

02:41:12.040 --> 02:41:16.960
[Guest]: because we are speaking about the Amrit Mahotsav and all that so what is it that we imagined

02:41:16.960 --> 02:41:22.120
[Guest]: then and what is it that we have become now and how much of it is not our own making it

02:41:22.120 --> 02:41:27.400
[Guest]: is because the world has changed and we have benefited immensely from that so you can say

02:41:27.400 --> 02:41:31.640
[Guest]: globalization is bad there was a phase in Karnataka when all these seminars would have

02:41:31.640 --> 02:41:36.720
[Guest]: this theme about globalization and every goddamn writer would say globalization has killed

02:41:36.720 --> 02:41:41.040
[Guest]: this or globalized but they don't realize that globalization also brought great ideas

02:41:41.040 --> 02:41:46.480
[Guest]: into you the internet also gave you a lot of great ideas you started accessing a lot

02:41:46.480 --> 02:41:52.400
[Guest]: of things books that were not available and you know were very very expensive and a father

02:41:52.400 --> 02:41:56.920
[Guest]: of mine had to you know take a loan to buy books you know became very expensive inexpensive

02:41:56.920 --> 02:42:01.120
[Guest]: if you walk down that street you will get any book for you know I mean an affordable

02:42:01.120 --> 02:42:06.880
[Guest]: price so a lot of good things happened so we are not this we are struck this earlier

02:42:06.880 --> 02:42:12.360
[Guest]: generation which sort of framed these ideas and bought these ideas I mean and are stuck

02:42:12.360 --> 02:42:17.320
[Guest]: it does stuck with those ideas don't know how to reconcile with this opening up and

02:42:17.320 --> 02:42:22.880
[Guest]: I think that is a kind of negotiation that happens in a culture we have had this I'm

02:42:22.880 --> 02:42:27.440
[Guest]: telling you this is not an experience that is for any culture the first time I can go

02:42:27.440 --> 02:42:32.800
[Guest]: back to the 8th century I can go back to a text called Kaviraja Marga in Kannada and

02:42:32.800 --> 02:42:37.160
[Guest]: it's a book of poetics and it tells you how to deal with Sanskrit how to deal with

02:42:37.160 --> 02:42:43.280
[Guest]: Sanskrit Alankaras and it actually looks like it is borrowing a lot from Sanskrit but it's

02:42:43.280 --> 02:42:49.840
[Guest]: actually creating an agenda for a Kannada kind of cultural space so you know I mean

02:42:49.840 --> 02:42:55.200
[Guest]: you have constantly dealt with such a cultural influence Sanskrit was a huge problem for

02:42:55.200 --> 02:43:00.680
[Guest]: Kannada so Kumar Vyasa Bharata is seen as the original Kannada Mahabharata because he

02:43:00.680 --> 02:43:08.480
[Guest]: sort of shunned Sanskrit in a way that you know I mean is still celebrated so these kind

02:43:08.480 --> 02:43:18.000
[Guest]: of what you call as like Russia has invaded Ukraine such invasions have happened culturally

02:43:18.000 --> 02:43:26.280
[Guest]: also and a culture figure takes time to figure out but for the first time these cultures

02:43:26.280 --> 02:43:32.120
[Guest]: feel a little more threatened or endangered if one has to use that kind of a language

02:43:32.120 --> 02:43:38.280
[Guest]: is because English also has an economic power which is not just soft power which a Sanskrit

02:43:38.280 --> 02:43:44.320
[Guest]: had a Sanskrit borrowed its soft power from several other kind of institutional arrangements

02:43:44.320 --> 02:43:51.280
[Guest]: so English has economic power so money speaks so how does one counter the influence of a

02:43:51.280 --> 02:43:57.120
[Guest]: language like that which leaves any local language I mean within gives it a clipped

02:43:57.120 --> 02:44:01.520
[Guest]: existence you know you will you will stay there you will stay there as an artifact your

02:44:01.520 --> 02:44:06.040
[Guest]: language will survive as an artifact but it will have a clipped existence it will not

02:44:06.040 --> 02:44:11.800
[Guest]: have the ability to actually sit across the table and speak as an equal it loses that

02:44:11.800 --> 02:44:19.520
[Guest]: ability and that is why I am a little apprehensive about fellowships or whatever which only promote

02:44:19.520 --> 02:44:23.840
[Guest]: translation in one direction so you're actually contributing to that stream so there is a

02:44:23.840 --> 02:44:29.720
[Guest]: larger argument to be made so you know and your software also the the Microsoft thing

02:44:29.720 --> 02:44:33.840
[Guest]: that when it happened and when all of that was getting into regional languages they were

02:44:33.840 --> 02:44:39.440
[Guest]: just templates that were coming from English so I met a very interesting I don't know what

02:44:39.440 --> 02:44:45.400
[Guest]: has happened to him now he was used to be at the Harvard Kenneth Keniston so I interviewed

02:44:45.400 --> 02:44:51.320
[Guest]: him for Deccanary way back in 96 or 97 and he spoke to me about localization of software

02:44:51.320 --> 02:44:56.480
[Guest]: and he gave me an example of Argentina and he said I had been to Argentina and there

02:44:56.480 --> 02:45:03.720
[Guest]: all the teachers in schools where free software and free computers have been given a ruling

02:45:03.720 --> 02:45:08.400
[Guest]: that all our children are becoming little Microsoftians or whatever you know I mean

02:45:08.400 --> 02:45:13.120
[Guest]: because you what we don't realize with the software thing it's a binary code that is

02:45:13.120 --> 02:45:21.280
[Guest]: written the idea of time see when you talk in your languages time is very circular time

02:45:21.280 --> 02:45:27.240
[Guest]: operates in a very concentric thing but here it is always linear there are lots of such

02:45:27.240 --> 02:45:35.080
[Guest]: things elements even without you understanding gets into you and you start your imagination

02:45:35.080 --> 02:45:43.800
[Guest]: and your approach and your cognitive things get a little affected or warped or you know

02:45:43.800 --> 02:45:48.280
[Guest]: it moves away from your whatever thing so how does one handle the economic strength

02:45:48.280 --> 02:45:55.880
[Guest]: of English and how does one handle the technological aspects which all again has English that the

02:45:55.880 --> 02:46:00.600
[Guest]: primacy is English right see the whole structures and templates are all built primarily for

02:46:00.600 --> 02:46:08.080
[Guest]: western audiences so that is the worry now so how does a small culture which is you know

02:46:08.080 --> 02:46:13.720
[Guest]: I mean so they have surrendered so this culture now if you look at it the audiences are lost

02:46:13.720 --> 02:46:19.800
[Guest]: I keep telling these people that okay you are now trying to dumb down do it you may

02:46:19.800 --> 02:46:24.640
[Guest]: get your TRP today but you are actually killing your culture killing your audience sorry not

02:46:24.640 --> 02:46:30.160
[Guest]: culture killing your audience because a slightly educated fellow will move away from watching

02:46:30.160 --> 02:46:35.160
[Guest]: you so how many television or you know I mean channels in Canada does a middle-class family

02:46:35.160 --> 02:46:39.520
[Guest]: watch I don't I mean it's it's it becomes it is not of their thing there is an aspirational

02:46:39.520 --> 02:46:44.360
[Guest]: element they are moving up the chain they are getting software jobs they are being so

02:46:44.360 --> 02:46:50.120
[Guest]: they are being sent on jobs to say Germany or somewhere in Europe or America whatever

02:46:50.120 --> 02:46:56.200
[Guest]: they see new things and they can't reconcile what he is speaking there you know in an absolutely

02:46:56.200 --> 02:47:01.600
[Guest]: narrow strange terms and then he says that is not important I'll consume my news on internet

02:47:01.600 --> 02:47:05.120
[Guest]: so you're losing your audience newspapers have lost their audience because they've become

02:47:05.120 --> 02:47:11.320
[Guest]: very narrow they've said I mean most newspapers I made this comment some years ago I said

02:47:11.320 --> 02:47:15.840
[Guest]: the Sunday supplements of most newspapers reads like an obituary thing because they're

02:47:15.840 --> 02:47:22.080
[Guest]: they're only involved and speaking about the past it's nostalgia somebody dies or you give

02:47:22.080 --> 02:47:27.360
[Guest]: a full page and you say oh this man died and this is gone so the so you're only speaking

02:47:27.360 --> 02:47:31.840
[Guest]: about your only sort of recording the decline of your culture you're not trying to reverse

02:47:31.840 --> 02:47:36.720
[Guest]: the whole thing and say there are there are small groups there are of course enthusiastic

02:47:36.720 --> 02:47:41.280
[Guest]: small groups trying to do this and that but you know of course you know they don't have

02:47:41.280 --> 02:47:46.760
[Guest]: that kind of wherewithal to sort of scale the whole thing and become mainstream there

02:47:46.760 --> 02:47:51.360
[Guest]: are always small groups and they do very interesting and fascinating work which one should not

02:47:51.360 --> 02:47:56.720
[Guest]: dismiss so lightly even in Canada it happens and I'm I really appreciate what they do for

02:47:56.720 --> 02:48:00.360
[Guest]: example the audiobooks kind of a thing that they're trying to do there are lots of good

02:48:00.360 --> 02:48:05.600
[Guest]: work that happens but then the the the mainstream Canada thing which you very rightly pointed

02:48:05.600 --> 02:48:11.120
[Guest]: on the mainstream thing looks very very weak and nobody people are getting disengaged with

02:48:11.120 --> 02:48:17.240
[Guest]: it the larger audience the educated the upwardly mobile audience is getting disengaged and

02:48:17.240 --> 02:48:21.960
[Guest]: you know what happens when that happens advertising stops coming into that media and then it becomes

02:48:21.960 --> 02:48:26.800
[Guest]: a rag and I mean you know in one of your shows I heard Mrinal Pandey speak about this constant

02:48:26.800 --> 02:48:32.360
[Guest]: thing about Hindi newspapers not getting advertising and why it doesn't get advertising and the

02:48:32.360 --> 02:48:38.680
[Guest]: scale and so numbers may be very quote-unquote sexy because the reach may be high but what

02:48:38.680 --> 02:48:42.920
[Guest]: is the purchasing power of that audience which reads those newspapers is a very very interesting

02:48:42.920 --> 02:48:47.320
[Guest]: question that comes back and in the kind of economic arrangement that we have now there

02:48:47.320 --> 02:48:53.600
[Guest]: is no input of money that is going and philanthropy which in a place like Bangalore plays a huge

02:48:53.600 --> 02:48:59.000
[Guest]: huge role it does not understand the complexities of these cultural questions at all because

02:48:59.000 --> 02:49:03.280
[Guest]: all these people have been software engineers or made their money through you know I mean

02:49:03.280 --> 02:49:09.240
[Guest]: new economy industries and for them you know I mean philanthropy is to sort of create a

02:49:09.240 --> 02:49:15.000
[Guest]: software for themselves and they don't engage with these real cultural issues that is where

02:49:15.000 --> 02:49:20.840
[Guest]: the death of the bilingual is more important so I mean the death is because you don't understand

02:49:20.840 --> 02:49:24.520
[Guest]: the other side not because you don't know the other language when I have far greater

02:49:24.520 --> 02:49:30.200
[Guest]: respect for Ramchandra Guha because he understands that the other side is sort of there and I

02:49:30.200 --> 02:49:34.520
[Guest]: have to respect it and for me that is a huge thing that acknowledgement is a huge thing

02:49:34.520 --> 02:49:39.880
[Guest]: but a lot of people don't acknowledge that right so he sort of he may not be accomplished

02:49:39.880 --> 02:49:45.600
[Guest]: in two or three languages like a lot of people but to know that there is that world out there

02:49:45.600 --> 02:49:51.460
[Guest]: which is far more interesting complex intricate is an acknowledgement.

02:49:51.460 --> 02:49:55.640
[Amit Varma]: So let me respond to some of the things you said because you know just thinking aloud

02:49:55.640 --> 02:50:00.660
[Amit Varma]: like I spoke about that seeming contradiction between the centralizing impulse on the one

02:50:00.660 --> 02:50:04.760
[Amit Varma]: hand the homogenization impulse on the one hand and the decentralization and while you

02:50:04.760 --> 02:50:11.240
[Amit Varma]: were speaking I realized that one way of looking at it perhaps simplistically but largely still

02:50:11.240 --> 02:50:17.760
[Amit Varma]: might have something to it is that politics has that centralizing and homogenizing impulse

02:50:17.760 --> 02:50:23.240
[Amit Varma]: while culture goes in the other direction you know because for politics number one as

02:50:23.240 --> 02:50:28.120
[Amit Varma]: Carl Schmitt the German theorist famously said that in politics you need an other and

02:50:28.120 --> 02:50:36.840
[Amit Varma]: therefore in politics it makes there is this incentive to define everything in stock terms

02:50:36.840 --> 02:50:41.400
[Amit Varma]: which leads to this kind of centralization conceptually which leads to homogenization

02:50:41.400 --> 02:50:47.320
[Amit Varma]: and all of that and that's a political imperative but culturally you know culture is getting

02:50:47.320 --> 02:50:54.440
[Amit Varma]: more and more decentralized now and the incentives there kind of go the other way and you know

02:50:54.440 --> 02:50:59.400
[Amit Varma]: the other minor aspect you pointed out about Microsoftians creating on Microsoftians and

02:50:59.400 --> 02:51:03.760
[Amit Varma]: time goes in a linear way I mean I use some software which is organized differently like

02:51:03.760 --> 02:51:08.280
[Amit Varma]: for my notes I use Rome research which is based on the German system of Zettelkasten

02:51:08.280 --> 02:51:12.720
[Amit Varma]: where everything is not quite linear or even orderly it can be circular it can you can

02:51:12.720 --> 02:51:17.760
[Amit Varma]: go off in different directions so I think you know there is scope for doing a lot more

02:51:17.760 --> 02:51:23.200
[Amit Varma]: than that but the other interesting thing that struck me was what you said about the

02:51:23.200 --> 02:51:27.840
[Amit Varma]: dumbing down of the media and that's been a constant lament and I think there it's a

02:51:27.840 --> 02:51:34.240
[Amit Varma]: combination of things that happen like when I started this podcast for example my you

02:51:34.240 --> 02:51:38.320
[Amit Varma]: know my early episodes were 20-30 minutes my impression was that listen people have

02:51:38.320 --> 02:51:42.840
[Amit Varma]: a short attention span everybody wants shallow content you gotta hook them in the first 15

02:51:42.840 --> 02:51:49.680
[Amit Varma]: seconds and don't do more than 15 minutes 20 minutes one episode I did was 11 minutes

02:51:49.680 --> 02:51:53.160
[Amit Varma]: and then over a period of time I realized everything about that was wrong one of course

02:51:53.160 --> 02:51:57.120
[Amit Varma]: there are the you know people listen to podcasts as a captive audience when they're you know

02:51:57.120 --> 02:52:01.840
[Amit Varma]: working out or commuting and so on so they are less likely to be distracted and also

02:52:01.840 --> 02:52:06.600
[Amit Varma]: they listen at higher speeds like 2x 3x whatever and therefore they're consuming like one hour

02:52:06.600 --> 02:52:11.520
[Amit Varma]: of content in half an hour of running but the most important factor was that we are

02:52:11.520 --> 02:52:15.200
[Amit Varma]: wrong about what people want we don't live in the age of the short attention span people

02:52:15.200 --> 02:52:20.200
[Amit Varma]: crave depth and they especially crave depth more today because the media doesn't give

02:52:20.200 --> 02:52:24.760
[Amit Varma]: it to them and the media for all kinds of incentives economic incentive incentives being

02:52:24.760 --> 02:52:28.920
[Amit Varma]: a big part of that because of the way our systems are structured they want to go what

02:52:28.920 --> 02:52:34.760
[Amit Varma]: my good friend Prem Panicker calls a mile wide and an inch deep right and you know because

02:52:34.760 --> 02:52:40.600
[Amit Varma]: you have you pay these enormous license fees to have a TV channel you you have price caps

02:52:40.600 --> 02:52:46.220
[Amit Varma]: on you know subscriptions so it's advertising heavy you know unlike many other countries

02:52:46.220 --> 02:52:50.520
[Amit Varma]: in the world so you have to cater to the lowest common denominator you don't have a choice

02:52:50.520 --> 02:52:54.560
[Amit Varma]: and therefore you have that screamy shouty race to the bottom that we see in our news

02:52:54.560 --> 02:52:58.240
[Amit Varma]: television and that holds for all other medium I mean that's where radio is different from

02:52:58.240 --> 02:53:03.720
[Amit Varma]: podcasting because radio also you have license fees you have restrictions so you're going

02:53:03.720 --> 02:53:09.240
[Amit Varma]: wide you're not going deep and and that's one thing I realized that people crave depth

02:53:09.240 --> 02:53:13.620
[Amit Varma]: so much and the problem is when you're a mainstream media house and you're functioning under those

02:53:13.620 --> 02:53:18.120
[Amit Varma]: kind of incentives where you don't have an option you have to go broad then you don't

02:53:18.120 --> 02:53:22.840
[Amit Varma]: realize how many people there are who want to go deep and the point is a people who want

02:53:22.840 --> 02:53:29.560
[Amit Varma]: to go deep they are also more engaged so even if my absolute numbers may be lower than say

02:53:29.560 --> 02:53:33.760
[Amit Varma]: for the audience of a Shah Rukh Khan film just to take an extreme example or maybe that's

02:53:33.760 --> 02:53:40.680
[Amit Varma]: a wrong example but the point is the engagement that anything that gives you depth is way

02:53:40.680 --> 02:53:48.140
[Amit Varma]: way more so you know and that's again something that ideally should be sorted out but it isn't

02:53:48.140 --> 02:53:51.680
[Guest]: because you know what are your thoughts being a media person?

02:53:51.680 --> 02:53:57.600
[Guest]: Being a media person and having been an editor with brand managers and CEOs around I mean

02:53:57.600 --> 02:54:02.440
[Guest]: you're absolutely bang on on this you know they constantly try to tell you that attention

02:54:02.440 --> 02:54:08.240
[Guest]: spans have become smaller and people are not interested and I always wondered as to where

02:54:08.240 --> 02:54:12.720
[Guest]: they got their feedback from you know I went to the same market I saw the same television

02:54:12.720 --> 02:54:19.720
[Guest]: channel I read the same book see but there again you know I mean I don't mean disrespect

02:54:19.720 --> 02:54:26.660
[Guest]: to any degree any person who holds an MBA degree but you know I mean look at the kind

02:54:26.660 --> 02:54:33.360
[Guest]: of people put in charge of media houses when I worked with some of the biggest media houses

02:54:33.360 --> 02:54:38.840
[Guest]: and look at the people who are put in charge of those media houses who are trained to make

02:54:38.840 --> 02:54:45.520
[Guest]: money who are you know told that you have to make money and they don't sort of distinguish

02:54:45.520 --> 02:54:51.040
[Guest]: between this and a Pepsi you know most of actually many of the media managers came from

02:54:51.040 --> 02:54:56.920
[Guest]: Pepsi in fact who made a lot of money for these big houses came from you know I mean

02:54:56.920 --> 02:55:03.680
[Guest]: people who sold sugared water so they actually they these same people when they're sent

02:55:03.680 --> 02:55:08.640
[Guest]: to the car industry now we had a very interesting general manager I mean when I was still a

02:55:08.640 --> 02:55:15.320
[Guest]: news editor and whatever so this man would had come from this thing that shut down you

02:55:15.320 --> 02:55:19.640
[Guest]: know so he would come and he would say no no no front page you put this and therefore

02:55:19.640 --> 02:55:25.400
[Guest]: there's a problem so I would always ask him see did you say the same thing in your

02:55:25.400 --> 02:55:29.720
[Guest]: previous company did you tell them the headlights are looking a little wonky therefore I can't

02:55:29.720 --> 02:55:33.560
[Guest]: sell the car so your job is to sell what we have given you because we think that we have

02:55:33.560 --> 02:55:38.160
[Guest]: done a good job so go and sell it now don't come back and tell me that this product is

02:55:38.160 --> 02:55:43.480
[Guest]: not working because of this problem so I mean the numbers rose we were doing well but there's

02:55:43.480 --> 02:55:48.960
[Guest]: under such immense pressure from the owners that for them you know I mean they they try

02:55:48.960 --> 02:55:53.880
[Guest]: to sort of make money everywhere and that that basically does not agree when you're

02:55:53.880 --> 02:55:59.560
[Guest]: dealing with something like a newspaper or a magazine or whatever because it's a different

02:55:59.560 --> 02:56:06.920
[Guest]: product it's a knowledge product so they don't seem to have that kind of their training their

02:56:06.920 --> 02:56:12.840
[Guest]: academic training or their intellectual exposure or their whatever thing is very very limited

02:56:12.840 --> 02:56:18.120
[Guest]: and narrow and confined and I wish you know I mean different kinds of people are put there

02:56:18.120 --> 02:56:22.480
[Guest]: and different kinds of things happen I mean not it's not that everybody is like that but

02:56:22.480 --> 02:56:26.920
[Guest]: you know unfortunately I am in every other person that I have met in newsrooms are like

02:56:26.920 --> 02:56:34.600
[Guest]: that so I mean I used to have a lot of problem with the CEO kinds and the brand manager kinds

02:56:34.600 --> 02:56:39.960
[Guest]: who would come and talk glib English but would have absolutely no idea as to what they were

02:56:39.960 --> 02:56:43.680
[Guest]: talking about and then at the end of the day they would come and say you know I mean we

02:56:43.680 --> 02:56:48.560
[Guest]: are trying to get some advertising feature from this politician for one week please don't

02:56:48.560 --> 02:56:53.400
[Guest]: write anything against him so things like that you know I mean so you they are compromised

02:56:53.400 --> 02:56:58.840
[Guest]: all the value systems that you sort of had that you should not compromise you're on you're

02:56:58.840 --> 02:57:04.680
[Guest]: an uncompromising journalist you have a certain kind of professional you know I mean ethical

02:57:04.680 --> 02:57:11.480
[Guest]: framework all of that they actually push you to violate every single day so how will journalism

02:57:11.480 --> 02:57:17.240
[Guest]: survive so you may have made money in a small run but you've actually killed the industry

02:57:17.240 --> 02:57:22.680
[Guest]: that's what I meant when I said you have killed the audience so that is why the non-mainstream

02:57:22.680 --> 02:57:27.320
[Guest]: things are doing so well people rely more on the non-mainstream thing they would like

02:57:27.320 --> 02:57:32.720
[Guest]: to listen to you more they would like to read something that is being offered and a bunch

02:57:32.720 --> 02:57:38.640
[Guest]: of very interesting new media products in India now or abroad so I mean they have killed

02:57:38.640 --> 02:57:44.560
[Guest]: their audience they don't realize that in the long run everything is gone and they have

02:57:44.560 --> 02:57:49.000
[Guest]: permanently deleted that audience and then they go once that becomes mainstream they

02:57:49.000 --> 02:57:55.280
[Guest]: go and play the same havoc so at least one has to sort of build a kind of firewall and

02:57:55.280 --> 02:58:01.000
[Guest]: ensures that the whole thing has to be looked at differently as going forward so that is

02:58:01.000 --> 02:58:07.700
[Guest]: why I always say when it comes to politics these congresses and keep speaking so much

02:58:07.700 --> 02:58:12.480
[Guest]: of nostalgia I get really bugged they keep saying Nehru said this Nehru did this for

02:58:12.480 --> 02:58:17.740
[Guest]: India he built the idea of democracy you know this all of this has been done so the simple

02:58:17.740 --> 02:58:22.680
[Guest]: question if is that if you ran the country like that or if you did good things then why

02:58:22.680 --> 02:58:28.720
[Guest]: do you have someone like person that we have now so the project that we need to sort of

02:58:28.720 --> 02:58:34.040
[Guest]: political project or the cultural project that we need to have is not about restoration

02:58:34.040 --> 02:58:40.200
[Guest]: of the past or the glorious Congress regime is not the restoration project that we need

02:58:40.200 --> 02:58:45.640
[Guest]: to have as liberals today we have to sort of make correctives and build something new

02:58:45.640 --> 02:58:52.560
[Guest]: and far more diverse and interesting so restoration is a huge huge problem because you have made

02:58:52.560 --> 02:58:57.040
[Guest]: a lot of mistakes and therefore you have you are in the situation that you are in today

02:58:57.040 --> 02:59:01.520
[Guest]: and if you are not reflective and if you think you were good and you were suddenly overnight

02:59:01.520 --> 02:59:06.440
[Guest]: thrown away by some some kind of a current that came is wrong because everything builds

02:59:06.440 --> 02:59:12.400
[Guest]: up and I often tell me in spite of my deep deep respect for someone like Manmohan Singh

02:59:12.400 --> 02:59:18.000
[Guest]: Dr. Manmohan Singh I keep telling a lot of my Congress friends in my arguments that see

02:59:18.000 --> 02:59:23.440
[Guest]: Devagoda had far greater democratic engagement than a Manmohan Singh, Manmohan Singh was

02:59:23.440 --> 02:59:28.000
[Guest]: a technocrat you put him there for 10 years and there was no political engagement and

02:59:28.000 --> 02:59:33.960
[Guest]: people thought that this is the weak weakest Prime Minister we have in his during his term

02:59:33.960 --> 02:59:38.880
[Guest]: I don't think he was ever described as a strong man in 2009 I think that was the electoral

02:59:38.880 --> 02:59:44.000
[Guest]: plank of Advani they called him the weak Prime Minister but you know the economy is doing

02:59:44.000 --> 02:59:49.080
[Guest]: well and there were other reasons as to why they came back to power but the tragedy is

02:59:49.080 --> 02:59:54.960
[Guest]: the Congress could not give a political person at the helm for 10 long years I understand

02:59:54.960 --> 02:59:59.640
[Guest]: that as a stopgap arrangement that's not the ideal that we have to go back you have a CEO

02:59:59.640 --> 03:00:06.400
[Guest]: running your government and you have a power system elsewhere so that is what this created

03:00:06.400 --> 03:00:12.240
[Guest]: a urge for a strong leader and somebody sort of made use of that space so things have there

03:00:12.240 --> 03:00:17.520
[Guest]: is a reaction and there is a reaction to things that you have there are consequences to the

03:00:17.520 --> 03:00:23.120
[Guest]: your actions and we don't have to think of restoration so similarly culturally or media

03:00:23.120 --> 03:00:27.560
[Guest]: or it applies to everything that we are speaking about I don't think we have to you know say

03:00:27.560 --> 03:00:33.120
[Guest]: that I mean Madhubala was great so let's get another Madhubala there are new people coming

03:00:33.120 --> 03:00:39.000
[Guest]: so you don't have to get into this nostalgia trip each time or retro thing and say that

03:00:39.000 --> 03:00:43.720
[Guest]: all was great with Nehru and therefore we need to bring back the Nehru in India and

03:00:43.720 --> 03:00:49.840
[Guest]: that was the biggest thing I don't think it was correct and and Nehru operated in a completely

03:00:49.840 --> 03:00:56.360
[Guest]: different time and Nehru after the partition this is my understanding I may be wrong after

03:00:56.360 --> 03:01:02.120
[Guest]: the partition had to build reason into the system so he used reason a lot of reason he

03:01:02.120 --> 03:01:06.920
[Guest]: built brought in scientific temper he spoke of scientific temper he spoke like an enlightened

03:01:06.920 --> 03:01:12.800
[Guest]: statesman you know when he used the principles of enlightenment and and all of that and created

03:01:12.800 --> 03:01:18.920
[Guest]: an India which was which which thought logically you know or or propounded that or put it there

03:01:18.920 --> 03:01:23.080
[Guest]: on the table and he had such big cherishment nobody cared what he spoke he they voted for

03:01:23.080 --> 03:01:27.920
[Guest]: him or they voted for the Congress party because there was also the element of I mean independence

03:01:27.920 --> 03:01:32.800
[Guest]: and the memory of independence and all that but now if you continue in that stream which

03:01:32.800 --> 03:01:39.880
[Guest]: Rahul Gandhi never gets which is you Rahul Gandhi is logical he is very sincere he has

03:01:39.880 --> 03:01:46.720
[Guest]: reason sorted out but there is no emotion but politics is all about emotion it's a fantastic

03:01:46.720 --> 03:01:53.600
[Guest]: blend of reason and emotion and a great leader whoever across the world has operated by actually

03:01:53.600 --> 03:01:59.040
[Guest]: fusing these two elements brilliantly the formulas could be different the the percentages

03:01:59.040 --> 03:02:06.040
[Guest]: could be different but you don't communicate only invoking a certain kind of academic logic

03:02:06.040 --> 03:02:10.400
[Amit Varma]: in the in the parliament no and I honestly don't think that there is even reason there

03:02:10.400 --> 03:02:15.480
[Amit Varma]: in fact I think the Congress blunders continuously instead of celebrating Narsimha Rao and Manmohan

03:02:15.480 --> 03:02:20.200
[Amit Varma]: Singh they celebrate Indira Gandhi and Sanjay Gandhi you know every every year when it's

03:02:20.200 --> 03:02:24.280
[Amit Varma]: his birthday all the official Congress handles will talk about what a great guy he is and

03:02:24.280 --> 03:02:28.280
[Amit Varma]: even Nehru you know the point is we have the sedition law today because after the court

03:02:28.280 --> 03:02:32.880
[Amit Varma]: rule the courts ruled it unconstitutional in 1950 Nehru brought it back you know we

03:02:32.880 --> 03:02:37.600
[Amit Varma]: remained a poor country for more than seven decades which is why 2014 happened you oppose

03:02:37.600 --> 03:02:40.880
[Amit Varma]: the current guy I completely agree with you you oppose the current guy but understand

03:02:40.880 --> 03:02:45.080
[Amit Varma]: where he came from and what's going on and frankly the current guy is more of the same

03:02:45.080 --> 03:02:49.960
[Amit Varma]: right we we have the you know you can think in tribal terms and they can look like opposites

03:02:49.960 --> 03:02:55.320
[Amit Varma]: but it's in a sense more of the same and a little worse and some margins you know earlier

03:02:55.320 --> 03:03:00.960
[Amit Varma]: you made the point about the suits the MBAs the CEO types as you put it who only care

03:03:00.960 --> 03:03:06.440
[Amit Varma]: about money and even there I think that they're not good suits and good MBAs if they care

03:03:06.440 --> 03:03:10.120
[Amit Varma]: about money in the way that they do because they're caring about it in a short term way

03:03:10.120 --> 03:03:15.200
[Amit Varma]: if you actually think long term you you'd kind of learn to sort of segment the market

03:03:15.200 --> 03:03:20.100
[Amit Varma]: and realize that you know that this is not sustainable and earlier you'd mentioned very

03:03:20.100 --> 03:03:23.820
[Amit Varma]: evocatively when you spoke about the little magazines how your father would put it together

03:03:23.820 --> 03:03:28.280
[Amit Varma]: your mother would put the little stamp on it and you know you'd go on cycles and you

03:03:28.280 --> 03:03:33.800
[Amit Varma]: deliver it to people and I think what was happening there and the reason that it worked

03:03:33.800 --> 03:03:38.680
[Amit Varma]: was that there is that direct sense of who is reading it there is a sense of the human

03:03:38.680 --> 03:03:42.080
[Amit Varma]: beings who are reading it and they're paying you for it and they're taking it and that

03:03:42.080 --> 03:03:47.920
[Amit Varma]: keeps it alive and it dies out to some extent not because the audience dies out I feel but

03:03:47.920 --> 03:03:54.240
[Amit Varma]: because the connect dies out and what I think we need to figure out all the metaphorical

03:03:54.240 --> 03:04:00.480
[Amit Varma]: little magazines of the day is that one we need to realize that that audience is there

03:04:00.480 --> 03:04:04.560
[Amit Varma]: if anything it's bigger than ever before and what we just need to figure out is figure

03:04:04.560 --> 03:04:08.360
[Amit Varma]: out the logistics how do we get our work to them which is easier than ever before because

03:04:08.360 --> 03:04:12.760
[Amit Varma]: of technology and more importantly how do they pay us and I think that's easy to sort

03:04:12.760 --> 03:04:17.400
[Amit Varma]: out because you know one thing that I'm seeing in the creator economy is that more and more

03:04:17.400 --> 03:04:22.180
[Amit Varma]: the one big shift is that creators are being able to get money directly from consumers

03:04:22.180 --> 03:04:29.200
[Amit Varma]: you don't have to go via advertisers via sponsors all of that so I want to sort of talk about

03:04:29.200 --> 03:04:35.760
[Amit Varma]: this personal aspect this people aspect also in a context that you brought up earlier where

03:04:35.760 --> 03:04:42.360
[Amit Varma]: you spoke about you were reporting from Rajasthan and you you're chatting to Bhairon Singh Shikhawath

03:04:42.360 --> 03:04:46.680
[Amit Varma]: who by one section of the media would be painted as one caricature another section would paint

03:04:46.680 --> 03:04:51.840
[Amit Varma]: him as another caricature and you try to get behind the person and kind of go deeper in

03:04:51.840 --> 03:04:57.960
[Amit Varma]: a sense what I try to do as well and what I find in in modern times is that we live

03:04:57.960 --> 03:05:04.080
[Amit Varma]: in a world where there is almost we are incentivized to pass judgment all the time either to gain

03:05:04.080 --> 03:05:09.680
[Amit Varma]: status within our own little tribes or to feel virtuous for ourselves that oh I made

03:05:09.680 --> 03:05:14.320
[Amit Varma]: fun of him and therefore I'm better than him and so on and this really means that we start

03:05:14.320 --> 03:05:20.200
[Amit Varma]: looking at the world in black and white ways and that there is a constructed world anywhere

03:05:20.200 --> 03:05:24.920
[Amit Varma]: where you have polarized rhetoric so and so is evil so and so is you know a paragon of

03:05:24.920 --> 03:05:29.920
[Amit Varma]: virtue and we start kind of falling into those lines and it strikes me that what we need

03:05:29.920 --> 03:05:34.840
[Amit Varma]: is more of what you were doing and more of what good journalists do today where you go

03:05:34.840 --> 03:05:40.920
[Amit Varma]: deeper figure out the personal you know figure out basically you delve in all the shades

03:05:40.920 --> 03:05:47.560
[Amit Varma]: of grey and you make that concrete like you know to me a lot of the dangerous ideas that

03:05:47.560 --> 03:05:54.640
[Amit Varma]: we have around us are abstract ideas nationalism and purity and all of these and our lived

03:05:54.640 --> 03:06:00.240
[Amit Varma]: reality when we are actually engaging with the concrete is not like that at all you know

03:06:00.240 --> 03:06:04.040
[Amit Varma]: you you know in your Devegada book which maybe we'll have to talk about in a separate episode

03:06:04.040 --> 03:06:08.240
[Amit Varma]: because it's just got so much I want to talk five hours about that but in that book you

03:06:08.240 --> 03:06:13.440
[Amit Varma]: speak about how his secularism was a lived secularism it came from concrete things you

03:06:13.440 --> 03:06:18.280
[Amit Varma]: know he could see his you know father employ a Muslim in the field who's teaching him Urdu

03:06:18.280 --> 03:06:22.760
[Amit Varma]: and all of that and his lived experiences leading to a secularism not some ideological

03:06:22.760 --> 03:06:29.720
[Amit Varma]: abstract thing and in your view what can people like us or people like whoever's listening

03:06:29.720 --> 03:06:35.960
[Amit Varma]: to this conversation or just society as a whole what can we do to sort of start privileging

03:06:35.960 --> 03:06:42.240
[Amit Varma]: the concrete more over the abstract because we are ruled all around us by abstract rhetoric

03:06:42.240 --> 03:06:47.680
[Amit Varma]: by constructed realities by these imperatives that we have to pass judgment on others that

03:06:47.680 --> 03:06:53.280
[Amit Varma]: there's our tribe and then everybody else is evil and so on and so forth and these abstract

03:06:53.280 --> 03:06:57.940
[Amit Varma]: things break down the moment you have you know I mean maybe I'm being very idealistic

03:06:57.940 --> 03:07:04.080
[Amit Varma]: but they tend to break down when you have you know engagement with the real world so

03:07:04.080 --> 03:07:09.960
[Guest]: you know what are your thoughts no that's a very very profound question see you can't

03:07:09.960 --> 03:07:16.960
[Guest]: separate the abstract Amit actually in the in a common man's life if you think of it

03:07:16.960 --> 03:07:22.560
[Guest]: the abstract the biggest abstract is the God it begins with a prayer every morning and

03:07:22.560 --> 03:07:26.720
[Guest]: you don't know where you're sending it up and you're reconciling with a lot of things

03:07:26.720 --> 03:07:31.720
[Guest]: you know your there are religious ideas that have become so much part of you that you have

03:07:31.720 --> 03:07:36.200
[Guest]: you either believe in your karma siddhanta like my character of my book Deva Gowda believes

03:07:36.200 --> 03:07:40.160
[Guest]: and destiny and things like that and he's never offended with anything because he thinks

03:07:40.160 --> 03:07:44.920
[Guest]: that oh I must have made some mistake in my past life so it's come to haunt me today so

03:07:44.920 --> 03:07:50.360
[Guest]: so you reconcile all those are abstract ideas religion has given you that abstract ideas

03:07:50.360 --> 03:07:56.840
[Guest]: it is what is constructed by politicians for a certain purpose and for a certain thing

03:07:56.840 --> 03:08:02.560
[Guest]: which becomes problematic I don't think it's wonderful to be in a abstract kind of a thing

03:08:02.560 --> 03:08:09.040
[Guest]: and also bring the concrete so that you see in a lot of these 12th century vachanas like

03:08:09.040 --> 03:08:15.040
[Guest]: it was beautifully translated by Ramanujan I mean in English it's it sounds like this

03:08:15.040 --> 03:08:21.680
[Guest]: you know I mean my legs are pillars my body the shrine the head a cupola of gold wow right

03:08:21.680 --> 03:08:26.080
[Guest]: so you know I mean you are see that that particular thing

03:08:26.080 --> 03:08:38.440
[Guest]: so you are blending the two so that was written for a common man so that man is actually weaving

03:08:38.440 --> 03:08:42.920
[Guest]: you know I mean something or he's sewing I mean there is something happening in the fields

03:08:42.920 --> 03:08:48.800
[Guest]: or he and he's speaking of this and he's invoking the God he's invoking the Lord so nature itself

03:08:48.800 --> 03:08:53.200
[Guest]: sort of actually throws up a lot of abstract questions at you and I don't think you can

03:08:53.200 --> 03:08:58.280
[Guest]: escape the abstract the political abstract is the question the political thing is a problem

03:08:58.280 --> 03:09:03.440
[Guest]: and there I think it is common sense which has to come to play and we need more Deva

03:09:03.440 --> 03:09:07.840
[Guest]: Gowda's there you know people may not like what I say or whatever but then if they read

03:09:07.840 --> 03:09:13.600
[Guest]: my book they'll understand why that common sense plays such an enormous role to blend

03:09:13.600 --> 03:09:19.320
[Guest]: this whole idea of the abstract and the thing and then sorts out politics in a completely

03:09:19.320 --> 03:09:26.200
[Guest]: different way so so you can't escape the abstract the nation is of course the idea of a nation

03:09:26.200 --> 03:09:33.080
[Guest]: was as I probably you know I mean not as foolproof as the idea of religion because religion sort

03:09:33.080 --> 03:09:37.440
[Guest]: of appeals to us something else you know I mean it's about your being itself this is

03:09:37.440 --> 03:09:42.720
[Guest]: an artificial construct that was created and even the linguistic state you know I mean

03:09:42.720 --> 03:09:47.960
[Guest]: I was reading this Lisa Michelle who wrote a beautiful book on the South Indian linguistic

03:09:47.960 --> 03:09:54.040
[Guest]: states and there she says that this whole idea of linguistic state was a late 19th century

03:09:54.040 --> 03:09:59.240
[Guest]: idea it was not even there before that that you could construct a state around the idea

03:09:59.240 --> 03:10:06.560
[Guest]: of a language where did it come from so so those things are the abstract I mean I'm fascinated

03:10:06.560 --> 03:10:12.160
[Guest]: by the abstract poetry is abstract for me I mean half my life would not have been so

03:10:12.160 --> 03:10:17.320
[Guest]: I mean interesting or enriching if there was no poetry and and if Bendre doesn't make sense

03:10:17.320 --> 03:10:23.600
[Guest]: half the time but the sounds are so good language itself is abstract at times so there is no

03:10:23.600 --> 03:10:30.160
[Guest]: escaping the abstract it is that that is this engineered abstraction that we try to bring

03:10:30.160 --> 03:10:36.480
[Guest]: and put it there and make politics out of it is something that is the problem according

03:10:36.480 --> 03:10:41.640
[Guest]: to me but I mean this is something that you threw at me and I have just tried to think

03:10:41.640 --> 03:10:46.560
[Amit Varma]: about it on the spot so I may be wrong no no it's it's opened up a new dimension for

03:10:46.560 --> 03:10:51.440
[Amit Varma]: me to think about and you mentioned poetry and you know when you mentioned that editor

03:10:51.440 --> 03:10:56.600
[Amit Varma]: at the Irish newspaper where you worked where she sadly drowned herself and I thought yeah

03:10:56.600 --> 03:11:00.400
[Amit Varma]: and I thought of this beautiful poem which I really love which blends the abstract and

03:11:00.400 --> 03:11:06.000
[Amit Varma]: the concrete in this lovely way so I'll read it out it's it's called not waving but drowning

03:11:06.000 --> 03:11:11.280
[Amit Varma]: by Stevie Smith nobody heard him the dead man but still he lay mourning I was much further

03:11:11.280 --> 03:11:15.800
[Amit Varma]: out than you thought and not waving but drowning poor chap he always loved locking and now

03:11:15.800 --> 03:11:21.240
[Amit Varma]: he's dead it must have been too cold for him his heart gave way they said oh no no no it

03:11:21.240 --> 03:11:26.240
[Amit Varma]: was too cold always still the dead one lay mourning I was much too far out all my life

03:11:26.240 --> 03:11:31.320
[Amit Varma]: and not waving but drowning just just that image of not waving but drowning that concrete

03:11:31.320 --> 03:11:36.120
[Amit Varma]: image but it really kind of speaks to you and since you mentioned commonsensical I want

03:11:36.120 --> 03:11:42.040
[Amit Varma]: to read out this little bit by Montek Singh Aluwalia on Devagad from your book where Montek

03:11:42.040 --> 03:11:49.000
[Amit Varma]: says and I'm quoting you quoting Montek you know he had this habit of looking very sleepy

03:11:49.000 --> 03:11:52.960
[Amit Varma]: I have noticed that even when he appeared to be in a somnolent kind of state one ear

03:11:52.960 --> 03:11:57.080
[Amit Varma]: was always open and whenever something needed to be said he would say it without missing

03:11:57.080 --> 03:12:01.600
[Amit Varma]: anything my favorite recollection is that on one occasion we were trying to raise the

03:12:01.600 --> 03:12:07.160
[Amit Varma]: price of LPG gas as subsidy was building up so we said that it is one thing to have targeted

03:12:07.160 --> 03:12:12.640
[Amit Varma]: subsidy but to keep all cooking gas at low price is not helpful one minister was arguing

03:12:12.640 --> 03:12:16.760
[Amit Varma]: that if you raise the price it will hurt the common man immediately Gowda who was in a

03:12:16.760 --> 03:12:21.160
[Amit Varma]: somnolent appearance disagreed and now these are Gowda's words you know what is happening

03:12:21.160 --> 03:12:25.600
[Amit Varma]: in Delhi cooking gas has been used by all rich people to cook seekh and tikka kebabs

03:12:25.600 --> 03:12:30.320
[Amit Varma]: for their parties he said and offered to take us around one evening to show how many lavish

03:12:30.320 --> 03:12:35.400
[Amit Varma]: parties were fueled by subsidized cooking gas these guys can afford to pay why should

03:12:35.400 --> 03:12:39.920
[Amit Varma]: we subsidize that was an earthy response this would not have been the response of a civil

03:12:39.920 --> 03:12:44.960
[Amit Varma]: servant and then of course you kind of go on to point out what an actual geek or civil

03:12:44.960 --> 03:12:49.760
[Amit Varma]: servant would have said where they would have said oh 20% of the people are using 80% of

03:12:49.760 --> 03:12:53.200
[Amit Varma]: the benefits and rubbish like that and he went straight to the concrete and obviously

03:12:53.200 --> 03:12:58.920
[Amit Varma]: that can also hurt because then you can confuse anecdata for data and make wrong decisions

03:12:58.920 --> 03:13:04.320
[Guest]: Dev Gowda was good with both data and experience which is which was a surprise to me as I yeah

03:13:04.320 --> 03:13:10.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean everything that you have written about his research habits his incredible work ethic

03:13:10.720 --> 03:13:14.840
[Amit Varma]: and all of that is something we have to discuss in detail so the next time I come to Bangalore

03:13:14.840 --> 03:13:20.040
[Amit Varma]: we can talk about Dev Gowda but right now I'm kind of enjoying this conversation too

03:13:20.040 --> 03:13:27.520
[Amit Varma]: much so you know earlier on you spoke about how your view of the world was sort of shaped

03:13:27.520 --> 03:13:32.040
[Amit Varma]: by this fortunate circumstance of having a family like you did parents like you did an

03:13:32.040 --> 03:13:40.000
[Amit Varma]: environment like you did a bilingual environment like you did when it comes to journalism you

03:13:40.000 --> 03:13:45.480
[Amit Varma]: know you did journalism here you went abroad and you did journalism you came back you've

03:13:45.480 --> 03:13:50.160
[Amit Varma]: been an editor you know you worked in English journalism you worked in language journalism

03:13:50.160 --> 03:13:55.920
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about how your initial view of journalism was kind of shaped like

03:13:55.920 --> 03:14:00.920
[Amit Varma]: why do we do journalism what are our values what is good journalism in a definitional

03:14:00.920 --> 03:14:06.480
[Amit Varma]: sense how you kind of arrived at that and tell me a little bit about you know that sort

03:14:06.480 --> 03:14:11.040
[Amit Varma]: of journey and whether you feel that whether you feel more hopeful now or less hopeful

03:14:11.040 --> 03:14:20.080
[Guest]: now the last part is very difficult no but I never sort of defined journalism for myself

03:14:20.080 --> 03:14:25.040
[Guest]: I was never a student of journalism and ever went to university to study journalism I was

03:14:25.040 --> 03:14:30.200
[Guest]: a student of literature and culture so culture studies comparative literatures so I was in

03:14:30.200 --> 03:14:37.040
[Guest]: a whole different world and then I happened to sort of get into a newsroom and the editor

03:14:37.040 --> 03:14:43.080
[Guest]: was not very trusting of my me sustaining interest but somehow I sort of stayed back

03:14:43.080 --> 03:14:47.760
[Guest]: and never went out went away or you know because I was I thought I was a little successful

03:14:47.760 --> 03:14:55.400
[Guest]: and I could continue so I never defined what good journalism is for myself because I was

03:14:55.400 --> 03:15:00.800
[Guest]: I thought what the place that I was in Deccan Herald and the kind of multiplicity of views

03:15:00.800 --> 03:15:06.040
[Guest]: that I was seeing and the kind of assignments I was getting and what was getting published

03:15:06.040 --> 03:15:11.920
[Guest]: was not very different from a very ideal kind of a situation you could write about some

03:15:11.920 --> 03:15:16.200
[Guest]: philosopher called Derrida and you could get published you could write about Saeed, you

03:15:16.200 --> 03:15:20.640
[Guest]: could write about Chomsky, you could write about a new director of the Max Buller Bowen

03:15:20.640 --> 03:15:25.920
[Guest]: who has taken over and was great great new ideas you could write about Brecht in Canada

03:15:25.920 --> 03:15:32.860
[Guest]: cinema and Hindi cinema and and Canada plays so you could I was just completely immersed

03:15:32.860 --> 03:15:39.920
[Guest]: in my cultural and literary writing for Deccan Herald I did not think outside of it and also

03:15:39.920 --> 03:15:44.000
[Guest]: the very first piece that I published was you know it was some kind of a tribute to

03:15:44.000 --> 03:15:49.800
[Guest]: Adiga where I sort of wrote about Adiga and his poetry and sort of translated a small

03:15:49.800 --> 03:15:53.760
[Guest]: little piece that he had written about me and my poetry and it was a very intensely

03:15:53.760 --> 03:15:58.800
[Guest]: passionate piece when it was run again one page so I mean it became a kind of default

03:15:58.800 --> 03:16:04.320
[Guest]: to get one page for me in Deccan Herald I mean I mean I have so many of those clippings

03:16:04.320 --> 03:16:09.040
[Guest]: and if anybody cares to look at the archives they'll see how is this fellow you know I

03:16:09.040 --> 03:16:13.680
[Guest]: mean getting so much of space it's not that I was writing something very big or I was

03:16:13.680 --> 03:16:20.000
[Guest]: a great writer it didn't it wasn't that it was about the generosity of the editorship

03:16:20.000 --> 03:16:26.320
[Guest]: of the time it was like you know I mean I always imagined that I should work in an environment

03:16:26.320 --> 03:16:31.680
[Guest]: where someone like this Harold Evans worked and the Sunday Times and that kind of an ideal

03:16:31.680 --> 03:16:36.320
[Guest]: kind of an environment where even a Philip Knightley was encouraged and he did a lot

03:16:36.320 --> 03:16:42.220
[Guest]: of great stories but all of that came later see only after 2000 did I start looking at

03:16:42.220 --> 03:16:48.480
[Guest]: journalism as journalism should be looked at until then for me it was a venue to get

03:16:48.480 --> 03:16:56.300
[Guest]: my I mean half fulfilled literary or cultural ambitions in so it could be poetry or it could

03:16:56.300 --> 03:17:03.040
[Guest]: be short stories or whatever but after 2000 something changed because I went on a shivning

03:17:03.040 --> 03:17:08.480
[Guest]: scholarship to England and then so there was a it was a for print journalism and it was

03:17:08.480 --> 03:17:13.280
[Guest]: a program for young print journalists there was this great man who was running the program

03:17:13.280 --> 03:17:18.840
[Guest]: John Tullock who succumbed to cancer I think in 2016 if I remember right and there was

03:17:18.840 --> 03:17:25.520
[Guest]: Adam Hopkins who was a travel writer and they were running the program and they sort of

03:17:25.520 --> 03:17:30.800
[Guest]: put you in touch with great people like Edwin Taylor Edwin Taylor was someone who had designed

03:17:30.800 --> 03:17:34.760
[Guest]: the Deccan Herald and designed half a dozen newspapers of the world and written a great

03:17:34.760 --> 03:17:39.920
[Guest]: book with Harold Evans called pictures on the page on designing newspapers so I got

03:17:39.920 --> 03:17:44.600
[Guest]: terribly terribly interested in the mechanics of putting a newspaper together the design

03:17:44.600 --> 03:17:50.000
[Guest]: the the layout and you know picking a picture how should we look at that and of course reporting

03:17:50.000 --> 03:17:55.200
[Guest]: and writing and there was a Putin Blair summit and because you were a shivning fellow you

03:17:55.200 --> 03:17:59.040
[Guest]: were a giver you were given a pass to go and sit in the media you know thing so I went

03:17:59.040 --> 03:18:03.200
[Guest]: and watched that I mean there was a great opportunity to grow and there I still when

03:18:03.200 --> 03:18:09.840
[Guest]: I went to England I went as a provincial boy with my Kannada baggage and my literary baggage

03:18:09.840 --> 03:18:16.080
[Guest]: and my cultural baggage and besides John Tullock and Adam Hopkins who are putting me who are

03:18:16.080 --> 03:18:22.320
[Guest]: getting me to look at the mechanics of journalism a little more seriously I met this great mentor

03:18:22.320 --> 03:18:28.840
[Guest]: who was still with who still mentors me Mr. Jeremy Seabrook and Jeremy Seabrook was such

03:18:28.840 --> 03:18:33.840
[Guest]: a distinguished writer in England he was writing a column for the Guardian and he was given

03:18:33.840 --> 03:18:39.200
[Guest]: to me as a personal mentor there was a system where you were given big writers as your mentors

03:18:39.200 --> 03:18:45.920
[Guest]: I just met I think initially the plan was to give me Julian Bonds I mean there's some

03:18:45.920 --> 03:18:50.280
[Guest]: such talk you know and that never happened but of course I I mean I happened to run into

03:18:50.280 --> 03:18:55.560
[Guest]: him and said hello and all that but then just imagine getting a Julian Bonds and Jeremy

03:18:55.560 --> 03:19:00.440
[Guest]: was no less because Jeremy had published some 30 40 books he had an India interest and he

03:19:00.440 --> 03:19:06.680
[Guest]: was more than anything else he was someone who would give you time and he was empathetic

03:19:06.680 --> 03:19:11.600
[Guest]: he would listen and not many people had that kind of would give you that kind of time so

03:19:11.600 --> 03:19:17.120
[Guest]: he had I think injured his ankle and therefore he was at home and it gave me great opportunity

03:19:17.120 --> 03:19:22.120
[Guest]: to sort of you know go and vomit all my ideas before him and then he would listen for an

03:19:22.120 --> 03:19:27.120
[Guest]: hour or he's a great listener like you he would listen to ours together and then he

03:19:27.120 --> 03:19:32.480
[Guest]: would come back with a response which was so terrific he would say see you are looking

03:19:32.480 --> 03:19:37.760
[Guest]: at it in a very limited way so frame it this way look at it this way so go back and write

03:19:37.760 --> 03:19:43.240
[Guest]: it this way and come back to me having read this so he was he gave me I think the grant

03:19:43.240 --> 03:19:51.880
[Guest]: edition which was being edited by Ian Jack and it was about England and its loss of you

03:19:51.880 --> 03:19:55.800
[Guest]: know greatness the Great Britain had become just Britain so it was something around that

03:19:55.800 --> 03:20:02.080
[Guest]: and I forget the exact title of the grant issue and he had an essay in that about something

03:20:02.080 --> 03:20:08.080
[Guest]: related and he gave me that and he said you can keep this copy and getting a grant free

03:20:08.080 --> 03:20:11.800
[Guest]: for a student you know I mean was itself a very big thing so he said you can keep this

03:20:11.800 --> 03:20:16.880
[Guest]: and I am not giving it to you because I have written a piece but then I want you to sort

03:20:16.880 --> 03:20:21.600
[Guest]: of critique what I have written so then this was I thought he was sort of being very nice

03:20:21.600 --> 03:20:27.280
[Guest]: to me and so I read that I went I discussed I keep going back to him his house was in

03:20:27.280 --> 03:20:33.080
[Guest]: Muswell Hill so I mean I used to take the metro underground and reach his place and

03:20:33.080 --> 03:20:39.440
[Guest]: it was 3 Springfield Avenue Muswell Hill is shifted to another house now closer by but

03:20:39.440 --> 03:20:45.240
[Guest]: I used to go and I mean I thought I was boring him but he was very empathic and he was always

03:20:45.240 --> 03:20:49.400
[Guest]: someone because he was a writer he would ask me very personal questions you tell you tell

03:20:49.400 --> 03:20:53.800
[Guest]: me tell me something about your father what kind of a person is he what did he ask you

03:20:53.800 --> 03:20:57.960
[Guest]: to read you know how did you grow up you know what kind of an him so he was basically also

03:20:57.960 --> 03:21:03.040
[Guest]: soaking in my cultural environment he was trying to understand my family is understanding

03:21:03.040 --> 03:21:07.680
[Guest]: where I am coming from and then this whole Kannada Kannada Kannada business that I had

03:21:07.680 --> 03:21:13.760
[Guest]: in my head and literature literature and culture all that he sort of brought in a gently introduced

03:21:13.760 --> 03:21:20.640
[Guest]: polemical ideas you know just just ruffled a few of them and then that expanded the way

03:21:20.640 --> 03:21:27.440
[Guest]: I look at the world so I mean that is when I decided that this whole Kannada pride thing

03:21:27.440 --> 03:21:32.480
[Guest]: had because I had written I think I translated a piece in for Deccanary called Kannada pride

03:21:32.480 --> 03:21:38.880
[Guest]: and prejudice for the one of the November issues and I showed it to him and then he

03:21:38.880 --> 03:21:45.560
[Guest]: said how that idea can be sort of expanded why you should not sort of limit yourself

03:21:45.560 --> 03:21:51.720
[Guest]: to you know I mean one particular stream how you can actually make it richer by sort of

03:21:51.720 --> 03:21:55.960
[Guest]: taking in other things and exploring it there and language is a great dynamic you know I

03:21:55.960 --> 03:22:00.760
[Guest]: mean you put it into your language it becomes something else it is like you know in a recipe

03:22:00.760 --> 03:22:05.360
[Guest]: where you mix a certain ingredient it becomes a separate dish so he said you should you

03:22:05.360 --> 03:22:09.880
[Guest]: should sort of start exploring these things and then for the first time there was a huge

03:22:09.880 --> 03:22:14.680
[Guest]: problem of migrants and there was this very harsh rhetoric that was being spoken in the

03:22:14.680 --> 03:22:21.320
[Guest]: papers and British tabloids you know how they so he would tell me stories about migrants

03:22:21.320 --> 03:22:26.680
[Guest]: and he would tell me why we shouldn't speak this language what is the history of the world

03:22:26.680 --> 03:22:31.840
[Guest]: what is the history of migration and why you know these politicians are wrong and why you

03:22:31.840 --> 03:22:36.120
[Guest]: should go and listen to that fellow who's talking at the completely nonsensical thing

03:22:36.120 --> 03:22:40.720
[Guest]: but then you come back to me and tell me what he spoke and I'll tell you why that is wrong

03:22:40.720 --> 03:22:46.160
[Guest]: and why you should always sort of have a broad worldview and inclusive worldview but also

03:22:46.160 --> 03:22:52.040
[Guest]: be extremely conscious of the kind of atrocities committed by people in power how the policies

03:22:52.040 --> 03:22:57.960
[Guest]: are shaped to suit a handful of people so he would give me examples and there was a

03:22:57.960 --> 03:23:02.520
[Guest]: huge influx of Russian money at that time that had just about started I think at that

03:23:02.520 --> 03:23:06.200
[Guest]: time so we would we used to sort of whenever we went for a walk you would say see this

03:23:06.200 --> 03:23:11.440
[Guest]: is bought up by some some billionaire in Russia who's a faceless guy there's only a small

03:23:11.440 --> 03:23:16.880
[Guest]: little outhouse where a servant stays and this house has never been lit up fully it

03:23:16.880 --> 03:23:22.000
[Guest]: is just that little light that glows you know I mean he had a very poetic language he's

03:23:22.000 --> 03:23:28.560
[Guest]: a he had a polemical sense he is he was superb in that sense and he had visited India innumerable

03:23:28.560 --> 03:23:33.240
[Guest]: number of times and he had friends here he had written a lovely book for Pluto Press

03:23:33.240 --> 03:23:38.640
[Guest]: called Another India and he was quite well known in Bangladesh because he had learnt

03:23:38.640 --> 03:23:42.960
[Guest]: I mean he had worked very closely with the government workers there the workers there

03:23:42.960 --> 03:23:48.480
[Guest]: and written a lot and he had worked in Thailand so he has extremely was very very familiar

03:23:48.480 --> 03:23:53.960
[Guest]: with South Asia so the moment I said something he would just you know build the chain in

03:23:53.960 --> 03:23:58.440
[Guest]: such a way that it would be became started becoming very fascinating so for the first

03:23:58.440 --> 03:24:03.320
[Guest]: time when I went to England I started reading newspapers completely differently I wouldn't

03:24:03.320 --> 03:24:07.480
[Guest]: start with the supplements I would start with the front page and then go to the edit page

03:24:07.480 --> 03:24:12.160
[Guest]: read the edit in a very serious I would read edits here I would throw sort of do all that

03:24:12.160 --> 03:24:18.920
[Guest]: here but you know the way I looked at a newspaper itself changed because the way I looked at

03:24:18.920 --> 03:24:24.520
[Guest]: the world had changed can you elaborate on that yeah that is because this these inputs

03:24:24.520 --> 03:24:31.000
[Guest]: were being given to me and what was appearing in newspapers I was allowed to critique them

03:24:31.000 --> 03:24:36.320
[Guest]: so there were certain newspapers which were speaking a language of foul language and a

03:24:36.320 --> 03:24:41.400
[Guest]: very unwelcome language about immigrants and then there was this teacher here a great teacher

03:24:41.400 --> 03:24:46.280
[Guest]: was telling me that but Great Britain's economy was built by immigrants see look at how much

03:24:46.280 --> 03:24:50.760
[Guest]: they have contributed and he was he was from Northampton he had studied at Cambridge he

03:24:50.760 --> 03:24:55.640
[Guest]: was a local person and when a local person tells you that it becomes far more authentic

03:24:55.640 --> 03:25:01.040
[Guest]: so then then you start transport when transpose yourself into the Canada situation and you're

03:25:01.040 --> 03:25:08.240
[Guest]: sitting here and if you say that that fellow who's a Hindiwala or a Marwadi or a Bengali

03:25:08.240 --> 03:25:14.160
[Guest]: fellow so I became extremely conscious and I said I shouldn't talk that language that

03:25:14.160 --> 03:25:18.960
[Guest]: is not the language that has to be spoken in a civilized world so look at how Jeremy

03:25:18.960 --> 03:25:24.080
[Guest]: is speaking about people who have come to his land to his city and have made a life

03:25:24.080 --> 03:25:28.680
[Guest]: there and and sort of enriched that thing in fact he wrote a intellectual history of

03:25:28.680 --> 03:25:34.400
[Guest]: immigrants later which was I think released in the House of Commons later so it's a it's

03:25:34.400 --> 03:25:40.520
[Guest]: a thick fat book so he was he was that is the the way I looked at newspapers change

03:25:40.520 --> 03:25:45.840
[Guest]: because there was a teacher who was telling me see you've come yourself to come here to

03:25:45.840 --> 03:25:51.640
[Guest]: sort of train yourself to become an editor later or become a better journalist so you

03:25:51.640 --> 03:25:58.040
[Guest]: have to lot of absorb all these things and then of course there was I read Harold Evans

03:25:58.040 --> 03:26:03.360
[Guest]: very seriously the good times and the bad times and the Murdochian revolution was taking

03:26:03.360 --> 03:26:09.120
[Guest]: place so then the whole thing was getting dismantled the layoffs was happening I read

03:26:09.120 --> 03:26:13.440
[Guest]: John Pilger very very seriously when I went there because I think I went and listened

03:26:13.440 --> 03:26:18.400
[Guest]: to a lecture that he was giving somewhere and then he had problematized all this whole

03:26:18.400 --> 03:26:24.440
[Guest]: revolution that was taking place inside journalism the commodification the the kind of straight

03:26:24.440 --> 03:26:31.000
[Guest]: jacketing of ideas the kind of dumbing down you know reduction of pages for literature

03:26:31.000 --> 03:26:37.040
[Guest]: or whatever all that sort of you know was put into a context for me when I went to England

03:26:37.040 --> 03:26:41.160
[Guest]: and then there was a magazine that used to come to Jeremy's I was used to I think write

03:26:41.160 --> 03:26:45.160
[Guest]: also for the New Internationalist so he used to say New Internationalist had a completely

03:26:45.160 --> 03:26:49.400
[Guest]: different perspective of the world and there was New Statesman of course and there was

03:26:49.400 --> 03:26:54.240
[Guest]: the bunch of other magazines and then you went out to make calls to India there was

03:26:54.240 --> 03:27:00.200
[Guest]: these red little booths and you saw all these porn stickers stuck there saying call this

03:27:00.200 --> 03:27:03.960
[Guest]: number I am available you know those that was also a shock there was Soho and there

03:27:03.960 --> 03:27:10.440
[Guest]: was all those things it culturally shook you up and saying that oh the world that you imagined

03:27:10.440 --> 03:27:15.960
[Guest]: staying in Bangalore all these years is not just Maleshwaram or Basangudi here you are

03:27:15.960 --> 03:27:22.600
[Guest]: not even willing to accept the cantonment and here you are in this huge big city that

03:27:22.600 --> 03:27:29.280
[Guest]: everything is so very big so it I became completely conscious of that fact that what I know what

03:27:29.280 --> 03:27:34.240
[Guest]: I understand what I perceive is very very limited it's better to be humble and pick

03:27:34.240 --> 03:27:39.800
[Guest]: up things as I go on rather than be didactic and say I am right I have come from India

03:27:39.800 --> 03:27:45.880
[Guest]: it's a great culture I have a family like this my father is this so and so and my father

03:27:45.880 --> 03:27:51.160
[Guest]: was a very influential figure in Canada so I mean I had gone with that baggage but then

03:27:51.160 --> 03:27:58.480
[Guest]: it sobered me down so much and then that changed my journalism so it was basically a shock

03:27:58.480 --> 03:28:03.440
[Guest]: and then because I was into this there was a placement thing that would happen as part

03:28:03.440 --> 03:28:10.320
[Guest]: of the fellowship and I think it was John Deluxe idea to send me to Irish times in Dublin

03:28:10.320 --> 03:28:16.680
[Guest]: so I went from one city to another European city and that oh my god that was completely

03:28:16.680 --> 03:28:22.880
[Guest]: different from London and here you know people would you know very very with great difficulty

03:28:22.880 --> 03:28:27.480
[Guest]: nod at you or smile at you when you're in the tube or when you were walking on the street

03:28:27.480 --> 03:28:32.560
[Guest]: or in the supermarket and supermarket was not so difficult because you had Indians but

03:28:32.560 --> 03:28:38.400
[Guest]: you went to Southall to bring your masala and stuff like that but here in Dublin the

03:28:38.400 --> 03:28:44.880
[Guest]: very first encounter was different you know I met this editor called Kiran Fagan and Kiran

03:28:44.880 --> 03:28:48.560
[Guest]: said what are you doing here come let's have a drink so that was a completely different

03:28:48.560 --> 03:28:53.760
[Guest]: language it's not that I was much of a drinker or whatever I mean I did not sort of alcohol

03:28:53.760 --> 03:28:58.880
[Guest]: you know I mean my family was a vegetarian family because you know there was a this whole

03:28:58.880 --> 03:29:04.080
[Guest]: process of Sanskritization that Ambedkar and later MN Srinivas speak about which was I

03:29:04.080 --> 03:29:09.160
[Guest]: think part of that part of that family construct that if you are you know elevating yourself

03:29:09.160 --> 03:29:13.040
[Guest]: you have to give up these things and they were more loyal to the Sringeri mutt and the

03:29:13.040 --> 03:29:18.800
[Guest]: Shankar mutt and all that so here was I go there and this man who's supposedly you know

03:29:18.800 --> 03:29:22.520
[Guest]: going to take care of me for the next few months and he's saying come let's have a drink

03:29:22.520 --> 03:29:27.800
[Guest]: and he's sort of giving getting me the dark stout thing you know and he asked me saying

03:29:27.800 --> 03:29:32.360
[Guest]: they just taste it it's not going to knock you off and then one comes the second one

03:29:32.360 --> 03:29:39.960
[Guest]: comes and then I'm I become very very so I mean my this whole inside the I mean it sort

03:29:39.960 --> 03:29:46.360
[Guest]: of I became this moralistic there's this element of moral thing fiber that gets woven into

03:29:46.360 --> 03:29:52.560
[Guest]: your learning and reading and all that if you are in a certain setup and that you know

03:29:52.560 --> 03:29:57.440
[Guest]: you choose because if you drink you think you're a bad man if you smoke you're you get

03:29:57.440 --> 03:30:04.040
[Guest]: you start to start you know classifying people like that oh he has bad habits so drinking

03:30:04.040 --> 03:30:10.320
[Guest]: was a bad habit which was sort of put into me very early in my life eating non-vegetarian

03:30:10.320 --> 03:30:16.640
[Guest]: food was a was not such a welcome thing smoking is no no you know that kind of a thing because

03:30:16.640 --> 03:30:22.720
[Guest]: my parents and my grandparents were all in that kind of a bubble and you learn to judge

03:30:22.720 --> 03:30:28.320
[Guest]: people on the basis of their habits or their orientation that orientation was still not

03:30:28.320 --> 03:30:35.920
[Guest]: clear to me gay or being a being a LGBT person you never learned all that here you know because

03:30:35.920 --> 03:30:40.800
[Guest]: your culture never even people did not even bring it on their lips and their tongues and

03:30:40.800 --> 03:30:46.880
[Guest]: this but all of that started becoming opening up there so you went here and you first thing

03:30:46.880 --> 03:30:51.120
[Guest]: that the man says who's using a senior who's supposed to take care of you says come let's

03:30:51.120 --> 03:30:56.440
[Guest]: have a drink and that completely brought down walls for me and it was such a fascinating

03:30:56.440 --> 03:31:02.760
[Guest]: you're such a great good man he was he treated you as an equal he took you there to the pub

03:31:02.760 --> 03:31:06.800
[Guest]: and then he bought you a drink and then he put you into the newsroom and he put you and

03:31:06.800 --> 03:31:11.800
[Guest]: he sort of made such a gave such a glowing introduction to all his senior colleagues

03:31:11.800 --> 03:31:16.880
[Guest]: and the other senior editors he said he's a bright young man who's got the finest fellowship

03:31:16.880 --> 03:31:21.480
[Guest]: and he's come from India he was in London but the London people have some good sense

03:31:21.480 --> 03:31:26.040
[Guest]: they have given him to us so we have to sort of take care of me I want him to go back with

03:31:26.040 --> 03:31:32.360
[Guest]: good memories that's what he said what a remarkable man he was and then he then said Caroline

03:31:32.360 --> 03:31:37.640
[Guest]: this boy I think knows a lot of English literature you you will find him use useful so why don't

03:31:37.640 --> 03:31:42.440
[Guest]: you sort of speak to him you know the people were so welcoming and they would take me home

03:31:42.440 --> 03:31:47.000
[Guest]: in England I except for my mentors drawing room I would have I had not entered anybody's

03:31:47.000 --> 03:31:52.520
[Guest]: home and here people said you come home Saturday oh come we'll go trekking yo we'll go to that

03:31:52.520 --> 03:31:57.720
[Guest]: island the things like that started happening I used to share an apartment with a lady called

03:31:57.720 --> 03:32:02.920
[Guest]: Barbara Clinton and this lady is again you know I mean she was working with another rival

03:32:02.920 --> 03:32:08.760
[Guest]: newspaper or I think she was doing some work for other newspapers and she was a single

03:32:08.760 --> 03:32:13.800
[Guest]: lady and she was again very welcoming in her home you know I mean this whole dynamics changes

03:32:13.800 --> 03:32:20.440
[Guest]: right you're a Hindu boy provincial boy going to England staying in an apartment shared

03:32:20.440 --> 03:32:25.680
[Guest]: with by another lady and you are you don't know whether you have to tell your parents

03:32:25.680 --> 03:32:30.080
[Guest]: or your mother especially that you know is this lady also living with me I mean it's

03:32:30.080 --> 03:32:36.400
[Guest]: all perfectly normal there and you learn to navigate those choppy waters or which is cultural

03:32:36.400 --> 03:32:42.800
[Guest]: shock for you and because nobody in my family had gone abroad to study my father was so

03:32:42.800 --> 03:32:48.480
[Guest]: enlightened but he had never crossed the seas he went abroad much later after all of us

03:32:48.480 --> 03:32:52.920
[Guest]: took him abroad he went to Europe and my brother settled down in the US and became a citizen

03:32:52.920 --> 03:32:59.200
[Guest]: there so he facilitated it much later but all of that came later for him England he

03:32:59.200 --> 03:33:05.840
[Guest]: would he could speak so beautifully about London streets through his reading he could

03:33:05.840 --> 03:33:12.240
[Guest]: speak of you know I mean Russia so you know I mean with such passion I mean that through

03:33:12.240 --> 03:33:16.920
[Guest]: his reading so everything was a textual kind of a thing that had reached him but he had

03:33:16.920 --> 03:33:23.320
[Guest]: never crossed the seas physically so this was for me you know in a lot of ways it opened

03:33:23.320 --> 03:33:30.920
[Guest]: up and so journalism obviously had to be a cosmopolitan idea it could not have been a

03:33:30.920 --> 03:33:35.800
[Guest]: kind of narrow whatever agenda with which you drive it so it was a cosmopolitan thing

03:33:35.800 --> 03:33:40.780
[Guest]: because you had benefited from it and you had seen it function you had seen the great

03:33:40.780 --> 03:33:48.080
[Guest]: examples there and so then I did I had to figure out where does Canada figure if I am

03:33:48.080 --> 03:33:53.760
[Guest]: trying to embrace the world with such speed so Canada has to be somewhere it can't go

03:33:53.760 --> 03:33:57.960
[Guest]: away and even if I want to sort of you know flush it down it won't go away so how does

03:33:57.960 --> 03:34:05.680
[Guest]: it work out so that is when Jeremy sort of navigated my journey and he said that you

03:34:05.680 --> 03:34:10.760
[Guest]: can be for the first time I think I heard it from him he said you can be rootedly cosmopolitan

03:34:10.760 --> 03:34:16.640
[Guest]: that's such a lovely phrase rootedly cosmopolitan and I use it much a lot in my writing later

03:34:16.640 --> 03:34:21.760
[Guest]: I've used it later and I don't think I've attributed to my guru because guru is part

03:34:21.760 --> 03:34:26.360
[Guest]: of me you know I there is sort of invoke the Indian thing I mean I am part of him and he's

03:34:26.360 --> 03:34:31.120
[Guest]: part of me so I mean it's like the guru shishya parampara so what is his is mine you know

03:34:31.120 --> 03:34:36.080
[Guest]: that kind of a thing so he used it very very I don't think he used it in the exact same

03:34:36.080 --> 03:34:41.640
[Guest]: way but then he spoke about you can be rooted and you can be cosmopolitan at the same time

03:34:41.640 --> 03:34:47.760
[Guest]: and your cosmopolitanism is not confined to the English language alone because there was

03:34:47.760 --> 03:34:53.080
[Guest]: this construct that if you had to be cosmopolitan you had to speak the English language and

03:34:53.080 --> 03:34:57.320
[Guest]: if you are living in Bangalore if you want to appear cosmopolitan you have to go to Koshy's

03:34:57.320 --> 03:35:02.800
[Guest]: and come to the MG road and roam around the brigade road looking at all the girls in many

03:35:02.800 --> 03:35:08.280
[Guest]: skirts and go back and say that oh I've had a cosmopolitan experience so so that those

03:35:08.280 --> 03:35:15.000
[Guest]: notions of the English divide of the other all of that sort of sort of this great man

03:35:15.000 --> 03:35:21.800
[Guest]: sort of you know pushed me to sort of I mean it made me dismantle all of it so it more

03:35:21.800 --> 03:35:26.520
[Guest]: than say again as I told you earlier Amit it was not it was not always trying to bring

03:35:26.520 --> 03:35:32.600
[Guest]: correctives to my journalism it was about everything so if you bought correctives to

03:35:32.600 --> 03:35:36.960
[Guest]: the way you look at then your journalism automatically changes the kind of topics that you pick to

03:35:36.960 --> 03:35:41.240
[Guest]: write will change the kind of you know I mean language you use will change the diction will

03:35:41.240 --> 03:35:46.920
[Guest]: change the tone will change the way you approach people will change so with all this I came

03:35:46.920 --> 03:35:53.000
[Guest]: back to India and I would have happily settled down in Dublin but then there was a huge labor

03:35:53.000 --> 03:35:57.360
[Guest]: problem and union problem and all that they could not have absorbed me although they were

03:35:57.360 --> 03:36:01.700
[Guest]: very very kind and they said we want you for more and they gave me a lovely letter at the

03:36:01.700 --> 03:36:07.680
[Guest]: end of the day I still preserve and I mean I feel a little embarrassed to frame it or

03:36:07.680 --> 03:36:13.520
[Guest]: whatever but then they said Sugata was here and he was such a great colleague and he was

03:36:13.520 --> 03:36:18.600
[Guest]: there on the South Asia desk and LTT problem was big those days so then I used to sort

03:36:18.600 --> 03:36:23.080
[Guest]: of write a few copies on that and then he had special interest in Irish language thing

03:36:23.080 --> 03:36:29.680
[Guest]: and all that but his knowledge of English literature put all of us to shame was the

03:36:29.680 --> 03:36:34.880
[Guest]: I mean can you believe somebody writing that in a letter of recommendation or a letter

03:36:34.880 --> 03:36:42.040
[Guest]: of whatever I mean there was there such good people you know and I felt that I was a mini

03:36:42.040 --> 03:36:48.080
[Guest]: success and I came back to India and here then of course I went to Jaipur and Veer Sanghvi

03:36:48.080 --> 03:36:53.800
[Guest]: had taken over the Hindustan Times and there was nobody to go to Jaipur to look after the

03:36:53.800 --> 03:37:00.160
[Guest]: news desk so I went there as a news editor and with all this baggage and in a new culture

03:37:00.160 --> 03:37:08.400
[Guest]: and Godhra was just happening and I was just put in the middle of elections and riots and

03:37:08.400 --> 03:37:13.160
[Guest]: all that and I had to figure this all out which I had not until then because I was in

03:37:13.160 --> 03:37:19.080
[Guest]: this very secure cultural literary bubble in Deccan Herald and England had sort of shaken

03:37:19.080 --> 03:37:26.040
[Guest]: me up given me a way to look at all this but then I was now actually thrown there I was

03:37:26.040 --> 03:37:32.360
[Guest]: a young news editor a very young person and I had people who had served the organization

03:37:32.360 --> 03:37:37.520
[Guest]: for 30 years 25 years there and I had to handle them there was a young team also but there

03:37:37.520 --> 03:37:45.400
[Guest]: was I had to reconcile and so my whole approach of managing reconciling these age differences

03:37:45.400 --> 03:37:49.800
[Guest]: these language differences cultural difference all of them were put to very good use because

03:37:49.800 --> 03:37:55.640
[Guest]: I had had a good primer you know I mean so I mean I was I handled it and people accepted

03:37:55.640 --> 03:38:01.520
[Guest]: me they were good people they were nice people again I was not too it was not too problematic

03:38:01.520 --> 03:38:06.480
[Guest]: for me to adjust to the new environment and there for the first time I handled assembly

03:38:06.480 --> 03:38:13.320
[Guest]: elections on my own I created packages I created I got I developed a fascination for polo I

03:38:13.320 --> 03:38:17.160
[Guest]: still keep in touch with a lot of my friends who played polo there and there was a bit

03:38:17.160 --> 03:38:21.720
[Guest]: of royalty thing so then you know you just that rubbed off on you a little so I used

03:38:21.720 --> 03:38:27.680
[Guest]: to bring out a monthly supplement called polo passion because polo was big so I mean I had

03:38:27.680 --> 03:38:33.560
[Guest]: very generous colleagues I had a very generous resident editor initially he moved on he later

03:38:33.560 --> 03:38:37.840
[Guest]: and then he I mean pretty much I was left to run the place you know and that was very

03:38:37.840 --> 03:38:44.480
[Guest]: incredible of the people of people and there this whole again new thing there again I looked

03:38:44.480 --> 03:38:51.960
[Guest]: at the language issue there I looked at oral histories because oral history was big and

03:38:51.960 --> 03:38:57.840
[Guest]: so I looked at royalties I sort of made friends with some people like I mean I never thought

03:38:57.840 --> 03:39:03.480
[Guest]: I'll meet the big man Bhairav Singh Shakawat but then I he took to me somehow you know

03:39:03.480 --> 03:39:10.400
[Guest]: I mean I was pretty lucky about that and then I then one fine day I got a call from Delhi

03:39:10.400 --> 03:39:16.440
[Guest]: and Outlook asking if I would like to run their south and the elections were coming

03:39:16.440 --> 03:39:23.920
[Guest]: and 2004 is when I moved to the Outlook magazine and it was always by then you know I mean

03:39:23.920 --> 03:39:30.880
[Guest]: my father had created this very lovely image of Vinod and the Sunday Observer and then

03:39:30.880 --> 03:39:36.960
[Guest]: he used to tell me that he also edited a magazine which was not you know I mean a literary magazine

03:39:36.960 --> 03:39:42.600
[Guest]: but it was a great magazine he would never tell me it was Debonair something would stop

03:39:42.600 --> 03:39:47.200
[Guest]: him from telling me that it was so Sunday Observer I think he was very he had watched

03:39:47.200 --> 03:39:52.080
[Guest]: it closely he had seen Outlook we had I still remember the sample issue of Outlook reaching

03:39:52.080 --> 03:39:58.400
[Guest]: our home so we had seen all that and somewhere in the corner of my mind by then I had realized

03:39:58.400 --> 03:40:05.120
[Guest]: that here is a great editor a great man who seems to be very liberal who gives you your

03:40:05.120 --> 03:40:10.240
[Guest]: space and allows you to do your thing so if at all if it's possible I think I should work

03:40:10.240 --> 03:40:18.920
[Guest]: with him one day and that dream came true in 2004 and I stayed with Vinod till the day

03:40:18.920 --> 03:40:26.280
[Guest]: he retired so I mean I had a job offer and I went and told him and he said I'll walk

03:40:26.280 --> 03:40:31.760
[Guest]: to the sunset stay with me until I'm there and he took eight months or one year to leave

03:40:31.760 --> 03:40:36.760
[Guest]: so I had to keep that job with the Times of India in abeyance for that long and then I

03:40:36.760 --> 03:40:40.920
[Guest]: came and took over as the editor-in-chief of Vijay Karnataka their biggest regional

03:40:40.920 --> 03:40:46.360
[Guest]: paper which was making a lot of money but money yes but then it was completely on the

03:40:46.360 --> 03:40:51.640
[Guest]: right so they wanted they had bought that paper from another person and they wanted

03:40:51.640 --> 03:40:56.280
[Guest]: me to sort of bring it to the center make it more acceptable so that their intention

03:40:56.280 --> 03:41:03.300
[Guest]: was to make it more commercially viable so that big advertisers come in for me it coincided

03:41:03.300 --> 03:41:08.800
[Guest]: with my mission of making it centrist and making it more liberal so there was a kind

03:41:08.800 --> 03:41:15.200
[Guest]: of thing together which is running parallel so I think I flourished there it was a real

03:41:15.200 --> 03:41:22.160
[Guest]: big success so I did not have a problem again transiting from English to Canada because

03:41:22.160 --> 03:41:26.600
[Guest]: I was anyway a bilingual and I was offered this job because I'm a bilingual but Outlook

03:41:26.600 --> 03:41:31.880
[Guest]: was a great phase and Outlook became such a enormous thing because it turned me into

03:41:31.880 --> 03:41:37.600
[Guest]: an investigative journalist it turned me into a political commentator and writer and I was

03:41:37.600 --> 03:41:43.720
[Guest]: probably the only one to have this record I've written every single week in the magazine

03:41:43.720 --> 03:41:50.680
[Guest]: since the day I joined and my very first piece was a cover story which is everybody here

03:41:50.680 --> 03:41:56.440
[Guest]: I came to Karnataka again see the perspectives that you developed become so interesting that

03:41:56.440 --> 03:42:02.760
[Guest]: I came to Karnataka for the 2004 elections so 2004 there was assembly and parliamentary

03:42:02.760 --> 03:42:08.400
[Guest]: elections happening and I came here and everybody I met was saying Krishna is SM Krishna is

03:42:08.400 --> 03:42:13.520
[Guest]: going to come back to power so I said okay TK you're saying this let me go and look around

03:42:13.520 --> 03:42:18.040
[Guest]: so I went to the hinterlands I went to the different districts I traveled quite a bit

03:42:18.040 --> 03:42:22.440
[Guest]: see Vinod was very liberal with all that you could just travel and he did not confine me

03:42:22.440 --> 03:42:27.160
[Guest]: to Karnataka I was covering the entire south I could go anywhere I want I had to just write

03:42:27.160 --> 03:42:31.800
[Guest]: this proposal and send it a give an interesting idea and then I had a very interesting and

03:42:31.800 --> 03:42:38.400
[Guest]: a very fine editor who was the political editor was Mr. Ajit Pillai and Ajit Pillai and Vinod

03:42:38.400 --> 03:42:46.160
[Guest]: Mehta Vinod himself describes him as a very dear colleague and so Ajit was not like other

03:42:46.160 --> 03:42:50.760
[Guest]: editors in between your top man and you who would snatch your ideas and make it their

03:42:50.760 --> 03:42:58.040
[Guest]: own and you know he was a he was a man with great rectitude and great moral bearing and

03:42:58.040 --> 03:43:01.920
[Guest]: he encouraged me he whenever a great idea was there he would say don't worry I will

03:43:01.920 --> 03:43:06.480
[Guest]: tell Vinod you travel because Vinod is busy I will tell him on Saturday or whatever you

03:43:06.480 --> 03:43:10.360
[Guest]: travel it's okay I have given you the consent so initially you know that meant mattered

03:43:10.360 --> 03:43:16.280
[Guest]: a lot although you were a senior guy and all that and there was the reporting structure

03:43:16.280 --> 03:43:22.120
[Guest]: you always had to sort of convince Vinod through him and and once Vinod saw that he started

03:43:22.120 --> 03:43:29.480
[Guest]: talking to me directly and of course Ajit would be looped in but we developed this bond

03:43:29.480 --> 03:43:34.320
[Guest]: where Vinod knew I was a little stuck up kind of a character who would you know it was not

03:43:34.320 --> 03:43:39.080
[Guest]: very comfortable speaking these small things of life but only speak of big ideas and big

03:43:39.080 --> 03:43:44.040
[Guest]: things so whenever we had this arrangement where Vinod would call me every Saturday at

03:43:44.040 --> 03:43:52.240
[Guest]: seven o'clock this was an you know I mean an editor of Vinod's stature having a contact

03:43:52.240 --> 03:43:56.800
[Guest]: with his bureau head down south with this manner itself was a very interesting thing

03:43:56.800 --> 03:44:01.720
[Guest]: so he used to call me at seven and he would never ask me what story you're doing he would

03:44:01.720 --> 03:44:07.560
[Guest]: only say who's sleeping with who what is that happening what is that gossip that I hear

03:44:07.560 --> 03:44:11.760
[Guest]: why is that fellow behaving like that is he sleeping with somebody you know I mean Vinod

03:44:11.760 --> 03:44:16.920
[Guest]: was so much on the gossip side initially it shocked me I would say I mean I would all

03:44:16.920 --> 03:44:21.480
[Guest]: all be ready to you know just tell him that this is happening sir that is happening next

03:44:21.480 --> 03:44:26.120
[Guest]: week we should look at this and I think this is the the the idea that we pursued last time

03:44:26.120 --> 03:44:30.640
[Guest]: is not really working but Vinod would lighten the whole thing he would not talk about ideas

03:44:30.640 --> 03:44:34.760
[Guest]: at all and then when I tried to insert he would say no tell that to Ajit, Ajit will

03:44:34.760 --> 03:44:39.680
[Guest]: take care of it don't worry you tell me the gossip so so so he would come here we would

03:44:39.680 --> 03:44:46.520
[Guest]: have great time hopping bar hopping pubs and restaurants so the idea of an editor how I

03:44:46.520 --> 03:44:54.200
[Guest]: should behave as an elder in the newsroom when I if and when I became an editor at that

03:44:54.200 --> 03:45:00.400
[Guest]: time was again Vinod Mehta became a model he was he I mean a lot of people may have

03:45:00.400 --> 03:45:06.000
[Guest]: a lot of stories to say but with me you know I mean I always got you know I mean a great

03:45:06.000 --> 03:45:11.040
[Guest]: response from Vinod and he never curtailed me on anything in fact when I did the very

03:45:11.040 --> 03:45:18.000
[Guest]: big story in 2005 on the Infosys land scam that was a big story when everybody was speaking

03:45:18.000 --> 03:45:24.480
[Guest]: gaga about the Infosys and all that I knew that they were you know making putting making

03:45:24.480 --> 03:45:30.520
[Guest]: petitions for more land and when when they had not actually used what was already with

03:45:30.520 --> 03:45:37.120
[Guest]: them and they were making all these projections and all that and I wanted to do a story because

03:45:37.120 --> 03:45:44.920
[Guest]: I had some documents and all that and it still not reached me but then I had seen them so

03:45:44.920 --> 03:45:49.040
[Guest]: and there was this big debate that was happening in Karnataka as to why they are greedy after

03:45:49.040 --> 03:45:55.080
[Guest]: land and all that so I suggested the idea and Vinod said yeah go ahead no problem so

03:45:55.080 --> 03:45:59.760
[Guest]: I wrote this story and then he called me on a Wednesday he said are you sure of all that

03:45:59.760 --> 03:46:04.400
[Guest]: you've written because by then he had started getting calls from various quarters saying

03:46:04.400 --> 03:46:09.400
[Guest]: somebody had leaked that this story is happening and he said I've been getting calls are you

03:46:09.400 --> 03:46:14.400
[Guest]: sure of what you've written I said yes sir then he would insist that I call him Vinod

03:46:14.400 --> 03:46:21.040
[Guest]: but then I would never say I could never do it so I yes I said I'm pretty sure I've checked

03:46:21.040 --> 03:46:25.200
[Guest]: looked up my facts and all that he said do you have doc do you have the documents which

03:46:25.200 --> 03:46:30.040
[Guest]: support all that you're saying I said sir I have seen all of it this person has promised

03:46:30.040 --> 03:46:35.760
[Guest]: that he'll give it to me on a Friday but he said but we go to press on the Thursday or

03:46:35.760 --> 03:46:40.240
[Guest]: your form is going to the press on Thursday how what we what shall we do you know I mean

03:46:40.240 --> 03:46:45.400
[Guest]: if you're going to get the documents on Friday have you seen it are you very sure are you

03:46:45.400 --> 03:46:53.400
[Guest]: bakka and this is my first year in Outlook 2005 I said sir I'm pretty much sure it was

03:46:53.400 --> 03:47:00.600
[Guest]: yeah second year in Outlook 2004 I joined so he said okay then okay I'll run it because

03:47:00.600 --> 03:47:05.560
[Guest]: he sort of gave himself this reason he said too many people are calling so it must be

03:47:05.560 --> 03:47:12.240
[Guest]: correct Wow superb he said too many are calling it must be correct we go down we go down together

03:47:12.240 --> 03:47:20.080
[Guest]: don't worry I'll run it it was a five page thing it's just went on the thing and that

03:47:20.080 --> 03:47:26.160
[Guest]: was a great moment and then on a Friday I got all the documents I just faxed them to

03:47:26.160 --> 03:47:31.800
[Guest]: Ajit and I said I've got everything so nothing to worry and then again Saturday the call

03:47:31.800 --> 03:47:38.880
[Guest]: comes at seven o'clock and he is laughing and he said have we restored the balance I

03:47:38.880 --> 03:47:45.760
[Guest]: said yes sir so he said everything is quiet and silent and people are appreciating what

03:47:45.760 --> 03:47:51.200
[Guest]: you have written so it must be true it is correct so he said don't stop with this story

03:47:51.200 --> 03:47:57.680
[Guest]: it has done well so do two more let's make it a series so I started scrambling for more

03:47:57.680 --> 03:48:02.720
[Guest]: documents and then I realized that SM Krishna had preferential shares in Infosys then I

03:48:02.720 --> 03:48:11.000
[Guest]: realized that his son-in-law who I mean drowned himself again had dealt with I mean had underwritten

03:48:11.000 --> 03:48:16.240
[Guest]: the Infosys IPO and there was a great deal of involvement between these two and then

03:48:16.240 --> 03:48:22.280
[Guest]: Krishna had accommodated a lot of Infosys people in his administration you know urban

03:48:22.280 --> 03:48:28.320
[Guest]: infrastructure airport so there was a lot of conflict of interest so I wrote that and

03:48:28.320 --> 03:48:34.720
[Guest]: then of course I at that point of time Mr. Mohandas Pai was still part of Infosys and

03:48:34.720 --> 03:48:39.120
[Guest]: then he said I want to meet I said I'll come to your office and then I can never forget

03:48:39.120 --> 03:48:44.960
[Guest]: that conversation that happened between him and me and I said I stand by what I write

03:48:44.960 --> 03:48:51.040
[Guest]: so then they sent a kind of rejoinder to my piece and at the end of the last line was

03:48:51.040 --> 03:48:56.680
[Guest]: this is only for your understanding not to print so I still keep that percent from one

03:48:56.680 --> 03:49:05.160
[Guest]: of the PR people so that story was not contested so it was great so that was sort of give confidence

03:49:05.160 --> 03:49:12.440
[Guest]: to Vinod and that led to my big even bigger story that is the breaking of the mining scam

03:49:12.440 --> 03:49:17.880
[Guest]: in Pallari so we went with the headline the Reddy Republic when even when the world had

03:49:17.880 --> 03:49:22.920
[Guest]: not woken up to anything like that the Loka Yukta had not woken up and the first criminal

03:49:22.920 --> 03:49:29.200
[Guest]: defamation case by the Reddy's the notorious Reddy's who finally got jailed was filed against

03:49:29.200 --> 03:49:34.840
[Guest]: Vinod Mehta and me the very first criminal defamation case so we felt vindicated after

03:49:34.840 --> 03:49:41.280
[Guest]: that also was proved but in between all of this Vinod knew that I was this I was my feature

03:49:41.280 --> 03:49:46.280
[Guest]: side was also very good not just the political and the other side and this SM Krishna thing

03:49:46.280 --> 03:49:50.800
[Guest]: when I came to Karnataka the first time the cover story that I first did I went around

03:49:50.800 --> 03:49:55.160
[Guest]: and I realized Krishna is losing I got a sense that this man is not going to come I wrote

03:49:55.160 --> 03:50:04.920
[Guest]: that Vinod published it he said Krishna and the covers cover was Krishna's photograph

03:50:04.920 --> 03:50:10.960
[Guest]: and Naidu's photograph and Krishna had a red light there and I had explained why Krishna

03:50:10.960 --> 03:50:16.520
[Guest]: may not come back and it turned out to be correct because although Krishna was very unhappy with

03:50:16.520 --> 03:50:21.880
[Guest]: what I had written and they sort of somebody from his side called me and they spoke badly

03:50:21.880 --> 03:50:28.720
[Guest]: I didn't really worry too much but that turned out to be correct so I think you know we journalists

03:50:28.720 --> 03:50:35.240
[Guest]: or reporters have to convince their writer editors not by taking fancy ideas to them

03:50:35.240 --> 03:50:39.600
[Guest]: but actually doing these stories and those stories turning out to be correct and that

03:50:39.600 --> 03:50:45.600
[Guest]: builds a relationship with your editor so he impulsively trusts what you're trying to

03:50:45.600 --> 03:50:49.920
[Guest]: tell him or trying to you know I mean the ideas that you're trying to give him and then

03:50:49.920 --> 03:50:55.440
[Guest]: he gives you a so finally it became an outlook or Sugata's what's true a story you would

03:50:55.440 --> 03:51:00.840
[Guest]: not even ask what it is you say okay one page enough two page enough it came down to that

03:51:00.840 --> 03:51:06.240
[Guest]: so you felt very happy and in between something very big happened which is the 10th anniversary

03:51:06.240 --> 03:51:13.360
[Guest]: of Outlook and I was made I was officially made the historian of Outlook so I wrote this

03:51:13.360 --> 03:51:18.080
[Guest]: longest essay I think the only competitor I had in Outlook was Arundhati Roy it was

03:51:18.080 --> 03:51:23.960
[Guest]: as long an essay as that which is titled the history of Outlook in ten and a half chapters

03:51:23.960 --> 03:51:29.480
[Guest]: it was ten years of Outlook and I begin with I mean I'd asked Julian Barnes to I thought

03:51:29.480 --> 03:51:34.080
[Guest]: of him when he told me that I'd asked him for a it was an eponymous title of course

03:51:34.080 --> 03:51:37.680
[Guest]: I'd asked him for a quote or something he had said I'm too busy or something I start

03:51:37.680 --> 03:51:43.840
[Guest]: with that and then I this went on and then for that 10th anniversary issue I sort of

03:51:43.840 --> 03:51:49.600
[Guest]: all my exposure to the to England and all that had came good because one is of course

03:51:49.600 --> 03:51:57.280
[Guest]: Julian Barnes which is incidental but then I interviewed Harold Evans I interviewed

03:51:57.280 --> 03:52:03.320
[Guest]: Shyam Lal the great Times of India's editor I mean I think I had a lot of pages in that

03:52:03.320 --> 03:52:07.960
[Guest]: you know the biggest essay was mine the cover story was mine and that was a very momentous

03:52:07.960 --> 03:52:13.360
[Guest]: occasion because it was ten years of Outlook an alternate magazine to India today had survived

03:52:13.360 --> 03:52:18.120
[Guest]: and Vinod was at his peak and when there was this party that was organized to celebrate

03:52:18.120 --> 03:52:24.040
[Guest]: in the evening so Vinod came looking for me he held my hand took me to Rajan Raheja the

03:52:24.040 --> 03:52:28.800
[Guest]: owner and he said he's the one who's written the history of Outlook and that was my finest

03:52:28.800 --> 03:52:35.120
[Guest]: moment Amit because you know I mean you always dreamt of Vinod Mehta and working for Vinod

03:52:35.120 --> 03:52:40.400
[Guest]: Mehta and here was a moment when he sort of you know I mean said well done and Vinod was

03:52:40.400 --> 03:52:47.000
[Guest]: very stingy with praise he would only say well done that's all and you had to even his

03:52:47.000 --> 03:52:52.560
[Guest]: appraisal letters used to be so very you know in increment letters used to be so very tighted

03:52:52.560 --> 03:52:57.880
[Guest]: just two lines and then he would if he really wanted to say that he meant it he would call

03:52:57.880 --> 03:53:02.960
[Guest]: and you would say well done well done keep it up keep it up that's all if he says I would

03:53:02.960 --> 03:53:08.080
[Guest]: tell my wife he said keep it up twice so which means he's trying to emphasize that thing

03:53:08.080 --> 03:53:14.920
[Guest]: so I used to be so alert to his phone calls the great man and he did not make he also

03:53:14.920 --> 03:53:23.960
[Guest]: taught me about financial probity he never made money he never you know built farmhouses

03:53:23.960 --> 03:53:31.880
[Guest]: and he did not sort of you know go on transatlantic trips and he did not like going to going and

03:53:31.880 --> 03:53:36.480
[Guest]: staying in five-star hotels used to come here and used to say he take me to some dosa place

03:53:36.480 --> 03:53:41.600
[Guest]: that corner thing that you took me last time on the footpath it was that kind of a so that

03:53:41.600 --> 03:53:47.480
[Guest]: taught me a lot of lessons without actually besides journalism of course besides the great

03:53:47.480 --> 03:53:55.360
[Guest]: journalism that he allowed us to do and that was it was a it was a he was living the role

03:53:55.360 --> 03:54:03.120
[Guest]: that I you know when I had imagined and it was a great it was a great great time for

03:54:03.120 --> 03:54:10.600
[Guest]: me when I I think I mean I used to then I when I became an editor I was trying to imitate

03:54:10.600 --> 03:54:16.640
[Guest]: Vinod many times trying to be accommodative trying to allow ideas to come inside the newsroom

03:54:16.640 --> 03:54:23.640
[Guest]: I brought in this practice of asking the junior most you know we had a panel you know the

03:54:23.640 --> 03:54:27.760
[Guest]: junior most in the newsroom should come and sit in the news meeting not just the seniors

03:54:27.760 --> 03:54:32.840
[Guest]: and they would absorb they could speak and I made this rule that the best idea wins not

03:54:32.840 --> 03:54:38.840
[Guest]: the senior who speaks you know does not get space it is the best idea that wins and these

03:54:38.840 --> 03:54:43.340
[Guest]: things you know I mean it was a very nice little cushy ride for the for three years

03:54:43.340 --> 03:54:49.400
[Guest]: and the Times of India's Vijay Karnataka and then of course Modi happened so that started

03:54:49.400 --> 03:54:55.220
[Guest]: disrupting things because I think they started orienting themselves differently and I was

03:54:55.220 --> 03:55:01.000
[Guest]: inconvenient although I had critical and commercial success the papers number we had touched a

03:55:01.000 --> 03:55:06.480
[Guest]: readership of nearly 8 million readership you know it's not very unnatural for a regional

03:55:06.480 --> 03:55:12.000
[Guest]: paper but it was huge for a Kannada paper because the market was a very small market

03:55:12.000 --> 03:55:17.980
[Guest]: for various historical reasons and it had expanded and the circulation had gone up revenues

03:55:17.980 --> 03:55:23.320
[Guest]: were good we were all being taken you know annual holidays to foreign countries so it

03:55:23.320 --> 03:55:30.720
[Guest]: was all very good until what he happened and that I think is a statement.

03:55:30.720 --> 03:55:37.040
[Amit Varma]: So here's a question that struck me has there been a time where it's Saturday and it's 7

03:55:37.040 --> 03:55:42.560
[Amit Varma]: p.m. and you're missing Vinod because that's a time he used to call?

03:55:42.560 --> 03:55:49.080
[Guest]: Initially yes I think you know I mean I was but also that seven o'clock call stopped after

03:55:49.080 --> 03:55:57.080
[Guest]: Vinod retired and I moved on and I started editing a Kannada beast called Vijay Karnataka

03:55:57.080 --> 03:56:02.720
[Guest]: and then of course I was then I mean yeah I think he passed away when I was with the

03:56:02.720 --> 03:56:10.800
[Guest]: Asianet whatever so that had broken in a way but then you know the mental association and

03:56:10.800 --> 03:56:15.520
[Guest]: I mean I always wanted to report back to Vinod saying that I have done this so that was always

03:56:15.520 --> 03:56:22.600
[Guest]: the basic thing you know I mean so if I'd got a if my newspaper broke a big story or

03:56:22.600 --> 03:56:27.840
[Guest]: if when I got a guy to sort of do something very interesting I just always felt that I

03:56:27.840 --> 03:56:31.920
[Guest]: should tell him and I would occasionally call him you know because it was also a kind of

03:56:31.920 --> 03:56:37.760
[Guest]: relationship where you know he's a very big man and he used to appear on television channels

03:56:37.760 --> 03:56:42.840
[Guest]: and used to be very busy also he kept himself very busy he was editorial chairman but then

03:56:42.840 --> 03:56:47.160
[Guest]: he used to still attend office and all that I would and it became a little complicated

03:56:47.160 --> 03:56:53.800
[Guest]: with others around and all that I didn't want to sort of cannibalize on his time and also

03:56:53.800 --> 03:56:59.360
[Guest]: but I would occasionally call him up and tell him that I wanted to tell you this and very

03:56:59.360 --> 03:57:04.440
[Guest]: briefly tell him that and my conversations on the phone are very formal so you know it's

03:57:04.440 --> 03:57:08.000
[Guest]: another thing when I'm sitting in front of him I can confess I can speak I can tell him

03:57:08.000 --> 03:57:13.960
[Guest]: that this happened so there were a few couple of occasions where I told him about the problems

03:57:13.960 --> 03:57:19.920
[Guest]: that I'm having in the newsroom and all that and he gave me some wonderful advice and when

03:57:19.920 --> 03:57:26.440
[Guest]: his Rahul when the Sanjay Gandhi biography got reprinted I was the editor in editor of

03:57:26.440 --> 03:57:32.400
[Guest]: Vijay Karnataka and he called me up and he said this has got reprinted and somebody in

03:57:32.400 --> 03:57:37.040
[Guest]: Bangalore wants to organize a launch function at the Taj so will you be in conversation

03:57:37.040 --> 03:57:42.760
[Guest]: with me so I was mighty pleased you know I mean you know asking me to be in conversation

03:57:42.760 --> 03:57:48.520
[Guest]: with him and so I did that so I mean I so that that point I felt that there was this

03:57:48.520 --> 03:57:55.160
[Guest]: kind of it was reciprocal you know he was seeing me as someone whom he could sort of

03:57:55.160 --> 03:58:00.760
[Guest]: as some kind of a there was an emotional linkage so he never let it out but then it would always

03:58:00.760 --> 03:58:07.920
[Guest]: be there so so that made me very happy and then of course I read some initial pages from

03:58:07.920 --> 03:58:14.520
[Guest]: Lucknow boy and all that and he was very excited about that he would talk about it and then

03:58:14.520 --> 03:58:20.920
[Guest]: I he asked me when somebody wanted to get it translated into Kannada so after it got

03:58:20.920 --> 03:58:25.640
[Guest]: published and it was a roaring success so that somebody had directly approached him

03:58:25.640 --> 03:58:30.840
[Guest]: so then he said he told them very very very nice of him to say that he said that will

03:58:30.840 --> 03:58:36.880
[Guest]: be decided by Sugata so so then it became imperative and obligatory on me to sort of

03:58:36.880 --> 03:58:40.960
[Guest]: quickly fix up a translator but of course he did not live to see the translation which

03:58:40.960 --> 03:58:46.440
[Guest]: came out really beautifully in Kannada the Lucknow boys in Kannada as well so I mean

03:58:46.440 --> 03:58:53.640
[Guest]: of course I Sumita Mehta was there and she was very kind to give permission to the book

03:58:53.640 --> 03:59:02.000
[Guest]: and it came out in Kannada and it was a big success in Kannada as well so this was Vinod

03:59:02.000 --> 03:59:09.120
[Guest]: and the kind of bonding and you know I mean I remember a line from William Shon's a

03:59:09.120 --> 03:59:14.440
[Guest]: book on William Shon written by Ved Mehta and that's a one of the one of the books

03:59:14.440 --> 03:59:18.800
[Guest]: that I really love reading because William Shon I always thought was a character like

03:59:18.800 --> 03:59:25.320
[Guest]: Vinod Mehta and I always used to tell Ajit that Ajit you have to write a book and it

03:59:25.320 --> 03:59:32.320
[Guest]: should be called Vinod Mehta's outlook like William Shon's New Yorker so Ajit of course

03:59:32.320 --> 03:59:37.560
[Guest]: Ajit wrote a lovely book on journalism which did well Hachette published it it was called

03:59:37.560 --> 03:59:42.720
[Guest]: off the record it was full of stories and his lovely interaction with Vinod and Vinod

03:59:42.720 --> 03:59:46.960
[Guest]: wrote the foreword for that book as well and that's where he said that Ajit Pillai would

03:59:46.960 --> 03:59:52.800
[Guest]: have thrived even without me he was a great reporter whom I sort of had the joy of having

03:59:52.800 --> 03:59:57.920
[Guest]: in my newsroom so that was the humility of the man as well so he taught us to extend

03:59:57.920 --> 04:00:02.560
[Guest]: that kind of courtesies to others you know if you are under a great man and a good man

04:00:02.560 --> 04:00:07.280
[Guest]: he teaches you a lot of these things and and very indirectly without without being didactic

04:00:07.280 --> 04:00:13.600
[Guest]: and instructive so so that so William Shon I was telling you about William Shon and Ved

04:00:13.600 --> 04:00:20.480
[Guest]: Mehta so there's a line there which struck me when I was reading it and this was around

04:00:20.480 --> 04:00:26.760
[Guest]: the time when Vinod was still alive and I was to do this introduction and conversation

04:00:26.760 --> 04:00:32.480
[Guest]: on the Sanjay Gandhi book so I was preparing myself and I wanted to impress him and I took

04:00:32.480 --> 04:00:40.360
[Guest]: this line from that book and I and it said that whoever I mean I sort of became emotionally

04:00:40.360 --> 04:00:45.560
[Guest]: attached to I saw them as my father that's that's some something like that I'm not quoting

04:00:45.560 --> 04:00:51.000
[Guest]: verbatim so he's here met William Shon and he's given him a job in New Yorker and is

04:00:51.000 --> 04:00:56.040
[Guest]: nurturing his talent and he says you know you I developed that what he meant was that

04:00:56.040 --> 04:01:00.560
[Guest]: I developed that kind of kinship relationship with him so whoever sort of they became my

04:01:00.560 --> 04:01:06.120
[Guest]: kind of father figures or whatever so I use that for Vinod and I'm very very happy that

04:01:06.120 --> 04:01:12.760
[Guest]: I used it and he heard it and he never responded he did not say anything and Vinod Vinod did

04:01:12.760 --> 04:01:18.120
[Guest]: not say anything that meant that he has registered on him Vinod did not have children of course

04:01:18.120 --> 04:01:25.080
[Guest]: he speaks about a girl he sort of may have fathered and must be living somewhere in Europe

04:01:25.080 --> 04:01:29.720
[Guest]: in his Lucknow boy but Vinod did not have children and I always was curious what he

04:01:29.720 --> 04:01:37.200
[Guest]: thought of people like us who were bordering on almost worship you know when we literally

04:01:37.200 --> 04:01:42.280
[Guest]: worship not mean worship was not the bhakt kind of worship but that genuine respect for

04:01:42.280 --> 04:01:49.640
[Guest]: his integrity which is very very rare in journalism that financial probity that see I went to

04:01:49.640 --> 04:01:57.400
[Guest]: cover the crash in Mangalore air crash okay I went there and I took the first flight and

04:01:57.400 --> 04:02:02.640
[Guest]: landed there and I wrote a story and I sent it to Outlook and I was supposed to come back

04:02:02.640 --> 04:02:06.200
[Guest]: and then you know usually the arrangement in Outlook was that you got the ticket from

04:02:06.200 --> 04:02:10.800
[Guest]: Delhi you went there and then I had to tell them when I'm returning and they would send

04:02:10.800 --> 04:02:17.240
[Guest]: me another ticket and this smart Alec kind of a MBA person someone sitting in the in

04:02:17.240 --> 04:02:23.840
[Guest]: the marketing office or the the business office I sent a note saying that I'm supposed to

04:02:23.840 --> 04:02:28.760
[Guest]: return on such and such a day so please send me a ticket and all that and we had done mortuary

04:02:28.760 --> 04:02:34.080
[Guest]: visits for three days continuously and the scene was so bad I write in my story that

04:02:34.080 --> 04:02:39.080
[Guest]: we went to report but we were actually asked to help so we had to pull out people we had

04:02:39.080 --> 04:02:43.960
[Guest]: to sort of help people identify so you became part of something else you know you went to

04:02:43.960 --> 04:02:49.480
[Guest]: report and it was a very traumatic experience you know I mean you can't see charred bodies

04:02:49.480 --> 04:02:55.160
[Guest]: like that and be normal and it was all over in those mortuaries and we had done that for

04:02:55.160 --> 04:03:00.120
[Guest]: three days me and the photographer and I wrote for air tickets back to Bangalore and this

04:03:00.120 --> 04:03:08.880
[Guest]: fellow says oh the air tickets are very expensive you take a bus back I was furious I asked

04:03:08.880 --> 04:03:13.840
[Guest]: him who told you to deny me an air ticket I mean I was a senior editor I was already

04:03:13.840 --> 04:03:19.280
[Guest]: an associate editor with Outlook he said no no no we have a the CEO or somebody has said

04:03:19.280 --> 04:03:24.000
[Guest]: that you know the air tickets are it's it's a bad time for the organization so we have

04:03:24.000 --> 04:03:29.480
[Guest]: to sort of cut costs so we can't send you the ticket so sitting on the pavement there

04:03:29.480 --> 04:03:37.200
[Guest]: of a mortuary and I had a luxury of a blackberry those days and I was had this fancy instrument

04:03:37.200 --> 04:03:41.680
[Guest]: and I wrote on my blackberry to Vinod Mehta directly saying I have done these many things

04:03:41.680 --> 04:03:46.800
[Guest]: I have filed my story I have done these mortuary visits I'm exhausted I'm broken in some sense

04:03:46.800 --> 04:03:52.760
[Guest]: and when I write for what is my legitimate thing for a ticket to go back to Bangalore

04:03:52.760 --> 04:03:59.440
[Guest]: I am told to take a bus this is how you treat your journalists so you know I wrote that

04:03:59.440 --> 04:04:05.840
[Guest]: I sent it and I was so furious I usually am a very calm collected kind of I don't do it

04:04:05.840 --> 04:04:10.040
[Guest]: I was very unhappy because you know I think those deaths and those the environment was

04:04:10.040 --> 04:04:19.600
[Guest]: so bad and I got an immediate response on the mail Vinod said I'm very sorry it has

04:04:19.600 --> 04:04:25.480
[Guest]: happened without my knowledge I'll ensure that the ticket comes to you I mean which

04:04:25.480 --> 04:04:31.160
[Guest]: editor on earth of that stature of that kind of thing would say a sorry to a ordinary you

04:04:31.160 --> 04:04:38.700
[Guest]: know person you know like me a person reporting from some corner of India so that that again

04:04:38.700 --> 04:04:46.000
[Guest]: was a life lesson he was like Vivek Mehta you know made William Shawn established a

04:04:46.000 --> 04:04:50.440
[Guest]: kinship relationship with him it happened with me also I have to confess it happened

04:04:50.440 --> 04:04:56.720
[Guest]: with me also and by then my father was dead my father was gone and I was hurriedly looking

04:04:56.720 --> 04:05:03.280
[Guest]: to substitute you know I mean people and then Vinod came like that so it was a very special

04:05:03.280 --> 04:05:10.240
[Guest]: bond it is that bond exists with Vinod that bond exists with Jeremy Seabrook I think there

04:05:10.240 --> 04:05:15.400
[Guest]: are two people who sort of I don't I wouldn't say they replaced my father or whatever like

04:05:15.400 --> 04:05:22.360
[Guest]: that but then you extend those kind of that kind of relationship and have that relationship

04:05:22.360 --> 04:05:28.560
[Guest]: and extend those courtesies and those respects to these two people so they were Vinod I mean

04:05:28.560 --> 04:05:34.320
[Guest]: more than Vinod it was Jeremy because Jeremy got involved I mean with the I mean with the

04:05:34.320 --> 04:05:37.800
[Guest]: family in the sense he was he was very he would understand try to understand what's

04:05:37.800 --> 04:05:42.200
[Guest]: happening in my family what's happening with my children he would talk to my wife for long

04:05:42.200 --> 04:05:47.400
[Guest]: hours talk to my children would counsel them he would speak to them so he developed a very

04:05:47.400 --> 04:05:52.040
[Guest]: different kind of bond Vinod could not shake off that thing it was a limited thing but

04:05:52.040 --> 04:05:56.760
[Guest]: he had a connect with my wife too in a sense he would speak to her would he would ask her

04:05:56.760 --> 04:06:01.080
[Guest]: a few things when he came here he would be very particular he would tell bring her for

04:06:01.080 --> 04:06:06.080
[Guest]: dinner when we sort of meet in Bangalore when we went to Delhi to call on him what was he

04:06:06.080 --> 04:06:12.320
[Guest]: would be very gracious but Jeremy was at a different level but then you exit this Vedmahata

04:06:12.320 --> 04:06:17.960
[Guest]: thing I quoted just to say that it happens with all of us that people who are you always

04:06:17.960 --> 04:06:23.400
[Guest]: want to sort of extend the kinship relationship you see somebody as your mother who's not

04:06:23.400 --> 04:06:28.600
[Guest]: your biological mother you see somebody as your father because he's been nice and not

04:06:28.600 --> 04:06:34.840
[Guest]: not a patriarch but then someone who has nurtured you who sort of you know sheltered you what

04:06:34.840 --> 04:06:39.960
[Guest]: was been who's made you feel very special was you know advanced your career without

04:06:39.960 --> 04:06:44.800
[Guest]: putting themselves before you know a lot of such things so I always remember that line

04:06:44.800 --> 04:06:52.000
[Guest]: from William Shawn's I mean Vedmahata's book on William Shawn a great book you know I don't

04:06:52.000 --> 04:06:57.440
[Guest]: still have a copy I read it with some I borrowed somebody's copy and then I have a Kindle version

04:06:57.440 --> 04:07:02.600
[Guest]: of it so I mean I still have not been able to get a hard copy which I will I hope to

04:07:02.600 --> 04:07:08.820
[Guest]: buy someday and just keep it there for myself so that was Vinod Mehta so that was the kind

04:07:08.820 --> 04:07:15.520
[Guest]: of liberal journalistic newsroom he built he sustained and he allowed a lot of people

04:07:15.520 --> 04:07:22.360
[Guest]: to thrive and I should say he spoiled us all because after that working anywhere was a

04:07:22.360 --> 04:07:27.440
[Guest]: very claustrophobic experience because there was I'm sure Vinod had to deal with his owners

04:07:27.440 --> 04:07:33.120
[Guest]: and when I had to deal with my owners directly there was no filter right there was no this

04:07:33.120 --> 04:07:38.100
[Guest]: man protecting your interests and arguing for your sake getting you money and increments

04:07:38.100 --> 04:07:45.520
[Guest]: and things to travel and all that so he was I mean I missed him and when I started and

04:07:45.520 --> 04:07:51.800
[Guest]: then the buck stopped at my table as an editor I used to be as careful and generous trying

04:07:51.800 --> 04:07:58.400
[Guest]: to be probably I would in with whatever limitations that was there you know the first thing when

04:07:58.400 --> 04:08:03.080
[Guest]: I went to Vijay Karnataka I realized that I something this is something that Binal Pandey

04:08:03.080 --> 04:08:07.400
[Guest]: also told you on your show the other day I realized that the salaries were pathetic of

04:08:07.400 --> 04:08:12.680
[Guest]: people who were stringers and refusal correspondents so the first thing the first big argument

04:08:12.680 --> 04:08:17.800
[Guest]: I made was there should be a parity and there should be a kind of structure that everybody

04:08:17.800 --> 04:08:23.520
[Guest]: sort of knows what they're trying to get or will get or whatever so that happened times

04:08:23.520 --> 04:08:29.160
[Guest]: was times that have bought that argument and they were quite happy to sort of I would tell

04:08:29.160 --> 04:08:33.440
[Guest]: them that you're such a big organization I don't think your employee should go out and

04:08:33.440 --> 04:08:38.680
[Guest]: say that we're not paid well and if you're not paid if a journalist is not paid well

04:08:38.680 --> 04:08:43.480
[Guest]: and if he has a family to run he'll always look for avenues to make supplementary incomes

04:08:43.480 --> 04:08:47.760
[Guest]: and that's when the politician comes into the picture so he'll try to push something

04:08:47.760 --> 04:08:54.160
[Guest]: else so let us say try and make it as reasonable as possible and they responded positively

04:08:54.160 --> 04:09:01.000
[Guest]: to that that whole argument and that happened and then I sort of also sort of I was did

04:09:01.000 --> 04:09:07.720
[Guest]: not want to look very moralistic or you know having come from the English spear and I knew

04:09:07.720 --> 04:09:12.240
[Guest]: that you know it was a world of a difference and people were not acclimatized to here so

04:09:12.240 --> 04:09:17.720
[Guest]: I would sort of very gently bring them around and get them to see my point of view and I

04:09:17.720 --> 04:09:22.040
[Guest]: would tell them that if you make innocent mistakes I will be the first one to pardon

04:09:22.040 --> 04:09:26.160
[Guest]: you but if you make deliberate mistakes then I'll kick you out you know I mean I cannot

04:09:26.160 --> 04:09:31.720
[Guest]: tolerate corruption because there was this problem that it still is there in Canada which

04:09:31.720 --> 04:09:37.960
[Guest]: is the problem of rampant financial corruption inside newsrooms you know journalists and

04:09:37.960 --> 04:09:45.160
[Guest]: others they sort of find ways to sort of corrupt journalists and there was a history to that

04:09:45.160 --> 04:09:53.040
[Guest]: paper also and it was completely on the right and those arguments had to be neutralized

04:09:53.040 --> 04:09:58.360
[Guest]: made more balanced made to look more like journalism and I had to I mean they all sort

04:09:58.360 --> 04:10:03.760
[Guest]: of mean it's also very nice that people when you speak to them the way you speak matters

04:10:03.760 --> 04:10:09.840
[Guest]: a great deal and my colleagues never gave me a problem they sort of care it was the

04:10:09.840 --> 04:10:15.320
[Guest]: marketing fellows and the circulation fellows who would come and tell no no no this we need

04:10:15.320 --> 04:10:20.560
[Guest]: to put more of this to sell more but I think journalists started seeing this whole joy

04:10:20.560 --> 04:10:26.640
[Guest]: of doing a great story and the natural reaction that it evokes you know we did so many human

04:10:26.640 --> 04:10:32.880
[Guest]: interest stories and that they saw the whole thing changing so I was I used to tell them

04:10:32.880 --> 04:10:39.280
[Guest]: the next day that this is the power of good journalism see this has changed something

04:10:39.280 --> 04:10:47.200
[Guest]: I still remember there was the story of a Muslim girl who had been treated I mean incorrectly

04:10:47.200 --> 04:10:55.360
[Guest]: in a government hospital and she had been paralyzed and her father was a poor Muslim

04:10:55.360 --> 04:11:01.400
[Guest]: guy who ran a workshop somewhere and he had to sell his I think house or pledge it or

04:11:01.400 --> 04:11:06.000
[Guest]: something like that and he was in debt and for a mistake that he had not committed it

04:11:06.000 --> 04:11:11.480
[Guest]: was a simple problem he took her to this hospital a government hospital a children's hospital

04:11:11.480 --> 04:11:18.760
[Guest]: and they gave her wrong medicine and it had all reacted and she had become paralyzed for life

04:11:18.760 --> 04:11:25.000
[Guest]: and he was running from pillar to post meeting ministers in a congress government who are

04:11:25.000 --> 04:11:29.880
[Guest]: Muslims and they were not helping him they were not sort of doing anything and then we

04:11:29.880 --> 04:11:34.640
[Guest]: were getting furious because he came and met one of my reporters and that reporter sort

04:11:34.640 --> 04:11:40.440
[Guest]: of did not tell us in the newsroom that there was this big story to be done but we somehow

04:11:40.440 --> 04:11:45.800
[Guest]: you know one of the chiefs one of his immediate seniors sort of recognized that there was

04:11:45.800 --> 04:11:49.760
[Guest]: something happening and then he said he suddenly raised the issue in the meeting and I and

04:11:49.760 --> 04:11:53.720
[Guest]: he said there must be a I think there's a great story there that that father has been

04:11:53.720 --> 04:11:57.680
[Guest]: coming and eating his head so there must be a story I think we can do a human interest

04:11:57.680 --> 04:12:01.640
[Guest]: story or something like that so I mean I was trying to humanize the newspaper as much as

04:12:01.640 --> 04:12:07.960
[Guest]: possible so I asked what this story was then they narrated this whole thing then I said

04:12:07.960 --> 04:12:15.300
[Guest]: instinctively I said check up the chief minister's relief fund and see who has been given money

04:12:15.300 --> 04:12:20.080
[Guest]: from the chief minister's relief fund if this child does not deserve money then who else

04:12:20.080 --> 04:12:24.240
[Guest]: deserves money from the government check up all this you know I mean the chief minister

04:12:24.240 --> 04:12:31.000
[Guest]: gives doles right to all these people so by evening my reporters had done a fantastic

04:12:31.000 --> 04:12:37.520
[Guest]: job they came back to me and they said sir you will be shocked one very big Kannada writer

04:12:37.520 --> 04:12:43.840
[Guest]: is being paid for his dialysis he was a former vice-chancellor he was a former chancellor

04:12:43.840 --> 04:12:49.240
[Guest]: former sitting chancellor former vice-chancellor and he has enough money he has a house in

04:12:49.240 --> 04:12:54.440
[Guest]: Bangalore he has a house in Mysore he has a farmhouse and he's being given money for

04:12:54.440 --> 04:13:02.040
[Guest]: his dialysis and his whole thing I mean I'm deliberately withholding the name so he is

04:13:02.040 --> 04:13:08.520
[Guest]: being given this money so but the child is being denied this child is a poem and we have

04:13:08.520 --> 04:13:13.480
[Guest]: been putting this whole story on the front page and the government is not responding

04:13:13.480 --> 04:13:19.920
[Guest]: so I said just contrast that and write a story so that went on the front page and all hell

04:13:19.920 --> 04:13:26.680
[Guest]: broke loose this writer who was also a friend of my father would come for his funeral called

04:13:26.680 --> 04:13:34.760
[Guest]: me and he and he sort of literally abused me and he said I'm sending you a note now

04:13:34.760 --> 04:13:39.200
[Guest]: and you do whatever you want and I'm it's not my problem if the government gives me

04:13:39.200 --> 04:13:43.640
[Guest]: money I mean I am in you don't know you're killing me you know what will happen if I

04:13:43.640 --> 04:13:51.840
[Guest]: see he was in serious medical condition but you know in the government is there for people

04:13:51.840 --> 04:13:58.440
[Guest]: like the little girl who is and she has committed no mistake it is she went to your institution

04:13:58.440 --> 04:14:04.280
[Guest]: and you have crippled her and here is a writer who can afford his costs and you're sort of

04:14:04.280 --> 04:14:08.640
[Guest]: you know pandering him and so he told me that it's not just this chief minister who gave

04:14:08.640 --> 04:14:13.560
[Guest]: me money the previous Eduard Appa also gave me money the other fellow also gave me money

04:14:13.560 --> 04:14:19.000
[Guest]: I said are you willing to sort of put all this on mail to me I will sort of carry your

04:14:19.000 --> 04:14:26.560
[Guest]: version so he sort of sent his version and I think he must have written it in complete

04:14:26.560 --> 04:14:33.560
[Guest]: he was in it was angry and he must have written it in his angry mood and that had some details

04:14:33.560 --> 04:14:41.800
[Guest]: which exposed him further so I just published that letter also and that sort of created

04:14:41.800 --> 04:14:47.760
[Guest]: such a buzz I'm just giving you one example of a story and how systems work unfairly and

04:14:47.760 --> 04:14:54.080
[Guest]: if you just decide to sort of do a little bit it sort of works to the benefits of the

04:14:54.080 --> 04:14:59.520
[Guest]: child had of course the child got some aid and all that but it exposed the system and

04:14:59.520 --> 04:15:03.640
[Guest]: it was a Congress government that was in power and this man had taken money from the Congress

04:15:03.640 --> 04:15:07.480
[Guest]: government the previous BJP government from Eduard Appa from everybody and I think it

04:15:07.480 --> 04:15:12.920
[Guest]: was a habit that had been formed that if I am a great writer I have sort of you know

04:15:12.920 --> 04:15:18.360
[Guest]: contributed to the culture of the state so I need to be taken care of that was a an attitude

04:15:18.360 --> 04:15:24.440
[Guest]: which I never sort of accepted and it is the same writers and same journalists in Karnataka

04:15:24.440 --> 04:15:30.640
[Guest]: who sort of protected this kind of an environment who took free sites from government you know

04:15:30.640 --> 04:15:37.560
[Guest]: they were called G category sites so SM Krishna distributed it all these people distributed

04:15:37.560 --> 04:15:41.400
[Guest]: all the all the chief ministers have done that it finally when it went to the high court

04:15:41.400 --> 04:15:48.160
[Guest]: it got state I mean so they were distributing this largest giving them benefits giving them

04:15:48.160 --> 04:15:52.200
[Guest]: discounted whatever some people took two sides so that they could sell one and build a house

04:15:52.200 --> 04:15:59.080
[Guest]: on the other one this is this this is I am speaking about G category sites in Karnataka

04:15:59.080 --> 04:16:04.600
[Guest]: this was journalism and of course communalism and was on the other side it was sort of on

04:16:04.600 --> 04:16:11.320
[Guest]: the rise and paper that I edited sort of had made it its ideological duty to sort of promote

04:16:11.320 --> 04:16:17.160
[Guest]: a certain kind of polarization and it started with that I'm sorry to say it started with

04:16:17.160 --> 04:16:23.680
[Guest]: that and corruption was another element so there were and so we today when we talk about

04:16:23.680 --> 04:16:28.920
[Guest]: the media Amit we say oh it's all gone bad today it's gone back gone bad yesterday oh

04:16:28.920 --> 04:16:36.000
[Guest]: it was not like this I'm sorry it was I think there were always people like this if you

04:16:36.000 --> 04:16:40.360
[Guest]: look at the emergency and the Indian media I'm working on a book on emergency and the

04:16:40.360 --> 04:16:45.880
[Guest]: Indian-American diaspora I'll be going to the US to research shortly they're full of

04:16:45.880 --> 04:16:51.680
[Guest]: examples of how media compromised how people sort of board how people sort of did not stand

04:16:51.680 --> 04:16:57.160
[Guest]: up for what was correct so I mean I mean I am not shocked by what we are seeing today

04:16:57.160 --> 04:17:02.760
[Guest]: the mainstream media so today we have Twitter and Facebook where we sort of amplify the

04:17:02.760 --> 04:17:08.600
[Guest]: whole problem but tell me all these senior editors who are in my book on Devya Gowda

04:17:08.600 --> 04:17:13.240
[Guest]: I speak about Ramkrishna Hegde and the people he cultivated people who did not belong to

04:17:13.240 --> 04:17:17.280
[Guest]: the state were given sites in the state and they were all big editors in Delhi and he

04:17:17.280 --> 04:17:22.320
[Guest]: was creating a lobby for himself in Delhi hoping that you know they will support him

04:17:22.320 --> 04:17:26.120
[Guest]: and they'll prop him up when the time comes but you know I mean Devya Gowda's destiny

04:17:26.120 --> 04:17:31.040
[Guest]: was something else so he got he became the Prime Minister not Mr. Hegde and Hegde was

04:17:31.040 --> 04:17:35.360
[Guest]: covering up all his corruption that was happening here with his kind of you know many things

04:17:35.360 --> 04:17:41.140
[Guest]: that were he could manage through public relations in Delhi so lobbies and cocktail circuits

04:17:41.140 --> 04:17:46.280
[Guest]: and moulding of opinion in cocktail circuits and the anglophone elite and the absence of

04:17:46.280 --> 04:17:52.040
[Guest]: understanding of the real India all of this has been true even three decades four decades

04:17:52.040 --> 04:17:58.800
[Guest]: ago and it's true today as well I think today we are far far far more aware of the problems

04:17:58.800 --> 04:18:04.520
[Guest]: than that existed then because they were just small little institutions tucked away nobody

04:18:04.520 --> 04:18:08.800
[Guest]: looked at them seriously now anything you do there are hundreds of people attacking

04:18:08.800 --> 04:18:13.760
[Guest]: you there are trolls and there are people who question you so I think we are in I mean

04:18:13.760 --> 04:18:18.840
[Guest]: I agree with you that we are in a slightly better situation now not in a worse situation

04:18:18.840 --> 04:18:23.920
[Guest]: because we are aware far more aware of the problems that confront us and have sort of

04:18:23.920 --> 04:18:29.900
[Guest]: put us in this kind of a condition and the other issue is of newsrooms is of diversity

04:18:29.900 --> 04:18:34.680
[Guest]: nobody speaks about it and you know I mean I try to correct the situation as much as

04:18:34.680 --> 04:18:41.400
[Guest]: possible I try to create a kind of rainbow or newsroom where people from the backward

04:18:41.400 --> 04:18:47.600
[Guest]: classes Dalits I appointed a Delhi bureau chief who was a Dalit I had a chief photographer

04:18:47.600 --> 04:18:54.200
[Guest]: who was a Dalit I made chief sub-editors I mean I'd consciously mix the castes because

04:18:54.200 --> 04:18:58.040
[Guest]: you know I mean without your knowledge or without your knowledge with or without your

04:18:58.040 --> 04:19:04.240
[Guest]: knowledge your worldviews that have that you've inherited unconsciously now not many people

04:19:04.240 --> 04:19:10.400
[Guest]: are cruel deliberately it's an unconscious kind of a thing they come in with those prejudices

04:19:10.400 --> 04:19:15.400
[Guest]: and that gets perpetrated so when you're reporting when you're when you're a medium that is sort

04:19:15.400 --> 04:19:20.480
[Guest]: of holding a mirror to the society and you are writing it from a certain perspective

04:19:20.480 --> 04:19:25.680
[Guest]: without even caring so that's where I remember Lankesh who asked do you have a Muslim friend

04:19:25.680 --> 04:19:29.600
[Guest]: do you have a Christian friend go and make a Muslim friend you will learn much more about

04:19:29.600 --> 04:19:34.960
[Guest]: society than actually reading 10 books on Tolstoy or Dostoevsky that was a great thing

04:19:34.960 --> 04:19:43.280
[Guest]: right so so here diversity is still a very big issue in Indian newsrooms it's largely

04:19:43.280 --> 04:19:52.000
[Guest]: upper caste it's largely men women have slowly sort of made some kind of thing because because

04:19:52.000 --> 04:19:56.880
[Guest]: of television mostly because of the screen and the and I don't know how much of control

04:19:56.880 --> 04:20:02.240
[Guest]: they have over what gets in or what gets out but then at least there are you see women

04:20:02.240 --> 04:20:09.480
[Guest]: because it's it's a visual thing right so diversity has been a big issue and I think

04:20:09.480 --> 04:20:15.080
[Guest]: if we don't solve that all this idea of India bankum that we keep speaking about will not

04:20:15.080 --> 04:20:21.640
[Guest]: get resolved because you don't have people in centers of communication who can pick up

04:20:21.640 --> 04:20:28.040
[Guest]: those ideas real diversity thing see lots of leaders in India we talk so much about

04:20:28.040 --> 04:20:33.960
[Guest]: Nehru why is it that we speak so little about a Morarji was he an outright kind of some

04:20:33.960 --> 04:20:39.560
[Guest]: buffoon no you know if you study Morarji if you read as a three volumes of Macmillan autobiography

04:20:39.560 --> 04:20:45.240
[Guest]: I mean my respect went up for the man you know I mean he was see you're condemned for

04:20:45.240 --> 04:20:50.680
[Guest]: one little thing and you're typecast you look at Jagjivan Ram who never succeeded it was

04:20:50.680 --> 04:20:54.680
[Guest]: a great administrator please know that he was a great administrator Devraj Harris was

04:20:54.680 --> 04:20:59.320
[Guest]: never celebrated is the man who gave you the idea of backward class reservation even before

04:20:59.320 --> 04:21:05.080
[Guest]: Mandal was commissioned during the Janata party regime he was the one who you know very

04:21:05.080 --> 04:21:10.760
[Guest]: innovatively made use of emergency to implement a lot of progressive policies in Karnataka

04:21:10.760 --> 04:21:16.880
[Guest]: and therefore came back to power when everybody lost when Congress lost everywhere he came

04:21:16.880 --> 04:21:23.560
[Guest]: back with a far improved margin and a far improved number so that is something that

04:21:23.560 --> 04:21:29.520
[Guest]: is because we don't have people who are sensitive to these see it doesn't happen in the American

04:21:29.520 --> 04:21:35.520
[Guest]: newsroom it is there the problem exists it exists everywhere there is a certain class

04:21:35.520 --> 04:21:42.040
[Guest]: and a certain caste or a certain set of people who sort of dominate environments but at least

04:21:42.040 --> 04:21:48.640
[Guest]: that consciousness has to grow inside you that we have to make our newsrooms diverse

04:21:48.640 --> 04:21:54.520
[Guest]: we have to sort of get people from all shades to come in in this mandalization of politics

04:21:54.520 --> 04:22:00.280
[Guest]: we speak so much about but the same politicians who benefited from the mandalization process

04:22:00.280 --> 04:22:05.760
[Guest]: are so bad about advocating these kind of causes so they've actually sabotaged their

04:22:05.760 --> 04:22:11.520
[Guest]: own revolution so I mean they have made it Parivarwad and all that is a separate issue

04:22:11.520 --> 04:22:16.760
[Guest]: but they never have advocated the kind of things that one needs to and diversity is

04:22:16.760 --> 04:22:22.160
[Guest]: at the center of Indian journalism and the center of Indian media and until unless you

04:22:22.160 --> 04:22:28.240
[Guest]: learn to accommodate different kinds of people in your newsroom you will not be doing justice

04:22:28.240 --> 04:22:33.520
[Guest]: to the idea of India or diversity of India or its multilingual heritage or the various

04:22:33.520 --> 04:22:39.560
[Guest]: world views that are around us you will just never get closer to reality.

04:22:39.560 --> 04:22:43.160
[Amit Varma]: I remember reading this great book one of the best books I've read in the last decade

04:22:43.160 --> 04:22:48.680
[Amit Varma]: by Philip Tetlockal, Super Forecasting and I came across a study in that which shows

04:22:48.680 --> 04:22:55.800
[Amit Varma]: that the best indicator of the quality of decision making is not intelligence is not

04:22:55.800 --> 04:23:01.800
[Amit Varma]: education it is diversity that the more diverse a group of people the better the decisions

04:23:01.800 --> 04:23:06.240
[Amit Varma]: you will get which is like the study showed it to be empirical fact you can argue about

04:23:06.240 --> 04:23:10.720
[Amit Varma]: why it is the case I think why it is the case would be that you have so many different viewpoints

04:23:10.720 --> 04:23:15.240
[Amit Varma]: that you are less likely to make mistakes and more likely to see things in a new way

04:23:15.240 --> 04:23:21.360
[Amit Varma]: and therefore I actually think that this is not even something that you know regardless

04:23:21.360 --> 04:23:28.120
[Amit Varma]: of whether it is mandated or not a good editor will try to voluntarily bring about this diversity

04:23:28.120 --> 04:23:32.880
[Amit Varma]: like you said you did like I think if I was running a firm not just a journalism this

04:23:32.880 --> 04:23:38.360
[Amit Varma]: thing but any firm out of pure self-interest the policy I'd put in place is that every

04:23:38.360 --> 04:23:44.400
[Amit Varma]: time there are multiple equal candidates for a job multiple equal candidates I'll pick

04:23:44.400 --> 04:23:49.240
[Amit Varma]: the one who increases the diversity right once you meet a certain you know whatever

04:23:49.240 --> 04:23:55.240
[Amit Varma]: the requirement kind of is I want to sort of let's talk about journalism because on

04:23:55.240 --> 04:24:00.120
[Amit Varma]: the one hand I you know in all my time in journalism as well it's just so it's always

04:24:00.120 --> 04:24:06.960
[Amit Varma]: been incredibly mediocre but on one margin I think it's become worse today and and I've

04:24:06.960 --> 04:24:12.320
[Amit Varma]: been thinking about this a bit that on the one hand you have sort of on the one hand

04:24:12.320 --> 04:24:16.200
[Amit Varma]: you have media that's clearly sold out and it's because of carrot and stick you know

04:24:16.200 --> 04:24:20.560
[Amit Varma]: so many media houses depend on government advertising and that's a carrot the threat

04:24:20.560 --> 04:24:25.160
[Amit Varma]: of taking it away is a stick and then you have the stick that any media house that has

04:24:25.160 --> 04:24:28.680
[Amit Varma]: any other business interest you are going to get raided your chemical factory can be

04:24:28.680 --> 04:24:33.560
[Amit Varma]: shut down and so on so on the one hand you have a lot of media which is completely blind

04:24:33.560 --> 04:24:37.400
[Amit Varma]: like in Indira's time it was said that you know they were asked to bend and they chose

04:24:37.400 --> 04:24:44.200
[Amit Varma]: to crawl and if there's a similar thing and on the other hand you have a bunch of brave

04:24:44.200 --> 04:24:52.960
[Amit Varma]: outliers like the News Minute and News Laundry, Wire, Scroll etc who you know Dhanaya Rajendran

04:24:52.960 --> 04:24:58.240
[Amit Varma]: of News Laundry recently put out of News Minute recently put out these tweets about how you

04:24:58.240 --> 04:25:02.560
[Amit Varma]: know they had been raided and the whole thing went on for years and the process is a punishment

04:25:02.560 --> 04:25:08.240
[Amit Varma]: but they stuck through it and it seems to me that while one group of people who sold

04:25:08.240 --> 04:25:13.360
[Amit Varma]: out are not fulfilling the basic duties of journalism another group of people are having

04:25:13.360 --> 04:25:20.500
[Amit Varma]: to go way beyond what should be reasonably expected of journalists in a sense to do good

04:25:20.500 --> 04:25:25.520
[Amit Varma]: journalism to continue to do good journalism they are almost being forced to turn into

04:25:25.520 --> 04:25:32.160
[Amit Varma]: crusaders that it is not possible anymore as a matter of course to do good journalism

04:25:32.160 --> 04:25:35.680
[Amit Varma]: what are your thoughts on this?

04:25:35.680 --> 04:25:40.640
[Guest]: So it's a situation is very grave what the picture that you painted is not incorrect

04:25:40.640 --> 04:25:47.720
[Guest]: at all see there are larger issues like diversity and all that but then this kind of vindictiveness

04:25:47.720 --> 04:25:54.600
[Guest]: of people who are not ideologically aligned to you is something which is it's becoming

04:25:54.600 --> 04:26:00.520
[Guest]: so very obvious ideologically or you know I mean who presented alternate point of view

04:26:00.520 --> 04:26:06.680
[Guest]: forget ideology, ideology is a very big word so that is becoming very obvious but that

04:26:06.680 --> 04:26:11.800
[Guest]: is the reason why you know we also have to start thinking about how we structure news

04:26:11.800 --> 04:26:17.400
[Guest]: organizations or what is the business model or how do we sort of incorporate a company

04:26:17.400 --> 04:26:23.440
[Guest]: and what should see there has to be some kind of legislative intervention as soon as possible

04:26:23.440 --> 04:26:29.920
[Guest]: or as and when it is possible where crossholding should be banned you know I mean your crossholdings

04:26:29.920 --> 04:26:35.000
[Guest]: and all of that also create a lot of problems because you are automatically making yourself

04:26:35.000 --> 04:26:41.040
[Guest]: liable right so you are a businessman you're doing this you're also using see this all

04:26:41.040 --> 04:26:47.080
[Guest]: of this started when you started using your business your journalism to leverage for your

04:26:47.080 --> 04:26:52.480
[Guest]: business interests see it is not innocent on the other side also right it is not just

04:26:52.480 --> 04:26:59.440
[Guest]: journalists who have started these tuta puta small little digital organizations my sympathies

04:26:59.440 --> 04:27:06.520
[Guest]: are entirely with them and I am I mean following their work and I also write for them occasionally

04:27:06.520 --> 04:27:13.880
[Guest]: but the problem is the other people who were supposedly upholders of this institutional

04:27:13.880 --> 04:27:20.320
[Guest]: journalism started leveraging journalism for other things you know they had to extend their

04:27:20.320 --> 04:27:26.200
[Guest]: plant or they had to do something new license had to be got or they had to import something

04:27:26.200 --> 04:27:31.520
[Guest]: you know I mean I hear ridiculous stories when I go to Delhi from my friends who would

04:27:31.520 --> 04:27:37.080
[Guest]: be panicking and then I tell them calm down let's have another drink or you can go later

04:27:37.080 --> 04:27:42.600
[Guest]: no no no madam had called or sir had called they are having some function and the road

04:27:42.600 --> 04:27:47.760
[Guest]: has not been asphalted properly I think I need to speak to somebody and just ensure

04:27:47.760 --> 04:27:52.760
[Guest]: that it is done so this and they hold big conclaves in Delhi and then you have to get

04:27:52.760 --> 04:27:57.200
[Guest]: guests and you have to get guests you have to sort of use your public relation so journalists

04:27:57.200 --> 04:28:01.840
[Guest]: have become so many things rolled into one public relations experts and people who speak

04:28:01.840 --> 04:28:07.240
[Guest]: to the local municipality to get roads asphalted and you know I mean of course you know checking

04:28:07.240 --> 04:28:12.320
[Guest]: on the application of your daughter or granddaughter or grandson in the passport office and then

04:28:12.320 --> 04:28:17.880
[Guest]: putting in a word I mean this is ridiculous and it's gone to that level and it is not

04:28:17.880 --> 04:28:24.680
[Guest]: that it's not again a problem that happened on the other side the government the government

04:28:24.680 --> 04:28:29.360
[Guest]: realized that they are vulnerable and they started there is somebody who came some smart

04:28:29.360 --> 04:28:34.880
[Guest]: fellow came in 2014 and he thought he could exploit them for that the earlier regime for

04:28:34.880 --> 04:28:42.680
[Guest]: was see I always say this about the Congress regimes which is the guilt of the emergencies

04:28:42.680 --> 04:28:48.160
[Guest]: put on them so much that they at least have a little you know I mean qualms about you

04:28:48.160 --> 04:28:54.000
[Guest]: know doing something with the media in a manner that will set deepen the kind of distrust

04:28:54.000 --> 04:29:01.880
[Guest]: about them so the Chidambaram did get Raju Nari Setty out of India so all of that these

04:29:01.880 --> 04:29:06.640
[Guest]: are stories that get you know come back in a different I didn't say that you said it

04:29:06.640 --> 04:29:13.160
[Guest]: yeah so they come back in a different context they get so we have seen again what happened

04:29:13.160 --> 04:29:19.080
[Guest]: with Bobby Ghosh and all of that is true and all of that is very real and I mean in my

04:29:19.080 --> 04:29:25.240
[Guest]: own it is autobiographical for me I could not stay in a newsroom because I had to once

04:29:25.240 --> 04:29:30.440
[Guest]: I realized that I had to make too many compromises I said let me keep the relationship and move

04:29:30.440 --> 04:29:37.920
[Guest]: out and I just moved out this is I mean I both with the times then I moved to the Asianet

04:29:37.920 --> 04:29:44.080
[Guest]: where I was looking after a very big old Kannada newspaper and also running television channels

04:29:44.080 --> 04:29:47.960
[Guest]: and then I mean I realized that you know I mean I was just not fitting into the whole

04:29:47.960 --> 04:29:53.680
[Guest]: thing it is see you're not asked to it doesn't at least in in my experience you are not asked

04:29:53.680 --> 04:29:58.800
[Guest]: to leave or you're not told on your face but then the situation is made so uncomfortable

04:29:58.800 --> 04:30:05.120
[Guest]: that then if you have some self-respect left in you you would say let me sort of step down

04:30:05.120 --> 04:30:09.360
[Guest]: and let them continue in the way they want to so that's exactly what happened with me

04:30:09.360 --> 04:30:13.800
[Guest]: and then I went and started a digital thing you know which is the first of its kind with

04:30:13.800 --> 04:30:19.200
[Guest]: podcasting, video, multiple thing you know interwoven thing and that also had to sort

04:30:19.200 --> 04:30:24.720
[Guest]: of wind up because the people who had funded me their names appeared in the paradise papers

04:30:24.720 --> 04:30:29.800
[Guest]: and then you know I mean I think they became squeamish about it and they withdrew the funding

04:30:29.800 --> 04:30:34.560
[Guest]: so then I decided writing is the best thing for some time because the atmosphere is not

04:30:34.560 --> 04:30:41.120
[Guest]: conducive for you to sort of pursue your journalism so I stood I mean at least I had writing to

04:30:41.120 --> 04:30:47.040
[Guest]: save me and I had some you know I mean I had I didn't have to worry about a house to live

04:30:47.040 --> 04:30:52.680
[Guest]: in so I sort of you know but that is not the case with everybody right people I mean I

04:30:52.680 --> 04:30:57.840
[Guest]: understand and I'm completely respect if people have to stay back in newsrooms because they

04:30:57.840 --> 04:31:01.720
[Guest]: have to run families they have to support families they have to you know support their

04:31:01.720 --> 04:31:06.240
[Guest]: children's education I can understand that I was slightly older and I had worked in senior

04:31:06.240 --> 04:31:12.640
[Guest]: positions and made relatively more money which sustains me for a longer period it's not that

04:31:12.640 --> 04:31:18.920
[Guest]: it can sustain me forever but and also there is this you know you're this thing idealistic

04:31:18.920 --> 04:31:25.520
[Guest]: and as I said little magazines were showcases of idealism Plimpton obituary you know it

04:31:25.520 --> 04:31:31.880
[Guest]: said this beautiful line in Boston Globe showcases of idealism so similarly you know you also

04:31:31.880 --> 04:31:37.200
[Guest]: have this value system which has been ingrained in you and you want to live up to that and

04:31:37.200 --> 04:31:41.560
[Guest]: you feel that your conscience is pricking and your answer answering your people you

04:31:41.560 --> 04:31:46.160
[Guest]: love who have sort of invested so much of trust and love and affection in you and they

04:31:46.160 --> 04:31:51.440
[Guest]: thought you'll never violate that so you are you're actually the moral you know quandary

04:31:51.440 --> 04:31:58.040
[Guest]: and that you're put into it is so stressful it's so stressful it is so difficult to negotiate

04:31:58.040 --> 04:32:03.160
[Guest]: that moral quandary and I think that is the biggest punishment it is not losing a job

04:32:03.160 --> 04:32:08.600
[Guest]: it is not having to leave a place it's not about making money it's about how do you answer

04:32:08.600 --> 04:32:15.440
[Guest]: your conscience how do you sort of navigate that delicate thing you know is the more troublesome

04:32:15.440 --> 04:32:19.800
[Guest]: thing because you're not answering yourself there you're not just answering your immediate

04:32:19.800 --> 04:32:25.120
[Guest]: material requirements you're answering your father your forefather your teachers and all

04:32:25.120 --> 04:32:29.720
[Guest]: your learning and education and the weight of that heritage falls on you at that point

04:32:29.720 --> 04:32:35.320
[Guest]: of time so you don't want to feel compromised because it's almost suicide.

04:32:35.320 --> 04:32:42.080
[Amit Varma]: So I sometimes think about the value one can bring to the world and you know when I think

04:32:42.080 --> 04:32:46.400
[Amit Varma]: about somebody like you obviously there is a lot of value in your writing and you're

04:32:46.400 --> 04:32:51.280
[Amit Varma]: doing everything that you're doing but another way in which you could benefit people is by

04:32:51.280 --> 04:32:56.400
[Amit Varma]: being to other people what Jeremy Seabrook and Vinod Mehta were to you right so on the

04:32:56.400 --> 04:33:02.360
[Amit Varma]: one hand that could be just editing a large publication or leading a large publication

04:33:02.360 --> 04:33:07.640
[Amit Varma]: where you're passing these values on to a younger generation who will carry it forward

04:33:07.640 --> 04:33:12.080
[Amit Varma]: right so in a sense you're playing the long game where you're saying that okay even if

04:33:12.080 --> 04:33:16.440
[Amit Varma]: I can make limited difference I can train these people and take it forward and this

04:33:16.440 --> 04:33:20.560
[Amit Varma]: need not be only through a job where you're an editor of a firm and you have people working

04:33:20.560 --> 04:33:21.560
[Amit Varma]: under you.

04:33:21.560 --> 04:33:26.200
[Amit Varma]: Are there ways to make this kind of mentorship this kind of guidance scale?

04:33:26.200 --> 04:33:30.200
[Guest]: I'm glad you asked that question Amit, I'm actually doing it with a couple of people

04:33:30.200 --> 04:33:35.120
[Guest]: you know there was one investigative journalist who was to work with me and he was so good

04:33:35.120 --> 04:33:39.280
[Guest]: that he used to bring a fresh story every day and it broke my heart when I was leaving

04:33:39.280 --> 04:33:45.600
[Guest]: and he said I will also leave and then I told him that see this is technology allows you

04:33:45.600 --> 04:33:50.720
[Guest]: to sort of work in different fashions so don't give up on journalism if you want to quit

04:33:50.720 --> 04:33:58.000
[Guest]: this organization it's up to you and he came from rural Karnataka so I mean I knew his

04:33:58.000 --> 04:34:03.880
[Guest]: strengths he had worked for four or five years with me so I created a product for him which

04:34:03.880 --> 04:34:10.080
[Guest]: sort of helps him sort of you know publish on his own without a staff or whatever and

04:34:10.080 --> 04:34:15.960
[Guest]: sustain himself by because those stories can't be written by anybody else he sort of you

04:34:15.960 --> 04:34:20.320
[Guest]: know I don't know he has a knack of picking these government documents and contrasting

04:34:20.320 --> 04:34:21.320
[Amit Varma]: it.

04:34:21.320 --> 04:34:22.320
[Amit Varma]: What's his name?

04:34:22.320 --> 04:34:30.440
[Guest]: His name is Mahantesh and he was with me in Asianet and he now runs a lovely one-man run

04:34:30.440 --> 04:34:38.360
[Guest]: site called the file.in and I'm incredibly proud to say that this boy brought out 50

04:34:38.360 --> 04:34:42.680
[Guest]: stories of corruption during Covid and it was discussed during a session of the assembly

04:34:42.680 --> 04:34:48.960
[Guest]: in Karnataka and he's a one-man person he has nobody and these days he gets small contribution

04:34:48.960 --> 04:34:55.760
[Guest]: from friends and others and he just about enough to pay his rent in Bangalore and survive

04:34:55.760 --> 04:35:01.240
[Guest]: and I mean he's not given up and I mean that is the kind of hope that I wish to see everywhere

04:35:01.240 --> 04:35:06.240
[Guest]: else and and in this I mean he's far greater than what I have done you know this is the

04:35:06.240 --> 04:35:12.320
[Guest]: kind of circumstances that he was in and the kind of background that he came from he is

04:35:12.320 --> 04:35:18.120
[Guest]: I mean he's outclassed all of us and this person makes me very very proud and he was

04:35:18.120 --> 04:35:22.040
[Guest]: there at my place even yesterday asking shall I run this story or not run this story so

04:35:22.040 --> 04:35:27.320
[Guest]: he's so focused he's now got a story on something and he says I won't run this but the lawyer

04:35:27.320 --> 04:35:31.360
[Guest]: friend whom you and I get him this pro bono thing you know because there were cases slapped

04:35:31.360 --> 04:35:36.880
[Guest]: on him and there was an FIR filed by a big pontiff of a big mutt and then there was a

04:35:36.880 --> 04:35:41.520
[Guest]: almost we thought he'd get arrested so we were just working all this to sort of help

04:35:41.520 --> 04:35:46.520
[Guest]: him and so he came and he said but your lawyer friend you suggested is saying that this is

04:35:46.520 --> 04:35:52.640
[Guest]: not going to work so I should I run it or not run it then I said let us read this story

04:35:52.640 --> 04:35:57.760
[Guest]: you know the proof is in the story that you've written so I read it and I said see he is

04:35:57.760 --> 04:36:01.760
[Guest]: telling you not to run it because of these two paragraphs so just eliminate those two

04:36:01.760 --> 04:36:07.160
[Guest]: paragraphs and bring in another perspective add this perspective and you're free to go

04:36:07.160 --> 04:36:11.480
[Guest]: and you're free to run it so I mean there are people like that there are people like

04:36:11.480 --> 04:36:18.480
[Guest]: that and he is so now the thing the sad thing is the big mainstream people steal from him

04:36:18.480 --> 04:36:25.200
[Guest]: because his thing comes out and and I told him that okay if they are doing that just

04:36:25.200 --> 04:36:29.800
[Guest]: the next day you say you're very happy that they have done back journalism they have taken

04:36:29.800 --> 04:36:34.480
[Guest]: your story and just say I'm very happy that the mainstream has picked this up and so one

04:36:34.480 --> 04:36:38.880
[Guest]: of the newspapers even served him a notice saying that oh you're saying this and it's

04:36:38.880 --> 04:36:48.280
[Guest]: ridiculous I said don't even respond let's see what happens don't even respond so journalism

04:36:48.280 --> 04:36:52.480
[Guest]: should thrive and somebody is doing good journalism you should encourage and you should sort of

04:36:52.480 --> 04:36:59.440
[Guest]: but now the other part of it is that one or two other newspapers have given him this little

04:36:59.440 --> 04:37:06.200
[Guest]: small you know monetary package and they have said we will use your stories also with full

04:37:06.200 --> 04:37:12.920
[Guest]: credit and because see newspapers don't have creative and investigative journalists like

04:37:12.920 --> 04:37:16.840
[Guest]: before and they need good stories and they know that this fellow is putting it out day

04:37:16.840 --> 04:37:20.800
[Guest]: in and day out so they accommodate him and give him a small package which is helping

04:37:20.800 --> 04:37:27.360
[Guest]: him sustain financially so that gives me a lot of hope and it's it's an it's a very arduous

04:37:27.360 --> 04:37:35.000
[Guest]: difficult trek it's a very difficult path but then let's see how long we can hold on

04:37:35.000 --> 04:37:39.400
[Guest]: is the kind of spirit with which we need to work I don't think we need to give up so easily

04:37:39.400 --> 04:37:45.360
[Guest]: okay you are challenging us we have the wherewithal to sort of address your challenges the spirit

04:37:45.360 --> 04:37:49.880
[Guest]: with which we have looked at it so far so I don't know what will happen so in fact he

04:37:49.880 --> 04:37:54.680
[Guest]: sometimes when this boy I mean I use him as a metaphor for a lot of good journalists around

04:37:54.680 --> 04:38:00.560
[Guest]: in this country doing incredible work bringing great stories to our attention that he won

04:38:00.560 --> 04:38:05.560
[Guest]: some sometimes he says sir when I think I have to compromise I'll give up and go and

04:38:05.560 --> 04:38:10.080
[Guest]: work somewhere else you know so my firm my friend has a transport company I can be a

04:38:10.080 --> 04:38:16.800
[Guest]: clerk there or I'll go back to my native Davangere my father has a home I don't have to pay rent

04:38:16.800 --> 04:38:22.080
[Guest]: my kid can go to the government school there so this is the kind of you know I mean level

04:38:22.080 --> 04:38:27.240
[Guest]: of commitment that journalists show and he is not from the upper caste again see that

04:38:27.240 --> 04:38:32.920
[Guest]: is see these are the stories that I think the rest of India has to listen and I'm happy

04:38:32.920 --> 04:38:38.080
[Guest]: that you asked me this question mentoring yes mentoring is a very I think it would be

04:38:38.080 --> 04:38:45.480
[Guest]: very arrogant on my part to say that I'm mentoring them what I am trying to do is just to listen

04:38:45.480 --> 04:38:54.360
[Guest]: give them the time because they are far bigger mentors than we can ever be because they have

04:38:54.360 --> 04:39:01.120
[Guest]: the pinch of that it's the poor that the poverty pinches them each day and they are not willing

04:39:01.120 --> 04:39:08.880
[Guest]: to give up as yet so that is bravery of a different order and I and we are I mean we

04:39:08.880 --> 04:39:14.000
[Guest]: are asked to play a small role in giving them that confidence to sustain that and sometimes

04:39:14.000 --> 04:39:18.280
[Guest]: it feels very cruel to say that go on that path keep continuing on that path because

04:39:18.280 --> 04:39:22.960
[Guest]: it's your idealism and you want somebody else to bear the cross so that also makes me feel

04:39:22.960 --> 04:39:28.800
[Guest]: very guilty at times because you are reflective of these things and you see that things are

04:39:28.800 --> 04:39:34.880
[Guest]: not shaping up well for him and journalism is dead the way it was.

04:39:34.880 --> 04:39:39.280
[Amit Varma]: And also you know I just think people like this are outliers in terms of courage and

04:39:39.280 --> 04:39:43.240
[Amit Varma]: commitment and you should not need to be an outlier you know good journalism should be

04:39:43.240 --> 04:39:49.880
[Amit Varma]: something that should be possible as a matter of course and what I meant about the mentorship

04:39:49.880 --> 04:39:55.560
[Amit Varma]: scaling is that okay it's a couple of people but and I'm just thinking aloud here and maybe

04:39:55.560 --> 04:40:02.240
[Amit Varma]: listeners will also have ideas that are there ways to kind of get this across to more people

04:40:02.240 --> 04:40:05.720
[Amit Varma]: spread the value around you know that's what I sometimes want.

04:40:05.720 --> 04:40:11.000
[Guest]: There was this platform that was created in Bangalore again to fund alternate media and

04:40:11.000 --> 04:40:16.560
[Guest]: all that and but that has become a forum for both sides both side is some kind of a thing

04:40:16.560 --> 04:40:21.520
[Guest]: so again they I mean I don't know if they came under pressure what happened but then

04:40:21.520 --> 04:40:27.600
[Guest]: you know you are you're funding right left and center so there is a certain value system

04:40:27.600 --> 04:40:33.640
[Guest]: that you should have embraced certain professionalism that should have been embraced and promoted

04:40:33.640 --> 04:40:40.120
[Guest]: but see again see the problem is that everybody comes under pressure and everybody comes under

04:40:40.120 --> 04:40:44.680
[Guest]: pressure they also have to sort of retain their identity and they retain it in some

04:40:44.680 --> 04:40:51.280
[Guest]: botched up manner and it's a very sad story it's a sad commentary of our times but I mean

04:40:51.280 --> 04:40:55.600
[Guest]: it's not fair to blame anybody because you know they come under such enormous I mean

04:40:55.600 --> 04:41:00.360
[Guest]: I know what it is you know I have faced it myself so we come under pressure and I don't

04:41:00.360 --> 04:41:05.560
[Guest]: think we should make victims of ourselves and play it up and say oh I face this I face

04:41:05.560 --> 04:41:10.880
[Guest]: these many cases I they went after me for this so people have their own way of coping

04:41:10.880 --> 04:41:16.200
[Guest]: with it and there are some incredible stories out there like the story that I just narrated

04:41:16.200 --> 04:41:18.800
[Guest]: to you of Mahantesh and Dipoye.

04:41:18.800 --> 04:41:23.880
[Amit Varma]: So couple of final questions as we grow older and I think you're on also in your late 40s

04:41:23.880 --> 04:41:29.680
[Amit Varma]: like I am so as we grow older I've realized that our conception of time changes it can

04:41:29.680 --> 04:41:34.720
[Amit Varma]: happen when people who were part of our lives no longer are as you know we you spoke about

04:41:34.720 --> 04:41:40.080
[Amit Varma]: Vinod and it can happen just because you know when you're young you have a very compressed

04:41:40.080 --> 04:41:44.800
[Amit Varma]: view of time when you're 20 you think 30 is old age you know you think 50 is completely

04:41:44.800 --> 04:41:49.640
[Amit Varma]: out there you romantically say oh I will never get that far but then the decades pass in

04:41:49.640 --> 04:41:52.960
[Amit Varma]: a hurry like I love this phrase his friend of mine Gautam John used while he was having

04:41:52.960 --> 04:41:57.800
[Amit Varma]: breakfast with me recently where he said the days are long the years are short and I feel

04:41:57.800 --> 04:42:03.320
[Amit Varma]: that the older I get that's kind of more and more true and this has a number of different

04:42:03.320 --> 04:42:09.080
[Amit Varma]: effects one is that things which are way back in the past like 30-40 years ago when we were

04:42:09.080 --> 04:42:13.880
[Amit Varma]: younger it would have seemed far away in the past today it's like a blink of an eye we

04:42:13.880 --> 04:42:19.720
[Amit Varma]: ourselves have seen decades pass in the blink of an eye so does that kind of change does

04:42:19.720 --> 04:42:24.600
[Amit Varma]: that kind of change your gaze in certain ways where if there's a lot of shit going down

04:42:24.600 --> 04:42:29.200
[Amit Varma]: right now you can be equanimous about it take a step back see the wider sweep of history

04:42:29.200 --> 04:42:36.920
[Amit Varma]: see where the arc is going and the other aspect also is like I was very intrigued by you know

04:42:36.920 --> 04:42:40.920
[Amit Varma]: keeping your Devika out of the book there is he gets married at 21 right and the thing

04:42:40.920 --> 04:42:45.640
[Amit Varma]: is that that's very common for someone you know people will get married even younger

04:42:45.640 --> 04:42:51.520
[Amit Varma]: and you go further back in time and you realize that life expectancies maybe decades ago was

04:42:51.520 --> 04:42:59.080
[Amit Varma]: like 40-45 you know you and I would be outliers and you know and I think about how their approach

04:42:59.080 --> 04:43:04.120
[Amit Varma]: to life then changes that then it makes sense that you're getting married earlier and you're

04:43:04.120 --> 04:43:08.760
[Amit Varma]: having more kids because you don't know how many will survive and so on and so forth and

04:43:08.760 --> 04:43:12.880
[Amit Varma]: now we've reached a stage where life expectancies are great especially for privileged elites

04:43:12.880 --> 04:43:18.240
[Amit Varma]: like us and and you know who knows me perhaps not in our lifetimes but at some point you're

04:43:18.240 --> 04:43:25.360
[Amit Varma]: going to like extend it to lengths which actually seem dystopian if you think about it. Everybody

04:43:25.360 --> 04:43:32.400
[Amit Varma]: would be Vishnu Pitamaha. What a horrible thought. Anyway so you know how does that

04:43:32.400 --> 04:43:37.400
[Amit Varma]: how has that changed your outlook on life in general like you know one of the ways in

04:43:37.400 --> 04:43:41.800
[Amit Varma]: which I think I have changed with time is that earlier I was kind of goal oriented that

04:43:41.800 --> 04:43:46.680
[Amit Varma]: I had specific goals yeh karna hai, woh karna hai, yeh karna hai but now I've become more

04:43:46.680 --> 04:43:50.760
[Amit Varma]: not even process oriented but more journey oriented that take happiness in the small

04:43:50.760 --> 04:43:55.080
[Amit Varma]: things you know wake up in the morning looking forward to what you're going to do that day

04:43:55.080 --> 04:44:00.160
[Amit Varma]: and so on so how has that changed your approach to life like when you wake up in the morning

04:44:00.160 --> 04:44:08.120
[Amit Varma]: what do you look forward to, how do you define happiness for yourself today? Oh that's a

04:44:08.120 --> 04:44:16.800
[Guest]: that's a very very tough question. It's it's it's I mean I have slowed down a little I

04:44:16.800 --> 04:44:23.160
[Guest]: think that is a great thing that I have done you know I mean I used to you know be in office

04:44:23.160 --> 04:44:28.400
[Guest]: from 10 in the morning till 10 in the night I would not see my daughter not see my son

04:44:28.400 --> 04:44:32.600
[Guest]: and you know these pressures and I would take calls even at one o'clock in the night because

04:44:32.600 --> 04:44:36.920
[Guest]: the final edition would go and I would I was very in I was a very meticulous edit I wanted

04:44:36.920 --> 04:44:42.600
[Guest]: to see the front page before it went to the press and they would wake me up and and calls

04:44:42.600 --> 04:44:47.600
[Guest]: could come at any time of the day and all that so the best thing that has happened after

04:44:47.600 --> 04:44:51.880
[Guest]: I have stopped running institutions in the last two or two and a half years or three

04:44:51.880 --> 04:44:56.900
[Guest]: years is and and it took took the whole time writing and I don't know if I will ever get

04:44:56.900 --> 04:45:01.200
[Guest]: back to the newsroom it may happen may not happen but the thing is that I have slowed

04:45:01.200 --> 04:45:07.480
[Guest]: down that it's I'm enjoying that that that slowness because you know I mean you don't

04:45:07.480 --> 04:45:13.360
[Guest]: have to sort of accomplish something or prove yourself to somebody else all that you're

04:45:13.360 --> 04:45:18.720
[Guest]: left to prove is to yourself and so that is sort of you know I mean I mean I I became

04:45:18.720 --> 04:45:24.640
[Guest]: hypertensive at one point of time and now all my indices are good is it's touch gold

04:45:24.640 --> 04:45:30.520
[Guest]: or touch whatever it's sort of looking normal and and I have to just manage a little and

04:45:30.520 --> 04:45:35.880
[Guest]: then it I don't have to really be worried about it so so that is one thing that has

04:45:35.880 --> 04:45:43.280
[Guest]: happened so I I usually get a very early I'm not a I mean for a journalist I'm an early

04:45:43.280 --> 04:45:49.960
[Guest]: riser I'm up by five so I'm looking forward to the walk with my wife in the morning so

04:45:49.960 --> 04:45:55.360
[Guest]: that is when I get to listen to you, your podcast you know I mean I I have a I create

04:45:55.360 --> 04:46:02.480
[Guest]: a playlist and then I do a certain ritualistic listening and then I walk for an hour and

04:46:02.480 --> 04:46:07.680
[Guest]: so I mean there is a spillover for the next day that the day after so I I look forward

04:46:07.680 --> 04:46:13.820
[Guest]: to that and then of course you know days that are I'm bored I just listen to music today

04:46:13.820 --> 04:46:19.120
[Guest]: for instance I listen to Jaitirtha Mevundi who's a rising star in Hindustani music and

04:46:19.120 --> 04:46:24.280
[Guest]: you see superbly rendered Chandrakants you know I mean so I mean I was listening to that

04:46:24.280 --> 04:46:30.920
[Guest]: so I mean the pace has come down and that pace coming down also sometimes brings anxiety

04:46:30.920 --> 04:46:38.240
[Guest]: to me let me confess because I feel that I have retired although because I'm still writing

04:46:38.240 --> 04:46:43.600
[Guest]: columns you know I mean I breathlessly writing I produce a lot of writing you know I mean

04:46:43.600 --> 04:46:49.320
[Guest]: I write four columns a month which is a lot and you have to come up with new ideas and

04:46:49.320 --> 04:46:54.000
[Guest]: then in between there are special requests so you have to do that and I'm working on

04:46:54.000 --> 04:46:59.080
[Guest]: two books simultaneously and I'm commissioned by Penguin to do those two books so so those

04:46:59.080 --> 04:47:05.160
[Guest]: things are lying on my mind so library work travel all that is there out there but then

04:47:05.160 --> 04:47:12.160
[Guest]: sometimes I feel that that buzz that was there in the newsroom is missing and oh I have I

04:47:12.160 --> 04:47:17.960
[Guest]: semi-retired oh is this how you sort of you know I mean live if you're not working full

04:47:17.960 --> 04:47:23.520
[Guest]: time so then I take solace from from people on Brunton Street in Bangalore that is where

04:47:23.520 --> 04:47:29.040
[Guest]: Ramachandra Gohar lives he has lived that life for a long time of just writing so I

04:47:29.040 --> 04:47:33.920
[Guest]: just calm myself you know I mean that occasionally comes up and because my father worked for

04:47:33.920 --> 04:47:39.280
[Guest]: his all all his life he went to teach first at the Christ College and then Canada University

04:47:39.280 --> 04:47:44.080
[Guest]: you know that he was just working and he retired for me my retirement or semi-retirement or

04:47:44.080 --> 04:47:50.000
[Guest]: a break has come I mean in my you know I'm just about touching 50 and so it's come very

04:47:50.000 --> 04:47:54.960
[Guest]: early so I mean you don't know what to do so you have to you innovate so I as I work

04:47:54.960 --> 04:48:00.280
[Guest]: with some startup trying to help them build a media thing and it's it's all it's all mentorship

04:48:00.280 --> 04:48:04.160
[Guest]: you know basically they come and then I discuss ideas with them so that gives me a lot of

04:48:04.160 --> 04:48:07.900
[Guest]: joy so there's somebody who's trying to develop a mental health product and they've said how

04:48:07.900 --> 04:48:12.720
[Guest]: does how does one link media to that and then I was just trying to get consumed with that

04:48:12.720 --> 04:48:18.400
[Guest]: idea so Bangalore that way I mean one thing I've learned is the small little idea that

04:48:18.400 --> 04:48:24.960
[Guest]: my father told me that as you grow older engage with the younger so they keep you young they

04:48:24.960 --> 04:48:29.800
[Guest]: bring new ideas and don't think that you have to pontificate listen to them because they

04:48:29.800 --> 04:48:34.560
[Guest]: would have brighter ideas they would have come with a different set of questions so

04:48:34.560 --> 04:48:41.560
[Guest]: to answer which you will have to equip yourself so don't be this person that you know you

04:48:41.560 --> 04:48:45.840
[Guest]: don't go with a set of ideas with them so that listening sort of helps so I come to

04:48:45.840 --> 04:48:51.520
[Guest]: Koshi's I go to other places and just listen to people speak and they come home and then

04:48:51.520 --> 04:48:57.120
[Guest]: there's because of my engagement in the newsroom my the the colleagues who work with me are

04:48:57.120 --> 04:49:02.400
[Guest]: all over so they call up they say sir if you were there you would allow this story this

04:49:02.400 --> 04:49:07.720
[Guest]: editor is not so I don't get into that kind of a thing but then I just listen to them

04:49:07.720 --> 04:49:16.240
[Guest]: so that gives them a bit of solace and whatever so I think writing I have what I have discovered

04:49:16.240 --> 04:49:24.080
[Guest]: is that after 2008-19 when I in 19 beginning of 19 is when I started working on the Deve

04:49:24.080 --> 04:49:30.440
[Guest]: Gowda book I feel I mean I have told myself that I'm essentially a writer and my wife

04:49:30.440 --> 04:49:35.280
[Guest]: has reiterated that she's also a writer so she is she's a poet so she has reiterated

04:49:35.280 --> 04:49:39.000
[Guest]: that thing that I married you essentially because you were a writer not because you

04:49:39.000 --> 04:49:43.860
[Guest]: were a big editor or that or this or whatever so that reassures me that there is no pressure

04:49:43.860 --> 04:49:49.200
[Guest]: from the home front where she's expecting a certain kind of you know thing from me and

04:49:49.200 --> 04:49:54.280
[Guest]: I am falling short of it so it's very very important that you have understanding partners

04:49:54.280 --> 04:50:00.600
[Guest]: so so that is there and then my daughter is full of stories and my son is you know I mean

04:50:00.600 --> 04:50:04.680
[Guest]: full of stories they are reading different kinds of things which I mentioned in the acknowledgement

04:50:04.680 --> 04:50:08.760
[Guest]: of my book you know I mean they're reading various different things and except reading

04:50:08.760 --> 04:50:12.160
[Guest]: their father they're doing everything else so which is a very good thing maybe they're

04:50:12.160 --> 04:50:16.240
[Amit Varma]: reading the father's secretly you don't you don't confess to these I read my father very

04:50:16.240 --> 04:50:21.160
[Guest]: secretly I never told him when he was alive that I liked something that he wrote which

04:50:21.160 --> 04:50:27.920
[Guest]: is a very strange thing I've written about it in my book pickles from home but it was

04:50:27.920 --> 04:50:33.920
[Guest]: I mean he was gone by then and then I mean in the final stages of his life we had developed

04:50:33.920 --> 04:50:40.360
[Guest]: a protocol where if he had written a new poem he would leave it on my table that is my bedroom

04:50:40.360 --> 04:50:46.320
[Guest]: table and I would look at it from a distance stare at it and then probably read a couple

04:50:46.320 --> 04:50:50.440
[Guest]: of lines and leave it there and after one week it would have gone back to his room or

04:50:50.440 --> 04:50:57.400
[Guest]: he would have taken it away so I speak about it I recall Oran Pamuk's Nobel I mean Nobel

04:50:57.400 --> 04:51:02.160
[Guest]: speech Nobel Prize speech where he speaks in a similar fashion about his father not

04:51:02.160 --> 04:51:06.680
[Guest]: that I was I'm not comparing myself with Pamuk or whatever and it's just a lovely piece of

04:51:06.680 --> 04:51:11.560
[Guest]: literature which I'm picking and using it as an anecdote to tell you what exact emotion

04:51:11.560 --> 04:51:17.920
[Guest]: that went past in my mind so his father gives him a suitcase and it's and that suitcase

04:51:17.920 --> 04:51:24.600
[Guest]: contained the writings of his father and he never opened it to read and his father always

04:51:24.600 --> 04:51:30.240
[Guest]: wanted this approval from the son who's already become a big writer right so so in my case

04:51:30.240 --> 04:51:34.360
[Guest]: that was not the thing my father was already an accomplished writer had won the all the

04:51:34.360 --> 04:51:40.480
[Guest]: awards that he had to win and he was celebrated all that but somehow there was that I could

04:51:40.480 --> 04:51:46.480
[Guest]: not build a relationship with his writing because he wrote a lot of one-act plays he

04:51:46.480 --> 04:51:52.760
[Guest]: wrote full-length plays and he was writing a fantastic full-length play on Columbus and

04:51:52.760 --> 04:51:58.400
[Guest]: globalization and I mean using Columbus as the prop to speak about globalization and

04:51:58.400 --> 04:52:05.280
[Guest]: he wanted to look at the history of this Vachana movement through the wives of Basavanna Gangambike

04:52:05.280 --> 04:52:10.480
[Guest]: and Nilambike it's a beautiful way of recently I was reading this Dheerendra Jha's book on

04:52:10.480 --> 04:52:16.160
[Guest]: assassin Gandhi's assassin and there I thought that why is it that nobody has explored that

04:52:16.160 --> 04:52:24.080
[Guest]: Manorama as a wonderful literary character now the girlfriend of that fellow the other

04:52:24.080 --> 04:52:29.920
[Guest]: fellow who gets hanged Godse's accomplice he has a girlfriend called Manorama she's

04:52:29.920 --> 04:52:36.600
[Guest]: a Christian girl and she also testifies later and nobody has exploited that character as

04:52:36.600 --> 04:52:42.200
[Guest]: a literary character so I mean I mean Gangambika and Nilambika that my father was working on

04:52:42.200 --> 04:52:48.240
[Guest]: I thought I mean adds great potential so but I never got to discuss all of this when he

04:52:48.240 --> 04:52:55.560
[Guest]: was around so he was his literary he was already an a kind of a star and we always responded

04:52:55.560 --> 04:53:00.800
[Guest]: to his public image of course he was a very kind father but later I think we can we became

04:53:00.800 --> 04:53:05.960
[Guest]: very conscious of his public stature I mean the road on which I live is named after him

04:53:05.960 --> 04:53:12.920
[Guest]: so it's ironically it's also the road where the BJP has its headquarters so you know in

04:53:12.920 --> 04:53:18.400
[Guest]: a lot of these things happen you know I mean I don't regret but I ask myself why is it

04:53:18.400 --> 04:53:23.520
[Guest]: that I never could come to speak of course he wrote a great poem called Chasana Alabandhu

04:53:23.520 --> 04:53:28.680
[Guest]: his collection is also called Chasana Alabandhu it was on the the coal collapse that happened

04:53:28.680 --> 04:53:35.280
[Guest]: in Bihar it was very empathetic and very I mean I really loved that poem and now when

04:53:35.280 --> 04:53:40.960
[Guest]: I look at it I feel he was such a sensitive writer and he should have written more but

04:53:40.960 --> 04:53:47.400
[Guest]: he spent all his time mentoring people and that is also there that sees I mean we always

04:53:47.400 --> 04:53:54.360
[Guest]: feel that he sort of spent a lot of time nurturing younger writers he published some 200 300

04:53:54.360 --> 04:53:58.280
[Guest]: volumes you know of young writers were all very big today and they all celebrate him

04:53:58.280 --> 04:54:03.640
[Guest]: and they all make him look bigger than me or obviously he is and I mean I am never sort

04:54:03.640 --> 04:54:09.960
[Guest]: of you know I mean put on par with him or made to look I mean as good or whatever but

04:54:09.960 --> 04:54:14.440
[Guest]: that's okay I can live with that in Canada because he is the star here you know I mean

04:54:14.440 --> 04:54:19.160
[Guest]: that is there but then but then I always feel that he was a better writer you know I mean

04:54:19.160 --> 04:54:24.880
[Guest]: probably should have written more and so I am trying to fulfill that thing I feel sometimes

04:54:24.880 --> 04:54:29.680
[Amit Varma]: in a personal sense not in a sense of achievements or writing do you sometimes look in the mirror

04:54:29.680 --> 04:54:39.840
[Guest]: and see him no I know I mean not in the mirror I suppose not in the mirror I am a completely

04:54:39.840 --> 04:54:48.600
[Guest]: different person I feel I carry a bit of my mother's grit my father was very humongously

04:54:48.600 --> 04:54:57.360
[Guest]: sensitive person and I am not as I feel I am not as sensitive as him or as empathetic

04:54:57.360 --> 04:55:04.080
[Guest]: as him or there's a lot to catch up I feel and he's a he's still a tower you know in

04:55:04.080 --> 04:55:09.680
[Guest]: towering figure for me and I think parents are always like that it's not just me when

04:55:09.680 --> 04:55:18.480
[Guest]: I probably am exaggerating so he is he's always that he was a fine moral you know that the

04:55:18.480 --> 04:55:24.520
[Guest]: moral core that he had you know I mean it's a it's a very remarkable achievement it's

04:55:24.520 --> 04:55:30.640
[Guest]: not his children or his writing or his status as a cultural literary patron of writing in

04:55:30.640 --> 04:55:35.960
[Guest]: Canada or whatever but I think his moral core was solid and he could empathize he could

04:55:35.960 --> 04:55:42.240
[Guest]: sort of allow people to come into his lives I am I am not that I don't think I am so much

04:55:42.240 --> 04:55:48.680
[Guest]: like him but I have huge admiration for him probably because I am not like him so that

04:55:48.680 --> 04:55:51.480
[Guest]: is that is there because.

04:55:51.480 --> 04:55:56.000
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of kind of final questions and I was struck by what you said your wife told

04:55:56.000 --> 04:55:59.440
[Amit Varma]: you that she married you because you were a writer not because you were an editor and

04:55:59.440 --> 04:56:04.180
[Amit Varma]: there's something in you know the way I'd interpret that is a writer is someone who

04:56:04.180 --> 04:56:08.920
[Amit Varma]: has a life of the imagination they have an interior life and earlier you spoke about

04:56:08.920 --> 04:56:13.520
[Amit Varma]: how your maternal grandmother loved to read and your mother loved to read and I was just

04:56:13.520 --> 04:56:18.240
[Amit Varma]: having this chat with a friend I met yesterday for breakfast where he was lamenting that

04:56:18.240 --> 04:56:22.480
[Amit Varma]: in the office where he works he can't have a conversation with anyone because everything

04:56:22.480 --> 04:56:26.760
[Amit Varma]: is restricted to what they do and the lane they're on and otherwise everything is beyond

04:56:26.760 --> 04:56:31.720
[Amit Varma]: that is like just banal and boring and they're not reading much they're not engaged in art

04:56:31.720 --> 04:56:37.440
[Amit Varma]: and all of that and clearly in your case you know within your family there is that engagement

04:56:37.440 --> 04:56:43.000
[Amit Varma]: and I can see why you know that's attractive that you have that interior life where you're

04:56:43.000 --> 04:56:48.120
[Amit Varma]: always so when you look around you and obviously your circles would be self-selected you would

04:56:48.120 --> 04:56:52.660
[Amit Varma]: hang out with people like you so they would all be reading books and all of that so do

04:56:52.660 --> 04:57:00.280
[Amit Varma]: you think in general that this is something that people miss out on do people like have

04:57:00.280 --> 04:57:06.520
[Amit Varma]: you ever kind of noticed this do you you know that does it strike you that in every generation

04:57:06.520 --> 04:57:10.880
[Amit Varma]: there must be the same standard fixed percentage of people who don't really engage with art

04:57:10.880 --> 04:57:16.280
[Amit Varma]: or books or whatever and it's the same all across time or do you think it's a greater

04:57:16.280 --> 04:57:21.680
[Amit Varma]: or smaller worry now you know do you look at people and say oh okay there's no sort

04:57:21.680 --> 04:57:25.720
[Amit Varma]: of you know other in rich interior life going on?

04:57:25.720 --> 04:57:32.000
[Guest]: No I think people have you know I mean there is a larger people coming into the pool I

04:57:32.000 --> 04:57:39.320
[Guest]: mean I don't feel cynical about that at all because I think from our times to now technology

04:57:39.320 --> 04:57:43.600
[Guest]: has facilitated a lot of things you know there's whether willy-nilly you know something comes

04:57:43.600 --> 04:57:49.080
[Guest]: your way and see even a Netflix or a movie that you watch or whatever you know pushes

04:57:49.080 --> 04:57:55.300
[Guest]: you into a different kind of stream and you know you're not robots not to sort of recognize

04:57:55.300 --> 04:58:01.000
[Guest]: that so you start living a different kind of a thing and I think technology also facilitates

04:58:01.000 --> 04:58:06.680
[Guest]: a lot of other lives that you can lead so I'm not very sure whether it's all for the

04:58:06.680 --> 04:58:15.040
[Guest]: good of bad or whatever but then people I always have felt lead several lives and you

04:58:15.040 --> 04:58:19.400
[Guest]: know I mean I mean I don't know if it was Graham Greene or somebody else who said that

04:58:19.400 --> 04:58:25.280
[Guest]: you know I mean I mean I think Marquess who spoke about there are always there's always

04:58:25.280 --> 04:58:32.520
[Guest]: a secret life that a person leads so I mean I think people lead different kinds of lives

04:58:32.520 --> 04:58:39.520
[Guest]: but whether it whether it has a literary or a cultural kind of accent on it is a question

04:58:39.520 --> 04:58:45.080
[Guest]: to be asked because what we are surrounded today is not just books, books have started

04:58:45.080 --> 04:58:53.120
[Guest]: coming in different forms it could be OTT shows platforms and you know movies and podcasts

04:58:53.120 --> 04:58:58.920
[Guest]: and radio and a lot of different things have suddenly started coming up you know I mean

04:58:58.920 --> 04:59:03.600
[Guest]: I didn't even know that my son listened to so many interesting podcasts I took a lot

04:59:03.600 --> 04:59:07.120
[Guest]: of recommendations from him you know I mean he was saying you're listening to the same

04:59:07.120 --> 04:59:14.400
[Guest]: boring stuff why don't you listen to this thank you son for so you know I mean I mean

04:59:14.400 --> 04:59:19.260
[Guest]: then I realized that he listens to that because he wants to keep a certain kind of mental

04:59:19.260 --> 04:59:23.640
[Guest]: balance when he is interacting with us so there are new things that they pick up and

04:59:23.640 --> 04:59:28.280
[Guest]: there are new things out there which people consume in ways that we don't understand as

04:59:28.280 --> 04:59:33.280
[Guest]: yet or I am probably very limiting and I mean I don't understand that as yet so but there

04:59:33.280 --> 04:59:39.400
[Guest]: are I mean there are lots of interesting things happening below this surface and suddenly

04:59:39.400 --> 04:59:44.720
[Guest]: you may have a writer here and a writer there and a filmmaker there and a documentary filmmaker

04:59:44.720 --> 04:59:49.040
[Guest]: there who may just want to give up his mainstream profession and pursue that and we see that

04:59:49.040 --> 04:59:53.880
[Guest]: a lot you know I mean in Bangalore and Karnataka especially where the software things sort

04:59:53.880 --> 04:59:59.400
[Guest]: of jades you so quickly I at least know half a dozen people who have given up their software

04:59:59.400 --> 05:00:08.640
[Guest]: jobs and I mean and I've taken up either filmmaking or writing or in one case who's now a very

05:00:08.640 --> 05:00:17.120
[Guest]: controversial subject has even become a historian so people find different avenues to sort of

05:00:17.120 --> 05:00:21.760
[Guest]: so I don't I'm not very cynical about that I think from our earlier generation to now

05:00:21.760 --> 05:00:28.400
[Guest]: our generation to later I think the whole thing is sort of opening up but what it how

05:00:28.400 --> 05:00:32.600
[Guest]: it sort of you know shapes you or whether it's the same kind of inner life you know

05:00:32.600 --> 05:00:37.000
[Guest]: I mean your understanding of inner life was also very limited it was inner life always

05:00:37.000 --> 05:00:42.960
[Guest]: meant a very spiritual thing but now that spiritual thing has a lot of other wings attached

05:00:42.960 --> 05:00:49.960
[Guest]: to it so it could it could mean you could acquire your spiritual thing through some

05:00:49.960 --> 05:00:54.320
[Guest]: godman or and that godman puts you on to something else and something else and something else

05:00:54.320 --> 05:00:59.560
[Guest]: and so it creates its own kind of world and cosmos and whatever so it's a very complicated

05:00:59.560 --> 05:01:02.880
[Guest]: question that you asked and you threw me out of gear.

05:01:02.880 --> 05:01:06.680
[Amit Varma]: I like what you said about you know people have several lives so before I go to my last

05:01:06.680 --> 05:01:11.060
[Amit Varma]: question I'll read out a poem I love which kind of is on that theme and it's called Harmony

05:01:11.060 --> 05:01:13.800
[Amit Varma]: in the Boudoir by Mark Strand.

05:01:13.800 --> 05:01:17.360
[Amit Varma]: After years of marriage he stands at the foot of the bed and tells his wife that she will

05:01:17.360 --> 05:01:21.800
[Amit Varma]: never know him that for everything he says there is more that he does not say that behind

05:01:21.800 --> 05:01:26.280
[Amit Varma]: each word he utters there is another word and hundreds more behind that one all those

05:01:26.280 --> 05:01:31.280
[Amit Varma]: unsaid words he says contain his true self which has been betrayed by the superficial

05:01:31.280 --> 05:01:32.680
[Amit Varma]: self before him.

05:01:32.680 --> 05:01:36.920
[Amit Varma]: So you see he says kicking off his slippers I am more than what I have led you to believe

05:01:36.920 --> 05:01:42.700
[Amit Varma]: I am oh you silly man says his wife of course you are I find that just thinking of you having

05:01:42.700 --> 05:01:47.800
[Amit Varma]: so many selves receding into nothingness is very exciting that you barely exist as you

05:01:47.800 --> 05:01:51.280
[Amit Varma]: are couldn't please me more.

05:01:51.280 --> 05:01:58.560
[Amit Varma]: So my final question is that I'd love you to share with me and my listeners books music

05:01:58.560 --> 05:02:03.520
[Amit Varma]: films anything at all that you absolutely love so you know it could be something you

05:02:03.520 --> 05:02:08.160
[Amit Varma]: read recently it could be an old favorite you always held close to your heart it could

05:02:08.160 --> 05:02:15.840
[Guest]: be any of these three or all of these three that would mean I get a little confused because

05:02:15.840 --> 05:02:21.840
[Guest]: a lot of things that I like from a very early time for very personal reasons I have always

05:02:21.840 --> 05:02:29.160
[Guest]: loved to reread Of Human Bondage by Somsit Maum I like the character there and I've identified

05:02:29.160 --> 05:02:37.080
[Guest]: myself with that character many times in crisis and so that is from a very from a real past

05:02:37.080 --> 05:02:42.240
[Guest]: and then there's another book for very strange reasons you know I mean taught me how to think

05:02:42.240 --> 05:02:47.160
[Guest]: and taught me how to look at explore an idea differently which was called Man's Worldly

05:02:47.160 --> 05:02:52.600
[Guest]: Goods by Leo Huberman and Paul Sweezy it was a economic history of the world I mean of

05:02:52.600 --> 05:02:56.360
[Guest]: course they were Marxist but of course the fact that they were Marxist was not important

05:02:56.360 --> 05:03:01.080
[Guest]: it was the narrative that they built which later on a lot of non-fiction that was published

05:03:01.080 --> 05:03:06.800
[Guest]: in the West you know explored and you have now a lot of good range of non-fiction writing

05:03:06.800 --> 05:03:11.720
[Guest]: which you read on specialist subjects so this was one of the very early books which sort

05:03:11.720 --> 05:03:17.040
[Guest]: of you know caught on and I read a lot of a good economic books after that I mean so

05:03:17.040 --> 05:03:23.400
[Guest]: that is that is something there and then of course my all-time autobiography favorite

05:03:23.400 --> 05:03:31.080
[Guest]: is Bertrand Russell the three volumes in Bantam Press paperback that I still preserve at home

05:03:31.080 --> 05:03:36.960
[Guest]: I read that and that I read that very early in my teens and I was very absolutely shocked

05:03:36.960 --> 05:03:41.760
[Guest]: when he spoke about his sexual life and things like that so so and then of course the chapter

05:03:41.760 --> 05:03:47.440
[Guest]: on mathematics and all that was intriguing and how could somebody be so many things was

05:03:47.440 --> 05:03:53.760
[Guest]: some first time that came before me was at that time and of course my Kannada writers

05:03:53.760 --> 05:03:59.960
[Guest]: of course K.S. Narasimhaswamy was very personal to me when I was very romantic and young and

05:03:59.960 --> 05:04:04.840
[Guest]: thought that every other girl that I meet may fall in love with me so he was he created

05:04:04.840 --> 05:04:12.680
[Guest]: that kind of connubial bliss and a world that he constructed was so fantastic and his metaphors

05:04:12.680 --> 05:04:18.080
[Guest]: and his images were even to this day you know I mean sort of they don't escape you so he

05:04:18.080 --> 05:04:22.760
[Guest]: was there and then Kopal Krishna Adiga tried to rationalize a lot of things for me so he

05:04:22.760 --> 05:04:26.920
[Guest]: tried to bring in history into his poetry he tried to bring in ideas into his poems

05:04:26.920 --> 05:04:32.440
[Guest]: and he sort of ridiculed the idea of writing on love and family the way the other man was

05:04:32.440 --> 05:04:41.560
[Guest]: writing so that was there and so there is Narasimhaswamy, there is Adiga and then of

05:04:41.560 --> 05:04:47.000
[Guest]: course there is Kuvempu, Kuvempu's prose you know I mean I don't like his poetry to be

05:04:47.000 --> 05:04:51.880
[Guest]: honest he's very sort of you know I mean I mean I feel he's very artificial of course

05:04:51.880 --> 05:04:56.920
[Guest]: there are some great poems too but then I love him for his prose and I love him for

05:04:56.920 --> 05:05:04.000
[Guest]: his novels so he was great and he was he was he again you know I mean what fascinates me

05:05:04.000 --> 05:05:10.800
[Guest]: was he or Lankesh never left the corner of their room but they imagined their world sitting

05:05:10.800 --> 05:05:14.800
